{[%evp 0,61,24,23,23,15,20,20,22,-26,7,-14,3,-4,-6,-6,-6,-2,9,-6,36,-34,18,-25,
-15,-48,-39,-65,-34,-61,-35,-49,-50,-50,-36,-52,-62,-61,-69,-69,-9,-10,-4,5,28,
17,81,152,72,83,198,162,162,162,939,216,691,772,29993,29992,29997,29998,29999,
-30000]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 ({Our traditional move order is} 
4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 {when we transpose to the game.})
4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 $1 {The inclusion of the early ...Nc6 is a
very important part of Black's strategy. By putting pressure on d4, we prevent
White from achieving his best attacking construction - e2-e4 followed by Bd3
and Ne2.} ({Let's take a look at what might happen if Black allows the
construction Bd3 and Ne2.} 6... d6 7. e4 O-O $6 {This move is already dubious.}
({Black could have still played the correct} 7... Nc6) 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Ne2 {
This is what White wants to achieve in the Saemisch System. After castling, he
can already start pushing his kingside pawns. The following game is quite
illustrative.} e5 10. d5 Na5 11. Bg5 $1 {This pin is particularly annoying
when Black has already castled. Now, it will be difficult for him to avoid the
creation of kingside weaknesses.} h6 12. Bh4 b6 13. g4 {Since the centre is
closed, White can start his kingside play. The kingside attack is so strong
that White typically sacrifices the c4-pawn.} Ba6 14. Ra2 {This is a typical
idea in the Saemisch Variation. White often brings the a1-rook to the kingside
via the second rank.} g6 {The idea of this move is to take the f5-square away
from the White knight. The move ...g7-g6, however, seriously weakens the
kingside.} ({Taking the pawn with} 14... Bxc4 {does not help either. White can
follow with} 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5,Ga2g2,Gg4g5] The kingside
attack is tremendously strong. White is ready to proceed with Nf5 followed by
Rg2 and g4-g5.} g6 ({In case of} 16... g5 17. Bxg5 hxg5 18. h4 $18 {[%cal
Ga2h2,Gg3f5] White has a winning attack.}) 17. Qc1 Kh7 18. f4 $40 {After
opening up the f-file, White is going to exploit the pin along the diagonal
h4-d8.}) {This position was reached in the game Ernst, S - Burovic, R, 2022.
At this point, the simplest would have been} 15. O-O Bxc4 16. Bxc4 Nxc4 17. Qd3
Na5 18. c4 $16 {When White is strategically winning. Black's extra pawn is
absolutely meaningless in the middlegame. At the same time, White has all the
time in the world to prepare the advance f3-f4.}) 7. e4 d6 {This is the first
critical opening position that we are going to study. Given the pressure on d4,
White cannot achieve his perfect construction (Bd3+Ne2) without accepting some
sort of concession. In the first couple of examples, we will examine the
setups with Be3.} 8. Be3 {By protecting the d4-pawn, White prepares Bd3
followed by Ne2. On the downside, however, the e3-bishop is a bit passive and
often vulnerable.} b6 {A very important move. Black not only protects the
c5-pawn but also prepares his main positional idea in this variation - putting
pressure on c4 by means of ...Na5 followed by ...Ba6.} 9. Bd3 Na5 ({Starting
with} 9... Ba6 $4 {would be a blunder since after} 10. Qa4 Qc8 11. d5 $18 {
Black is losing a piece.}) 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. Ng3 {For the time being, White is
tactically protecting the c4-pawn. At the same time, he is already planning to
develop a kingside activity by means of 0-0 followed by f3-f4.} Qc7 {I quite
like this typical move. Black indirectly increases the pressure on c4. Now,
White should reckon with the threat of ...cxd4 followed by ...Bxc4. That's why
he played} 12. d5 $6 {this move is dubious in view of Black's reaction.} ({
More in the spirit of the variation would have been to sacrifice the c4-pawn
by playing} 12. O-O O-O 13. f4 Bxc4 14. f5 {This is a typical scenario in the
Saemisch Variation. White sacrifices the c4-pawn and goes all-in on the
kingside. The precise way of handling White's kingside initiative is} cxd4 15.
cxd4 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qc4 17. Qd1 {[%cal Ge3g5] White is planning to develop a
dangerous initiative by playing Bg5 on the next move. Therefore, Black should
play} h6 $1 $15 {when White's compensation for the pawn is not that obvious.})
12... Nd7 $1 {Remember this typical idea against d4-d5. Black not only
threatens to win the pawn but is also planning to follow with ...Ne5.} 13. O-O
Ne5 14. Be2 Nexc4 15. Bf4 e5 {In my opinion, Black should have kept the
control of the f5-square as long as possible.} ({Better option would have been
} 15... O-O-O $17 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5] We will see, that in these structures
with doubled pawns, the black king is often quite safe on the queenside. Now,
Black is the one who can consider playing on the kingside. If given the chance,
he is ready to proceed with ...h7-h6 followed by ...g7-g5.}) 16. Bc1 O-O $2 {
This is a huge positional mistake. White's kingside attack is now very
dangerous. He can follow with Bd3 and Ra2-f2. Later on, the break f3-f4 will
be very dangerous. Eventually, White managed to win the game.} 17. Bd3 b5 18.
Ra2 Rab8 19. f4 b4 20. axb4 cxb4 21. cxb4 Rxb4 22. fxe5 Qb6+ 23. Kh1 dxe5 24.
Nf5 Bc8 25. Ne7+ Kh8 26. Qh5 Qc5 27. Bg5 Rb2 28. Rxf7 Re8 29. Rxg7 Bf5 30.
Rxh7+ Bxh7 31. Bf6# 1-0

