{[%evp 0,82,26,19,26,6,6,6,31,-33,-4,-3,-3,-2,9,-6,-6,-13,-6,22,25,-23,-6,-35,
-35,-69,-71,-109,-107,-103,-65,-56,-56,-81,-73,-65,7,-85,-108,-119,-78,-152,
-217,-202,-201,-182,-152,-156,-152,-167,-158,-159,-161,-163,-146,-154,-116,
-104,-110,-98,-102,-173,-167,-191,-191,-181,-176,-188,-188,-204,-203,-196,-196,
-321,-321,-344,-360,-381,-364,-418,-428,-439,-455,-484,-484] In this example,
we briefly examine another case where White sacrifices the c4-pawn in order to
develop a kingside attack. We will see that Black's counterplay is usually
more than enough.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 ({Once again, I would
like to remind you that our move order is} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7.
e4 d6 {when we reach the critical opening position.}) 4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6.
bxc3 Nc6 $1 {We should never forget this important move. Putting pressure on
d4 is essential!} 7. e4 d6 8. Be3 b6 9. Bd3 Na5 10. Ne2 Ba6 11. Ng3 O-O {
This is also a playable continuation. Black is immediately threatening to take
on c4.} ({Obviously, Black could have played} 11... Qc7 {by analogy with the
previous example.}) 12. O-O Bxc4 13. f4 {This is White's idea. He is ready to
follow with the typical attacking move f4-f5. In this particular position,
however, Black can make use of the vulnerable e3-bishop.} cxd4 {This move is
enough for an advantage.} ({Even more precise, however, would have been} 13...
Bxd3 14. Qxd3 d5 15. e5 Ng4 {[%cal Gd8h4] We can now see the vulnerability of
the bishop. Additionally, Black is winning an important tempo in view of the
threat of ...Qh4 on the next move.} 16. Bd2 Nb3 17. Ra2 f5 $17 {A typical
device designed to eliminate White's space advantage on the kingside. White
does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 14. cxd4 d5 15. e5 Ne4 {Black
wants to neutralize White's initiative by simplifying the position.} ({The idea
} 15... Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Ng4 {does not work in the same way as with pawns on c3
and c5. The problem is that after} 17. Bd2 {Black does not have ..Nb3 followed
by ...c5-c4. Nevertheless, Black is not worse at all. An interesting follow-up
would be} Qh4 18. h3 Ne3 $1 19. Qxe3 Nc4 20. Qf2 Nxd2 21. Qxd2 Qxg3 22. f5 f6 {
The most precise continuation. We shouldn't allow the advance f5-f6. After} 23.
Rf3 Qg5 24. Qxg5 fxg5 25. Raf1 $11 {the endgame is equal.}) 16. f5 Nxg3 17.
hxg3 f6 18. g4 $2 {This move is way too slow.} ({White should have settled for
the energetic} 18. fxe6 Qe7 19. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4] when one of the possible
lines is} Nc6 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. d5 Qc5+ 22. Kh2 Qxd5 23. exf6 Qxe6 24. fxg7
Rxf1 25. Qxf1 $13 {The position is unclear with chances for both sides.}) 18...
fxe5 19. dxe5 Qe7 $17 {Black indirectly targets the e5-pawn. It's clear that
White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.} 20. Qc2 exf5 21. gxf5
Qxe5 22. Rae1 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 Qe4 24. Qxe4 dxe4 25. Bd2 Rae8 26. Bxa5 bxa5 27.
Rf4 Re5 28. Rexe4 Rxe4 29. Rxe4 Rxf5 30. Re7 Rf4 31. Kh2 Ra4 32. Re3 Kf7 33.
Kh3 Kf6 34. g4 g6 35. Kg3 Rc4 36. Rf3+ Kg5 37. Rf7 Rxg4+ 38. Kf3 h5 39. Rxa7
Ra4 40. Kg2 Rxa3 41. Ra6 Kf5 0-1

