{[%evp 0,78,31,23,23,6,6,20,23,-45,-14,-14,-4,-4,17,-6,-6,-4,9,22,27,5,9,17,47,
61,39,30,30,-43,-28,-128,-94,-110,-53,-72,-6,-120,-21,-28,-28,-43,-13,-11,58,
20,71,109,143,62,59,58,77,77,65,43,44,34,38,39,43,35,74,62,75,16,35,-5,-2,0,0,
-45,1,14,8,14,14,9,14,-12,14] In this example, we shall see how to play when
White develops his knight via h3.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 ({
The Saemisch move order is} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 {
entering the main position.}) 4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 {Even though this
move is completely possible, I would have played the immediate 6...Nc6.} 7. e4
Nc6 {This is the last moment to play ...Nc6. Otherwise, White would achieve
the construction Bd3 + Ne2.} 8. Be3 b6 9. Bd3 Na5 10. Nh3 {The idea of this
move is to follow with Nf2. Later on, the f2-knight will be supporting the
advance of the kingside pawns. Sometimes, White can also play e4-e5 followed
by the active Ng5. The drawback of this move is that Black can immediately
target the knight by means of ...e6-e5. In the game, Black played} Ba6 $6 {
which is imprecise.} ({The typical reaction to Nh3 is} 10... e5 $1 {
immediately creating the threat of ...Bxh3. A possible follow-up would be} 11.
Nf2 Ba6 12. O-O Nd7 $1 {Again we see this typical multi-purpose move. First of
all, Black is immediately threatening to win the c4-pawn by playing ...Bxc4 on
the next move. Additionally, after eventual exchanges on d4, the knight will
utilize the important squares e5 and c5.} 13. Qa4 cxd4 14. cxd4 O-O 15. Rac1
exd4 16. Bxd4 Rc8 $15 {Black is already slightly better in view of the
vulnerable c4-pawn. Depending on White's reaction, he is ready to follow with
either ...Ne5 or ...Nc5.}) 11. Qe2 Qd7 12. e5 dxe5 13. dxe5 Ng8 14. Ng5 $6 {
This active move is a serious inaccuracy.} (14. O-O Qa4 15. Bg5 {[%cal Gf3f4,
Gf4f5] White would have enjoyed fantastic compensation for the c4-pawn that
will be lost anyway. The advance f3-f4-f5 is very difficult to deal with.})
14... Rd8 15. Bc2 Bxc4 $17 {Now, White does not have any compensation for the
pawn.} 16. Qf2 Ne7 17. Ne4 Qc7 18. Bf4 Ng6 19. Nd6+ Kf8 20. Bg3 Ba6 21. O-O-O
c4 22. f4 Qc5 23. Qxc5 bxc5 24. Nxc4 Rxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Bxc4 26. Bxg6 Nb3+ 27. Kb2
Ke7 28. Bh4+ f6 29. Be4 Rb8 30. Kc2 Bb5 31. Re1 c4 32. f5 Nc5 33. exf6+ gxf6
34. fxe6 Ba4+ 35. Kc1 Nb3+ 36. Kb2 Nd2+ 37. Kc1 Nb3+ 38. Kb2 Nc5+ 39. Kc1 Nb3+
1/2-1/2

