-792,-834,-1210,-1457,-2763,-2863,-29989,-29990,-29991,-29992,-29997,-29998,
-29999,-30000] As we have seen, the setups with Be3 can hardly pose Black any
problems. Therefore, in the next couple of examples, we shall pay attention to
the setups with Bg5. The first game shows what happens if White plays Bg5 as
early as move 8.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 ({The traditional move
order is} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6) 4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6.
bxc3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 8. Bg5 {This move order is a bit premature because White
neglects the development. Therefore, you can rarely see this move on a GM
level.} h6 $1 {A common theme in Nimzo-Indian Defence is to answer Bg5 with ...
h7-h6. Black's usual idea is to clarify the position of the bishop.} 9. Bh4 {
From the h4-square, the bishop does not have an influence on the queenside
actions. Therefore, Black's most logical continuation is} Qa5 {[%cal Ga5c3,
Gc5d4] when it turns out that White cannot avoid losing a pawn.} 10. Qd2 cxd4
11. Ne2 dxc3 12. Qxd6 $2 {This mistake is actually leading to a lost position.}
({Obviously, White should have played} 12. Nxc3 {when} e5 {[%cal Gc6d4] is a
very important move. Black opens the bishop and is planning to follow with ...
Nd4. The critical line is} 13. Nd5 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Na5 $15 {
when White still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Bd7 {
Even though this move does not spoil the advantage, Black could have won on
the spot.} ({Computer's suggestion is} 12... e5 $1 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qxf6 c2+
15. Kf2 Qb6+ 16. Ke1 Qb1+ 17. Kf2 Rg8 $19 {when White can resign.}) 13. Qd3 Ne5
14. Qxc3 Nxc4 15. Qxa5 Nxa5 $17 {Obviously, White's compensation for the pawn
is not enough. Later on, Black managed to win this game.} 16. Rc1 O-O 17. Nd4
Rac8 18. Kd2 e5 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Nf5 Nb3+ 21. Ke1 Rc1+ 22. Kf2 Bxf5 23. exf5
Nd5 24. g4 Nd4 25. Kg3 Nf4 26. h3 f6 27. a4 Kf8 28. a5 Ke7 29. Bg2 Rc2 30. Bf1
Kd6 31. a6 bxa6 32. Rg1 Nde2+ 33. Bxe2 Nxe2+ 34. Kf2 Nxg1+ 35. Kxg1 a5 36. Bf2
a4 37. Bxa7 a3 38. Bb8+ Kd5 39. Ba7 a2 40. Be3 a1=Q+ 41. Bc1 Qxc1# 0-1

