0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0] In this game, White played 9.Bg5 only after the preparatory 8.
Ne2. Even though this setup is more challenging, Black does not have problems
if he knows what he is doing.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5.
bxc3 c5 6. f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 8. Ne2 {White stabilizes the centre and is ready to
develop the c1-bishop to the active g5-square. The drawback of this idea is
the delay of the kingside development.} b6 {Black immediately starts his
typical play against the c4-pawn.} 9. Bg5 {The most principled continuation.} (
{In one of his games, the big Saemisch expert Salem, A played} 9. Ng3 O-O 10.
Be3 {which is logical as well. It appears, however, that Black gains valuable
time to put pressure on c4.} ({It's also possible to start with} 10. Bg5 {
Although, after} h6 11. Be3 Ba6 {it's not clear whether White can profit from
the inclusion of the move ...h7-h6. Let's take a look at one correspondence
game -} 12. Bd3 Na5 13. Qe2 {In this structure, White often protects the
c4-pawn by means of Bd3 and Qe2. If Black cannot increase the pressure on c4,
he should consider opening the c-file by means of ...cxd4. This is exactly
what happened in the current game -} cxd4 14. cxd4 Rc8 15. Rc1 Qc7 $1 {Black
is putting maximum pressure on c4 and White is forced to go for} 16. c5 {
It's important to understand that after} Bxd3 17. Qxd3 dxc5 18. dxc5 Rfd8 19.
Qe2 Qb7 {Only Black can be slightly better because of his better control of
the light squares. While both black knights can control the light squares,
White is able to control them with only one minor piece.} 20. Rb1 Nd7 21. cxb6
Nc4 22. O-O Ndxb6 $15 {Black was already slightly better in the game 0-1 (47)
Teverovski,B (1800)-Tenev,T (2348) ICCF email 2008}) 10... Ba6 11. Bd3 Na5 12.
Qe2 cxd4 13. cxd4 Rc8 14. Rc1 {This position was reached in the game 0-1 (57)
Salem, A (2690)-Yuffa, D (2567) Warsaw 2021. At this point, Black's simplest
solution would have been} Qc7 $1 {Just like in the correspondence game that
was examined above.} 15. c5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 dxc5 17. dxc5 Rfd8 $15 {Black is
already fighting for the advantage.}) 9... h6 {Never forget to clarify the
position of this bishop!} 10. Bh4 Na5 {Black should immediately start his play
against the c4-pawn. With his last move, he forces the white knight into the
passive c1-square.} 11. Nc1 {[%cal Gc1b3]} ({Since we have clarified the
position of the h4-bishop with the move ...h7-h6, White cannot even consider} 
11. Ng3 $4 {when after} g5 $19 {Black is winning a piece.}) 11... Bd7 $1 {
This is a very important prophylactic move. White was planning to proceed with
Nb3, thus solving the problem with the c4-pawn. Now, Nb3 is impossible in view
of ...Ba4.} ({The thematic} 11... Ba6 $6 {is already dubious since White can
follow with} 12. Nb3 $1 {It turns out that taking the c4-pawn is a bit
dangerous.} Bxc4 {This move marks the beginning of a forced sequence.} ({After
} 12... Nxc4 $2 13. Nd2 $1 Nxd2 14. Bxa6 $18 {[%csl Rd2] Black is losing on
the spot. The d2-knight does not have squares.}) 13. Nxa5 Bxf1 14. Rxf1 bxa5
15. dxc5 dxc5 16. Qxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rb1 $14 {Black still needs to work hard in
order to make a draw in this endgame.}) 12. Bd3 ({White could have prepared
Nb3 with} 12. a4 {In this case, Black's most reasonable continuation seems to
be} Qc7 {increasing the pressure on c4 and getting rid of the pin.} 13. Nb3 ({
It's important to point out that} 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. d5 {is well met by} f5 $1
15. exf5 exf5 {[%cal Gc7d8,Gd8f6,Ge8c8] when Black has decent counterplay. He
can consider transferring the queen to f6 and castling long.}) 13... Nxb3 14.
Qxb3 Nh5 $132 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gg7g5] Black does not have any problems in this
structure. He is ready to follow with ...g7-g5 and ...e6-e5. Putting the pawns
on dark-squares after parting with the dark-squared bishop fits very well into
the spirit of the Nimzo-Indian Defence. In this specific position, White's
bishop pair is not effective at all.}) 12... e5 13. O-O g5 {This move is
almost always positionally justified when Black hasn't played ...0-0. Besides
gaining kingside space, with his last move, Black also prevents the advance
f3-f4. Usually, a logical follow-up after ...g7-g5 is to establish a knight on
f4.} 14. Bg3 Nh5 15. Ne2 Nf4 16. Bf2 Nxd3 {In my opinion, this exchange is a
bit premature.} ({I would have preferred} 16... Qe7 $1 17. Ng3 f6 {[%cal Ge8c8,
Gh6h5,Gh5h4] Black is ready to proceed with ...0-0-0 followed by the advance
of the h-pawn. Actually, the d3-bishop is pretty useless now.}) 17. Qxd3 Ba4
18. Rfb1 Bb3 {This is the point behind the move 16...Nxd3. Even though Black
is going to win the c4-pawn, White will get access to the important f5-square.
After} 19. Ng3 Bxc4 20. Qc2 Qc7 21. Nf5 $44 {White managed to obtain enough
compensation for the pawn.} Be6 22. Ng7+ Ke7 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. d5 exd5 25. exd5
c4 26. f4 gxf4 27. Qf5 Ke8 28. Qg6+ Kf8 29. g3 Qd7 30. Kh1 Rg8 31. Qxh6+ Ke8
32. Rg1 Qf5 33. Qxd6 Rd8 34. Qh6 Qe4+ 35. Rg2 Qxd5 36. Re1 Kd7 37. Qh7+ Kd6 38.
Qxa7 Nc6 39. Qh7 f3 40. Rgg1 Rh8 41. Qg6+ Qe6 42. Rd1+ Ke7 43. Qg7+ Qf7 44.
