{[%evp 0,22,31,14,14,0,0,7,33,-1,-13,-13,22,-9,12,9,34,-55,6,13,-3,-41,-31,-31,
11] Now, let's briefly discuss how to play when White decides to quickly close
the centre with d4-d5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6.
f3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 8. d5 {I expect this move to become very popular in the future.
It was recommended by GM Abhijeet Gupta in his Modern Chess database Saemisch
Variation against Nimzo-Indian Defence and also by GM Ivan Sokolov in his
Chessable course Take Down the Nimzo-Indian. What is aiming for a static
position where he will have plenty of time to prepare and develop his kingside
play. He is always ready to sacrifice the c4-pawn. Black should handle the
arising positions very precisely.} Na5 9. Bd3 {Another bonus of the move d4-d5
is that White can now achieve the optimal attacking construction Bd3 + Ne2.} b6
10. Ne2 {The only sensible continuation.} ({The Benoni type of structure
arising after} 10. f4 exd5 11. cxd5 {is clearly in Black's favour. We can use
White's overextended position by means of} c4 12. Bb1 Nb3 13. Ra2 O-O $17 {
[%cal Gf8e8,Gb3c5] with ...Nc5 and ...Re8 to follow. White's centre is going
to collapse.}) ({Since Black hasn't committed to ...0-0, the move} 10. Bg5 {
is well met by} h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bf2 Qe7 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ge8c8] Black is
planning to proceed with ...Ba6 followed by ...0-0-0. In positions with a
bishop on a6, I would suggest against the advance ...e6-e5 for two reasons: 1)
White can transfer his knight to f5 2) Black can make use of the typical
manoeuvre...Nd7-e5} 13. Ne2 Ba6 $17 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gf6d7,Gd7e5] Black has a huge
advantage. He is ready to follow with the manoeuvre...Nd7-e5. At the same time,
in this structure, the king is pretty safe on the queenside.}) 10... Ba6 11.
O-O Qe7 $1 {Once again, this is the most precise move. Black is ready to
castle long and start playing on the kingside. The manoeuvre...Nd7-e5 is
always an option. A possible follow-up would be} 12. Ng3 O-O-O 13. Qe2 Nd7 $1 {
[%cal Gd7e5] Once again, Black makes use of this thematic idea. White should
now reckon with ...Ne5 on the next move.} 14. f4 g6 {Not only taking the
f5-square from the knight but also preparing the advance ...h7-h5-h4.} 15. Be3
h5 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf7f5] Even though the position remains complicated, I
would take Black. One of the possible ideas is to undermine White's
overextended centre by means of ...h5-h4 followed by ...f7-f5.} *

