{[%evp 0,88,16,28,27,-16,-9,4,4,23,26,-3,-3,-3,-14,-3,7,3,17,23,32,26,58,59,80,
-53,-6,-53,5,-24,-17,-17,-24,-59,-32,-32,-31,-118,-140,-165,-141,-141,-78,-78,
-129,-146,-143,-179,-179,-205,-179,-205,-196,-209,-199,-231,-208,-277,-286,
-308,-293,-291,-300,-324,-317,-506,-505,-578,-452,-533,-280,-457,-482,-509,
-488,-534,-513,-661,-664,-637,-591,-586,-658,-654,-660,-666,-670,-670,-663,
-671,-552] After studying the plans based on f2-f3 followed by e2-e4, now we
shall take a look at the seemingly less active 6.e3. As we will see, however,
White's ideas in this line shouldn't be underestimated. Black should be very
precise with the move order.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 ({The usual
move order is} 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2] As we have
seen, after the active f2-f3 followed by e2-e4, White cannot achieve his
perfect attacking construction because Black immediately starts putting
pressure on d4. The idea of 6.e3 is to overprotect the d4-pawn and proceed
with Bd3 followed by Ne2.  At this point, Black's most precise move order is}
b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 $1 {Besides provoking f2-f3 (it's no longer possible for White
to play f2-f4 in one move), Black takes the important e4-square under control.
Later in the game, we will see the importance of this control.}) 4... O-O 5. a3
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {Since White didn't play Nf3, he wants to build a strong centre
by means of Bd3 and Ne2 followed by e3-e4 and f2-f4.} b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 c5 {
Finally, we have transposed to the position that was examined via the move
order starting with 4.a3 (see above).} 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. e4 {We have arrived at
the first critical position for this setup. With his last move, White prepares
the annoying Bg5. The pin would be very dangerous for Black. That's why,
whenever White is ready to play Bg5, you should go for the thematic} Ne8 $1 11.
O-O Na5 {Now, Black starts his thematic play against the c4-pawn. The pressure
can be increased with different moves such as ...Rc8, ...Ba6, or even ...Nd6.}
12. f4 {This is the second critical position. Pushing the f-pawn all the way
to f6 is one of the most thematic attacking ideas. That's why, in response to .
..f3-f4, Black should immediately play.} (12. e5 $6 d6 13. f4 f5 14. exf6 Nxf6
15. f5 e5 $15) 12... f5 {Remember this move. Black fixes the f4-pawn and
restricts all the white minor pieces. The f5-pawn restricts the d3-bishop and
the knight while the f4-pawn restricts the dark-squared bishop and the knight.
We can now see the point behind the move ...Bb7. Now, White should decide how
to handle the pressure on e4.} 13. Ng3 Nd6 {Protecting f5 and attacking the
c4-pawn. White is now forced to release the central tension. A very
instructive position arises after} 14. exf5 exf5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rb1 Qc7 17.
Re1 g6 {The point of Black's previous play. Black has no way to activate his
minor pieces. Additionally, the c4-pawn is doomed. Black has a winning
advantage that Eljanov managed to convert.} 18. Bf1 Rae8 19. Be3 Ndxc4 20. Bf2
Rxe1 21. Qxe1 d6 22. Qd1 Qf7 23. a4 Bc6 24. Ne2 Qd7 25. h4 Bxa4 26. Qd3 Bc6 27.
Ra1 Be4 28. Qg3 Nb3 29. Rd1 Nbd2 30. Qg5 Qg7 31. Ra1 Nxf1 32. Kxf1 Bd3 33. Rd1
Qxc3 34. Qe7 Qf6 35. Qxa7 Qb2 36. Rxd3 Qb1+ 37. Be1 Qxd3 38. Bc3 Ne3+ 39. Kg1
Qd1+ 40. Kh2 Ng4+ 41. Kh3 Nf2+ 42. Kg3 Ne4+ 43. Kh2 Nxc3 44. Nxc3 Qd4 0-1

