{[%evp 0,64,21,11,11,6,6,2,31,28,27,15,15,15,15,18,23,16,23,23,23,23,47,43,43,
-48,-15,-15,-42,-39,-39,-37,-37,-48,-61,-58,-43,-33,-26,-37,-74,-78,-87,-95,
-54,-54,-71,-66,-25,-155,-147,-132,-194,-198,-174,-218,-194,-219,-242,-235,
-235,-287,-183,-196,-135,-134,-105] The following example is quite similar to
the game of Eljanov.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6.
bxc3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 $1 {By transposition, we got the same opening position.
Since we are going to meet 4.e3 with 4...c5, this move order is also quite
valid for us.} 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. e4 {[%cal Gc1g5]} Ne8 {Never forget to
play this move whenever your opponent is ready for Bg5.} 11. O-O Na5 12. f4 f5
{We have reached the same position as in the game Anton, D - Eljanov, P. Now,
instead of 13.Ng3, White immediately clarified the structure by means of} 13.
exf5 exf5 14. dxc5 bxc5 {As we have already discussed, this pawn structure is
quite favourable for Black. Besides the terrible weakness on c4, White cannot
activate his minor pieces. We can safely say that Black is strategically
winning.} 15. Ng3 g6 16. Be3 Rc8 {This move is obviously enough to keep the
huge advantage.} ({I would have even preferred} 16... Qc7 {[%cal Ge8f6,Ga8e8]
with the idea to proceed with ...Nf6 followed by ...Rae8. I think that the
a8-rook actually belongs to e8.}) 17. Rb1 Ba6 $6 {In my opinion, this decision
is slightly dubious. Black focuses on the c4-pawn but leaves the important
diagonal.} ({More logical would have been to attack the c4-pawn by means of} 
17... Qc7 18. Re1 Nd6 $17 {when Black keeps his huge advantage.}) 18. Re1 Rf7
19. Bf2 Bxc4 20. Bxc4 $6 {This time, White makes an inaccuracy.} ({Better
would have been} 20. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3] with the idea of transferring the
knight to e3. Even in this case, however, Black is better.}) 20... Nxc4 $17 {
White does not have compensation for the pawn. Later on, Aleksandrov managed
to convert his advantage into a full point.} 21. Qa4 Ned6 22. Qxa7 Nd2 23. Rbd1
N2e4 24. Nxe4 Nxe4 25. Qb7 Nxc3 26. Bh4 Rb8 27. Qf3 Qa5 28. Rd3 Ne4 29. Rb3 Rc8
30. Reb1 Nd2 31. Qb7 Rcf8 32. Be1 c4 0-1

