0,-28,-52,-44,-52,1,0,0,-70,-70,-66,-65,-63,-63,-84,-113,-180,-165,-165,-91,
-72,-72,-60,-51,-165,-165,-183,-196,-226,-145,-149,-149,-145,-147,-149,-150,
-378,-372,-374,-373,-364,-356,-324,-349] This game shows how to handle the
position when the advance f3-f4 cannot be answered with ...f7-f5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 ({Obviously, our move order will be} 4... c5 5. a3
Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O {transposing to the game.}) 5.
Bd3 Bb7 6. f3 c5 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Na5 11. e4 Ne8 {
So far so good. We are familiar with all the moves so far. Now, instead of the
usual f3-f4, White played} 12. Ng3 {The idea of this move is to deprive Black
of...f7-f5 in response to f3-f4. On the other hand, in some lines, the
d4-pawn is going to be vulnerable.} Ba6 {Black immediately starts putting
pressure on c4. It turns out that White cannot protect the pawn in a
favourable way.} 13. Qe2 {This move protects c4 but drops the d4-pawn.} ({
More principled would have been} 13. f4 Bxc4 14. Bxc4 Nxc4 15. f5 {[%cal Gf5f6]
White is threatening to follow with f5-f6. Black's most precise reaction is}
cxd4 16. cxd4 f6 $1 {Remember this idea. Whenever you cannot answer f2-f4 with
...f7-f5, you should meet f4-f5 with ...f7-f6. White's kingside initiative
cannot compensate for the missing pawn.} 17. Rf4 {[%cal Gf4h4] White is
planning to transfer the rook to h4.} ({A high-profile game saw} 17. Rb1 {
½-½ (36) Jobava,B (2713)-Wojtaszek,R (2683) Khanty-Mansiysk 2011. At this
point, Black could have played} Rc8 18. Rf4 exf5 19. exf5 Ned6 20. Rh4 Qe8 $19
{with a winning position. White does not have any attack.}) 17... Ned6 18. Rh4
Qe8 $17 {Once again, this move preventing Qh5 is Black's best response to Rh4.}
) 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Nb3 {As we have already pointed out, the vulnerability
of the d4-pawn is the main drawback behind 12.Ng3.} 15. Rb1 Nxd4 16. Qe3 Nc6
17. e5 Qh4 $6 {I don't particularly like this move since the queen will be
slightly misplaced on h4.} ({Black should have played} 17... Na5 $17 {with an
obvious advantage.}) 18. f4 f5 19. c5 Nc7 20. Bxa6 Nxa6 21. cxb6 axb6 22. Rxb6
Nc7 23. Rb7 Nd5 24. Qc5 Qd8 25. Bd2 Rf7 26. Ne2 Qc8 27. Rfb1 d6 28. Qxd6 Rxb7
29. Rxb7 Qxb7 30. Qxe6+ Kh8 31. Qxd5 Rd8 32. Qc5 Qb2 33. Qxc6 Qxd2 34. Kf2 Qa5
35. a4 Qa7+ 36. Ke1 Rb8 37. Qc2 g6 38. h3 Qe3 39. a5 Qa7 40. Qc3 Ra8 41. e6+
Kg8 42. Qc4 Qxa5+ 43. Kf2 Qa2 44. Qc6 Qa7+ 45. Kg3 Rd8 46. Qc4 Qe3+ 47. Kh2 Re8
48. e7+ Kh8 49. Nc3 Qxe7 50. Nd5 Qg7 51. Qc6 Rd8 52. Qe6 Qd4 53. Ne3 Qxf4+ 54.
Kg1 Qd4 55. Kh1 Ra8 0-1

