-315,-315,-1041,-1041,-1098,-1164,-1278,-29991,-29992] In this example, we
shall see how to handle the position when White answers ...f7-f5 with e4-e5.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({In this case, our move order would be
} 4... c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O {transposing
to the game.}) 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 c5 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O
Na5 11. e4 Ne8 12. f4 f5 {We are familiar with all the moves that have been
played so far. At this point, White decided to win central space by means of}
13. e5 {When playing e4-e5, White is usually ready to sacrifice the c4-pawn.
His idea is to grab space in order to restrict the mobility of the black
pieces. Therefore, Black should immediately challenge White's central
domination with the move} d6 ({A typical mistake would be} 13... Ba6 $6 {
when White will follow with} 14. d5 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. d6 {White has
tremendous compensation for the pawn since Black cannot coordinate his pieces.
The next move will be Qd3.}) 14. dxc5 $2 {After this poor positional decision,
White is strategically lost. For the sake of truth, however, Black was
