{[%evp 0,48,27,27,27,5,6,6,28,-1,-1,-1,24,18,23,21,26,11,21,21,21,21,58,59,85,
64,91,79,155,143,133,58,81,69,12,16,1,8,66,-7,-1,-20,-16,-14,-10,-4,0,0,0,0,0]
In the next couple of examples, we will examine situations where Black
sacrifices the c5-pawn. The following correspondence game is quite instructive.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. e3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8.
f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. e4 Ne8 {All the moves so far are quite familiar to us.
Now, instead of the usual 11.0-0, White played} 11. Be3 {putting pressure on
c5. It's very important to handle the pressure on c5 in the right way.
Obviously, Black cannot play ...cxd4, thus repairing White's pawn structure.
Practice as well as computer analysis show that sacrificing the c5-pawn is the
right decision in such positions. Usually, Black gets tremendous compensation
in view of his better structure and superior minor pieces.} Ba6 {Instead of
protecting the c5-pawn, Black immediately targets the weaknesso on c4.} 12. Qa4
Na5 13. dxc5 d6 $1 {A key move in Black's strategy. White can no longer keep
his c5-pawn.} 14. cxb6 {The most precise continuation.} ({The move} 14. c6 {
is very well met by} e5 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Re2,Re3][%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Ge6c5]
restricting all white minor pieces and planning the manoeuvre...Nc7-e6-c5. A
possible follow-up would be} 15. Nc1 Nc7 16. O-O Ne6 17. Rd1 Nc5 18. Bxc5 dxc5
19. Nb3 Nxb3 20. Qxb3 Qe8 $15 {The c6-pawn will be lost. In the arising
position, Black will be slightly better in view of his superior structure.})
14... axb6 15. Nd4 d5 $1 $132 {This is the simplest solution. It's important
to point out, however, that even without this move Black would have very nice
compensation for the pawn. The game ended in a draw quite soon.} 16. exd5 exd5
17. Qc2 Nxc4 18. Bf4 Qf6 19. Qc1 Ne5 20. Bxa6 Rxa6 21. O-O Nd3 22. Bg5 Nxc1 23.
Bxf6 Nxf6 24. Rfxc1 Rc8 1/2-1/2

