{[%evp 0,66,27,21,27,6,6,10,28,33,31,15,15,15,15,15,20,14,15,15,15,15,31,31,58,
31,-3,-29,-5,-5,-42,-42,-42,-40,-20,-37,-27,-69,-49,-62,-46,-60,-78,-84,-80,
-97,-97,-92,-99,-90,-100,-107,-83,-93,-83,-89,-130,-84,-138,-115,-131,-217,
-196,-316,-368,-161,-531,-29991,-29992] In most cases, Black is more
than happy to exchange the c5-pawn for the one on c4. This operation is
especially good when Black manages to eliminate White's light-squared bishop.
This game of Adorjan is a typical example.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3
c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O 10. O-O Ba6 $6 {
As we have already discussed, this is not the precise move order.} ({Black
should have played} 10... Na5) 11. e4 Ne8 12. Be3 $6 {This is not the right
way to put pressure on c5.} ({As we have already discussed, the best way of
using Black's imprecise move order is} 12. f4 f5 13. Ng3 {Let me remind you
that now the move} Nd6 $2 {will be met by} 14. exf5 exf5 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Be3
$16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 12... Nd6 $1 {Adorjan immediately
seizes the opportunity to exchange the c5-pawn for the one on c4. The next
couple of moves seems quite logical -} 13. dxc5 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. cxb6
axb6 $17 {Black has a huge advantage in this position in view of his better
pawn structure and the weak light squares in the camp of his opponent. Black's
bishop is clearly superior in this position. The weak light squares can be
utilized by means of simple moves such sa ...Qc7, ...Ba6, and ...Ne5.
Afterwards, the knight can go to either d3 or c4. Adorjan managed to win this
game in a rather convincing way.} 16. Rf2 Qc7 17. Nd4 Ne5 18. Rd2 Ba6 19. Bf4
d6 20. Nb3 Rfd8 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. Qc2 h6 24. h3 Rd3 25. Rc1 Qc4
26. Kh2 Kh7 27. Qb2 Re3 28. Rc2 Bb5 29. Nd2 Qd3 30. Qb3 Re2 31. a4 Be8 32. Qa2
Rf2 33. Rb2 Qe2 0-1

