{At the end of the lecture, we will deal with the so-called Leningrad System
arising after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {This system is no longer
popular at the highest level. As we will see in our games, very often Black is
the one who is fighting for an advantage.  In this game, I have employed
relatively rare but quite a strong move order -} c5 5. d5 h6 {Even though Black
can play 5...d6 or 5...Bxc3, I always prefer to first clarify the position of
the dark-squared bishop.} 6. Bh4 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 {This is the usual
continuation. White is planning to proceed with Bd3 and Ne2. If allowed, he
will start advancing the kingside pawns.} ({Note that the aggressive} 8. e4 $2
{drops a pawn after} g5 9. Bg3 Nxe4 $19 {Black is already winning.}) 8... Qe7
$5 {I quite like this move order. By protecting the d6-pawn, we want to follow
up with ...Nbd7 on the next move. For the time being, Black is delaying the
advance ...e6-e5. The idea is that if White plays Bd3 and Ne2, we can
challenge the entire construction by means of ...Ne5. The move ...e6-e5 should
be played in response to Nf3.} ({The traditional continuation is} 8... e5 9. f3
Nbd7 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gg1e2] when White usually proceed with Qc2 and Ne2.
Even though this position is also quite acceptable for Black, I would prefer
to restrict White's choice a little bit.}) 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Ne2 Ne5 {This is
the point. Now, White cannot save his light-squared bishop.} 11. O-O O-O ({
Another decent option is} 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 g5 13. Bg3 e5 {This kind of
position with opposite-coloured bishops is almost always favourable for Black.
White's minor pieces are simply not working. The next step is to carry out the
advance ...f7-f5.} 14. f4 {Obviously, Black cannot allow his opponent to open
the position.} e4 15. Qc2 Nh5 16. Be1 Ng7 17. Ng3 f5 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gh6h5,Gh5h4]
White didn't manage to activate his pieces. Black is now ready to gain space
on the kingside by means of ...g5-g4 followed by ...h6-h5-h4-h3.} 18. Rb1 g4
19. a4 h5 20. a5 h4 21. Ne2 Qc7 22. Qa2 h3 $1 {Black's idea is to close the
kingside and strike on the queenside with ...b7-b6.} 23. g3 O-O 24. Bd2 Bd7 {
At this point, the draw was agreed in the game ½-½ (24) Alexieva, S (2240)
-Maric,M (2280) Sofia 1994. Black should have kept playing. For example, a
possible continuation of the game would have been} 25. Rb2 b6 26. a6 ({After} 
26. axb6 $2 axb6 27. Qb3 Qa7 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gb6b5] Black is already winning.
Besides the possibility of invading via the a-file, he can also start
queenside play by means of ...Rfb8 followed by ...b6-b5. Taking the pawn with}
28. Qxb6 {loses to} Qxb6 29. Rxb6 Ra2 $19) 26... Ne8 {[%csl Rc4,Rd5][%cal
Gc7c8,Ge8c7,Gd7e8,Ge8f7,Gb6b5] Even though White might eventually hold this
position, Black still has a bunch of constructive ideas here. One idea is to
put pressure on a6 by means of ...Qc8 followed by ...Nc7. Later on, the
advance ...b6-b5 can be possible in some cases, especially when Black has a
bishop on f7.}) 12. e4 {Now, Black should pay attention, since White is ready
to launch his typical central expansion by means of f2-f4.} Nxd3 13. Bxf6 {
The idea of this move is to deprive Black of the advance ...g7-g5.} ({
In case of} 13. Qxd3 {, I would have played} g5 14. Bg3 e5 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gf7f5]
when the superiority of the black minor pieces is quite obvious. Black can
already consider playing on the kingside by means of ...Nh5 followed by ...
f7-f5.}) 13... Qxf6 14. Qxd3 e5 {Black is already slightly better since the
white knight does not have suitable squares. If allowed, Black will carry out
the advance ...f7-f5. White's only constructive idea is} 15. f4 exf4 16. Rxf4
Qe5 {Now, the queen is pretty safe on e5. White's play on the f-file is not
enough to compensate him for his multiple structural weaknesses. In the future,
after stabilizing the position, Black is going to initiate a queenside play by
means of ...b7-b5.} 17. Raf1 Bd7 18. Qf3 f6 {All pawns on dark squares! White
does not have any active play on the kingside. The advance ...b7-b5 is coming.}
19. g4 b5 20. h4 bxc4 $19 {Black's position is already strategically winning.
Unfortunately, due to my imprecise play in the endgame, I missed the advantage.
} 21. g5 hxg5 22. hxg5 Qxg5+ 23. Kf2 f5 24. Rg1 Qh6 25. e5 dxe5 26. Rh1 Qg6 27.
Rfh4 f4 28. Rg1 Qf5 29. Rh5 Qd3 30. Qh1 Bf5 31. Rh8+ Kf7 32. Qh5+ Bg6 33. Rxf8+
Rxf8 34. Qxe5 Re8 35. Qxf4+ Kg8 36. Qg4 Qe3+ 37. Kf1 Re4 38. Rg3 Qd2 39. Qf3
Bf5 40. Kf2 Qxd5 41. Rg5 g6 42. Rg1 Qd2 43. Re1 Qd3 44. Qg3 Qxg3+ 45. Nxg3 Rxe1
46. Kxe1 Kf7 47. Kf2 Kf6 48. Ke3 Ke5 49. Nf1 Bb1 50. a3 Bd3 51. Nh2 Kd5 52. Ng4
Bf5 53. Nh2 Kc6 54. Kd2 g5 55. Nf1 Bd3 56. Ng3 Kd5 57. Ke3 Ke5 58. Kf3 Bf5 59.
Ke3 g4 60. Ne2 Be4 61. Ng3 Bd3 62. Nh5 1/2-1/2

