{[%evp 0,72,16,16,35,5,10,16,28,-10,18,-46,-14,-46,-46,-78,-5,-9,-9,-9,-12,-25,
30,37,52,52,83,23,23,10,52,-40,-39,4,6,0,51,-15,-4,-53,39,20,-34,-77,-49,-77,
-33,-43,-43,-24,-19,-15,-45,-33,-64,-47,-51,-433,0,0,0,-470,-342,-326,-257,
-376,-407,-410,-372,-443,-369,-423,-395,-423,-447] Now, we shall see how Black
should handle the positions arising after Nf3.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. Bg5 h6 {Starting with this move is also a pretty good idea.} 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5
d6 ({I would have preferred} 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 Qe7 9. Bd3 Nbd7 {
when we get the position from the game.}) 7. e3 Qe7 8. Bd3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nbd7
10. Nf3 {This is the more logical continuation. Obviously, White does not want
to allow ...Ne5. Now, Black can already play} e5 {closing the centre and
winning an important tempo. In the arising structure, positional
understanding is way more important than theoretical knowledge. You should
just understand how to arrange your pieces. Strategically speaking, the move}
11. Nd2 {is forced.} ({Closing the b1-h7 diagonal by playing} 11. e4 $2 {
would be a terrible positional mistake. In my opinion, Black's most promising
reaction would be} g5 {When Black hasn't castled, this is usually the best way
of dealing with the pin.} 12. Bg3 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6] Black is planning to play .
..Ng6 on the next move. Later on, his plan is usually based on the advance of
the kingside pawns, with or without putting a knight on f4. Note that in this
structure the king is usually safe on the queenside. When possible, try to put
it on c7 by employing the manoeuvre...Kd8-c7!}) 11... g5 {This move should be
played. Otherwise, White will prepare the advance f2-f4 when the pin will be
very annoying.} 12. Bg3 Kd8 $1 {I like this move a lot. Before launching his
kingside play, Black is transferring the king to the safe c7-square.} {We can
now fully understand why White has put his pawn on e3 and not on e4.
Fortunately, Black has more than one way of dealing with the weakness of the
f5-square.} 13. Bf5 Kc7 14. O-O h5 15. h3 h4 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gh5g7] Besides
gaining kingside space and restricting the dark-squared bishop, Black is also
planning the manoeuvre...Nh5-g7.} ({Even simpler would have been} 15... Nb6 16.
Bxc8 Raxc8 17. a4 {The following line is a very good illustration of Black's
ideas in this structure -} h4 18. Bh2 g4 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is designed
to further weaken the kingside.} 19. hxg4 h3 20. Bg3 hxg2 21. Kxg2 Rcg8 22. a5
Nbd7 $17 {It's very difficult for White to hold the kingside.} {It's important
to mention that} 23. f3 {will be met by} e4 $1 $19) 16. Bh2 Nh5 17. Rb1 Ng7 18.
Bxd7 Bxd7 19. f4 f6 20. fxe5 fxe5 $17 {Once again, Black has an advantage in
this position with opposite-coloured bishops since the h2-bishop is out of
play. Later on, Dizdar managed to win the game.} 21. Ne4 b6 22. a4 Bf5 23. Qc2
a5 24. Rb2 Rab8 25. Qb1 Rhf8 26. Rbf2 Bg6 27. Qb5 Rxf2 28. Rxf2 Bxe4 29. Qc6+
Kd8 30. Bxe5 Ne8 31. Bh2 Qd7 32. Rf8 Qxc6 33. dxc6 Bxc6 34. Rg8 Rb7 35. Bxd6
Rg7 36. Rf8 Kd7 0-1

