{In the next model game, we shall see how to play when White puts his bishop
on e2, instead of d3. The Georgian grandmaster Kachieshvili managed to carry
out all the typical ideas in the variation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Bg5 c5 5. d5 h6 6. Bh4 d6 7. e3 Qe7 ({In my opinion, a more precise and
restrictive move order is} 7... Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Qe7) 8. Nf3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nbd7 ({
Since the white knight is already on f3, Black could have started with} 9... e5
) 10. Qc2 e5 11. Nd2 {We have reached a position that is quite similar to the
previous game. In this case, however, instead of Bd3, White has played Qc2. As
we will see, this difference provides Black with an extra opportunity. The
Georgian grandmaster played} g5 ({Another possibility is} 11... e4 12. Be2 g5
13. Bg3 Nf8 {Since White has spent a tempo on Be2, Black has time to answer}
14. h4 {with} Ng6 15. Rb1 O-O {It turns out that after transferring the knight
to g6, Black can even consider castling short. Given the fact that Black
enjoys tremendous space advantage, it's not easy for White to make use of the
h-file.} 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. f3 {The right approach to the position. The e4-pawn
should be removed.} exf3 {This move is not a mistake but Black should handle
the arising position with care.} ({Simpler would have been} 17... Bf5 {[%cal
Ga8e8] supporting the pawn and planning ...Rae8. A possible follow-up would be}
18. f4 g4 19. Kf2 Kg7 20. Rh2 Rh8 21. Rbh1 Rxh2 22. Rxh2 Rh8 23. Rxh8 Kxh8 $11
{Even though the position is objectively equal, Black is the one who has
a slight advantage.}) 18. gxf3 Qxe3 $6 {Taking the pawn is risky.} ({More
precise would have been} 18... Kg7 19. Kf2 Re8 20. Qd3 Bd7 {[%cal Gg6e5,Ge8h8]
Black managed to complete the development and is ready to proceed with ...Rh8
followed by ...Ne5. An illustrative line would be} 21. Rxb7 Ne5 22. Bxe5 Qxe5
23. Rxd7 Nxd7 24. Rh5 Nf6 25. f4 Qe7 26. Rxg5+ Kf8 $17 {White does not have
full compensation for the exchange.}) 19. Nf1 Qe7 20. Kf2 $44 {[%cal Ge2d3,
Gc2d2,Gb1e1] Black's position was already dangerous in ½-½ (41) Stocek,J 
(2582)-Eljanov,P (2717) Ohrid 2009 CBM 133. White can develop his attack by
means of simple moves such as Bd3 followed by Re1 and Qd2.}) 12. Bg3 e4 $1 {
We can now see another point behind the early ...Qe7. From that position, the
knight not only supports the advance ...e5-e4 but also protects the d6-pawn.
In this pawn structure, Black should settle for a light-square strategy. Only
two white minor pieces can control the light squares while Black can control
the light square complex with all his minor pieces. Therefore, the exchange of
the light-squared bishops is one of Black's major positional ideas.} 13. h4 {
This is White's only constructive idea. As we will see, however, the control
of the h-file is not that important. The reason is that the e4-pawn prevents
the rest of White's army to support the rook.} Rg8 {The standard reaction to
h2-h4. As we know, the king will go to c7.} 14. Be2 Kd8 15. Rb1 Kc7 {The king
has found safe heaven on c7. Now, Black is planning to complete the
development by employing the manoeuvre...Nf8-g6. Afterwards, he can consider
exchanging the light-squared bishops via g4.} 16. Rb5 {A tricky move. For the
time being Black cannot play 16...Nf8 in view of 17.Rxc5+!. Hence, it's
important to protect the c5-pawn by means of} b6 {Now, at least, White can use
the b6-pawn as a hook. His only constructive idea is a2-a4-a5.} 17. Rb2 Nf8 18.
Qb3 Ng6 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. a4 {An important prophylactic move. Black is
planning to answer a4-a5 with Rgb8.} Bd7 {[%cal Gg8b8]} ({The attempt to
immediately exchange the light-squared bishops with} 20... Bg4 $2 {loses to}
21. a5 Rgb8 22. Bxg4 Nxg4 23. Qb5 Qe8 24. Nxe4 Qxe4 25. Qc6+ Kd8 26. Bxd6 $18 {
White has a winning attack.}) 21. a5 Rgb8 22. Qa3 Bg4 $2 {Even though the
exchange of the light-squared bishops is generally desirable, in this concrete
position is a tactical mistake.} ({Better would have been} 22... Ne8 {planning
either ...f7-f5 or ...Nh4.}) 23. Rb5 $6 {This time White commits a serious
inaccuracy.} ({The problem is that after} 23. Bxg4 $1 Nxg4 24. Qa4 Qe8 25. Qxe8
Rxe8 26. Rh7 $18 {Black's position is falling apart.}) 23... Bxe2 24. Kxe2 Qd7
25. Rhb1 $4 {This move is losing on the spot.} ({More tenacious would have been
} 25. Qa4) 25... Qg4+ 26. Ke1 Nd7 $19 {[%cal Gg6e5,Gf7f5,Gf5f4] Black can now
follow with either ...f7-f5 or ...Nge5. He is already winning.} 27. Qb3 f5 28.
Qd1 Qxd1+ 29. Kxd1 Rh8 30. f3 f4 31. Bf2 exf3 32. Nxf3 g4 33. Ng5 Rh2 34. Ne6+
Kb7 35. a6+ Kxa6 36. Nc7+ Kb7 37. Nxa8 Rxg2 38. Be1 f3 0-1

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The System with 4.Qc2"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "14"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.10.28"]

{In this lecture, we deal with one of the most critical systems against the
Nimzo-Indian Defence arising after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 {
Besides preventing Black from doubling the pawns with ...Bxc3+, White takes
the control of the important e4-square. In many lines, he is ready to execute
the advance e2-e4. On the downside, White's last move does not contribute to
the development. Additionally, Black can now try to use the vulnerability of
the d4-square.  Also against this line, I suggest} c5 {immediately attacking
the vulnerable d4-spot. The first important tabiya arises after} 5. dxc5 O-O {
Obviously, Black will regain the c5-pawn. If allowed, we will do it by means
of the manoeuvre...Na6-Nxc5. Taking with the knight is desirable since in this
case, Black has better control of the centre. Nevertheless, the immediate 5...
Na6 is dubious in view of 6.a3 Bxc3 7.Qxc3 Nxc5 8.b4 Nce4 9.Qd4 when the
threat of f2-f3 is very annoying. Therefore, we mostly play ...Na6 when White
goes for Nf3. The main move in this position is} 6. a3 {forcing Black to take
on c5 with the bishop.} ({As pointed out above, the move} 6. Nf3 {is well met
by} Na6 {After capturing on c5 with the knight, Black has several plans at his
disposal. The most typical and universal one is ...b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7
and ...Rc8. Later on, Black can make use of the misplaced white queen by means
of ...d7-d5. Depending on White's concrete continuation, however, Black can
opt for different setups. In the model games, you will see all the must-know
important ideas.}) ({In this lecture, I also demonstrate why the endgame
arising after} 6. Bf4 Na6 7. Bd6 Re8 8. a3 Qa5 9. Rc1 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11.
Rxc3 Ne4 {followed by ...Naxc5 is harmless for Black.}) 6... Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 {
This is the main tabiya of our repertoire against 4.Qc2. In this position,
White has two systems of development: 1) Setups based on Bg5 2) Setups based
on Bf4 Usually, when White goes for Bg5, we play in the Hedgehog style.
Standard moves in that direction are ...Bb7, ...Bb7, ...a7-a6, and ...d7-d6.
You can play this setup without knowing too much of a theory. On the other
hand, the setups with Bf4 are usually more active and require dynamic play for
Black. For instance, if White goes for an aggressive setup based on Bf4, Rd1,
and e2-e4, Black is advised to prioritize the development of his queenside.
The usual way of developing the queenside pieces in this case is ...Bb7
followed by ...Nc6, and ...Rc8. On the other hand, after neutralizing White's
temporary activity, Black can again settle for a Hedgehog type of play.
Obviously, these are only general remarks. In the model games, you will see
that our move orders and setups will vary depending on White's exact variation.
} *

