{[%evp 0,78,27,27,27,3,-11,-2,-6,-14,0,-7,-4,-1,3,-45,-28,-29,-19,-50,-63,-33,
-64,-95,-83,-131,-79,-76,-108,-119,-100,-106,-127,-137,-135,-129,-129,-152,
-157,-170,-153,-375,-367,-464,-486,-492,-509,-513,-514,-517,-494,-527,-527,
-485,-359,-524,-581,-571,-752,-1035,-534,-559,-409,-413,-426,-451,-409,-508,
-540,-623,-682,-766,-787,-820,-811,-821,-834,-841,-717,-717,-698] This game
made me consider playing 4...c5 in response to 4.Qc2. The game was played in
the penultimate round of the Bulgarian National Championship under 18. In
order to keep the chances for the title, I needed to win with White. Maybe the
importance of this encounter is one of the reasons why I still remember this
instructive loss.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Nf3 {
This move is not bad in general but White shouldn't play it on general grounds.
Otherwise, Black can even overtake the initiative.} Na6 {As pointed out in the
introduction, Black always tries to capture the c5-pawn with a knight.} 7. a3
$6 {Facing unknown variation, I started playing on general grounds. During the
game, I was convinced that taking the bishop pair is favourable for White. The
problem, however, is that after} ({As we are going to see a bit later, the
most sensible continuation is} 7. g3) 7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 {[%csl Rc3]
Black manages to develop very strong initiative in view of the misplaced white
queen. As we are going to witness on multiple occasions, Black wins many
tempis by attacking the queen.} 9. b4 $6 {This moves appears to be
overoptimistic. With insufficient development, White shouldn't be playing with
overextended queenside.} ({Better would have been} 9. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1]
with the idea of completing the development by means of Be2 followed by 0-0.
We will see such an approach in the next examples. For the time being, I would
say that Black has three good plans at his disposal. The most common idea is}
b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8c8,Gd7d5] planning to proceed with ...Bb7 followed by ...
Rc8 and ...d7-d5.} ({Another positionally justified approach is} 9... d6 {
[%cal Ge6e5,Gc8e6,Ga8c8,Ga7a5] After parting with his dark-squared bishop,
Black puts his central pawns on dark squares. This time, he wants to put
pressure on c4 with ...e6-e5 followed by ...Be6, and ...Rc8. Quite often, we
can consider playing ...a7-a5 in order to stabilize the c5-knight.}) ({The
third perfectly valid option is} 9... a5 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ga5a4,Gd7d6,Ge6e5,
Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Gb7a6] I like this flexible move. First of all, Black wants to fix
the queenside by means of ...a5-a4, making use of the vulnerable b3-square. In
the future, we can play either ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5 followed by ...Be6 or
stick to the plan with ...b7-b6. In the latter case, the bishop can be even
developed to a6.})) 9... Nce4 10. Qd4 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge6e5] The queen is usually
quite vulnerable on d4. Now, the plan with ...d7-d6 followed by ...e6-e5 is
pretty sound.} ({The lesser evil would have been} 10. Qb2 {In this case, Black
will immediately open the centre with} d5 ({During the game, I was afraid of} 
10... Ng4 {It turns out, however, that White has} 11. h3 {with the idea to meet
} Ngxf2 $2 {by} 12. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gc1e3] It turns out tha tthe
f2-knight is in trouble. White is ready to follow with Be3.}) 11. cxd5 Nxd5 $36
{[%cal Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Gd5c3] In this symmetrical structure, Black has the
initiative in view of his better development. He can follow with natural moves
such as ...Bd7, ...Rc8, and ...Ndc3. With a precise play, however, White has
huge defensive resources.}) 10... a5 $1 {Even though the computer does not
like this move, I find it instructive. Before going for ...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5,
Iotov undermines White's queenside structure.} ({Mathematically speaking} 10...
d6 {[%cal Ge6e5] would have been more precise.}) 11. b5 $2 {After this
terrible positional move, White is strategically lost. I was afraid that after
...d7-d6 and ...e6-e5, Black can simultaneously target the pawns on b4 and f2
by playing ...Qb6.} ({White should have gone for the dynamic} 11. g4 $1 {
with an unclear play.}) 11... d6 12. Ng5 {As we will see, this attempt to
release the tension by means of some exchanges does not work.} e5 13. Qb2 Nc5
$1 {Correctly, Black avoids exchanges. Now, White will be forced to move the
knight back.} 14. Nf3 Be6 15. e3 Bf5 {The idea of this move is to prevent
White from castling. The threat is ...Nd3+ on the next move. Let's follow the
game for a few more moves.} 16. Be2 Nd3+ 17. Bxd3 Bxd3 18. Qc3 e4 19. Nd2 Rc8 {
[%cal Gd6d5] Introducing the threat of ...d6-d5.} 20. a4 {White protects the
b5-pawn with the idea to answer ...d6-d5 with c4-c5. With my last move,
however, I allowed} Nd5 21. Qd4 Nb4 $19 {White is completely lost. He can no
longer avoid material losses.} 22. Qc3 Nc2+ 23. Kd1 Nxa1 24. Bb2 Qg5 25. Bxa1
Qxg2 26. Re1 Qg4+ 27. f3 exf3 28. Qxd3 f2+ 29. Re2 Qg1+ 30. Kc2 Qxa1 31. Rxf2
Qxa4+ 32. Kb2 Qb4+ 33. Ka2 d5 34. Rg2 dxc4 35. Qd4 Qa4+ 36. Kb1 Qd1+ 37. Ka2
Qa4+ 38. Kb1 Qxb5+ 39. Kc1 f6 0-1

