{[%evp 0,34,27,27,27,-2,-10,6,8,-14,7,-4,3,3,4,-5,-17,0,0,-35,-28,-33,-9,-48,
-48,-48,-41,-51,-52,-331,-336,-332,-355,-476,-493,-544,-526] Now, we shall
take a look at another instructive example of how Black can use the vulnerable
white queen. By now, we know that the queen's vulnerability is a very common
theme in this variation.  The first 8 moves repeat my game against Valentin
Iotov.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Nf3 Na6 7. a3
Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 9. e3 {By playing this move, White shows his intention to
complete the development of the kingside. At this point, Black can apply all
three plans mentioned in my comments to the previous example. Gipslis
played} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] planning to fix the queenside by means of ...a5-a4.}
10. Be2 {White prioritizes the development over the queenside structure.} ({
Another natural move would have been} 10. b3 {In this case, Black's most
challenging plan would be} d6 11. Be2 ({The alternative} 11. Nd2 {does not
work quite well. White anticipates ...Nfe4 but allows} b5 $1 {which is a
typical way of exploiting White's inferior development. The idea is that after}
12. cxb5 Bb7 $17 {[%cal Ga8c8,Ge6e5,Gf6e4,Gd8h4] White cannot develop his
kingside. At the same time, Black can increase the pressure with simple moves
such as ...Rc8, ...e6-e5, ...Nfe4, and ...Qh4.}) 11... Nfe4 12. Qb2 a4 13. b4
Nb3 14. Rb1 e5 {[%cal Gc8e6,Ga8c8] White is under huge pressure. Black can now
put pressure on the vulnerable c4-pawn by means of ...Be6 followed by ...Rc8.})
10... a4 11. Nd2 b6 12. O-O Ba6 $1 {[%cal Ga6e2] This move makes a lot of
sense now. As we will see, Black can exploit the opposition on the diagonal
f1-a6. At the same time, it's not clear how White is going to develop his
queenside.} 13. Rd1 Rc8 14. Qb4 $4 {This is losing on the spot.} ({The lesser
evil would have been} 14. b4 {Nevertheless, after} axb3 15. Bb2 d5 $17 {
Black's advantage is beyond any doubt.}) 14... Nd5 $1 $19 {A simple but
elegant way of exploiting the restricted mobility of the white queen.} 15. cxd5
Bxe2 16. Rf1 Bxf1 17. Nxf1 Nb3 0-1

