{[%evp 0,102,23,20,23,15,15,15,26,8,8,16,21,0,0,-14,-11,-32,-24,-19,-11,-33,
-11,-21,-13,-1,-1,-1,-25,-25,-6,-10,-1,-22,-21,-23,-36,-30,-30,-30,-20,-20,-18,
-22,-18,-38,-30,-30,-32,-26,-43,-55,-42,-58,-45,-41,-35,-40,-33,-32,-23,-23,
-13,-76,-81,-98,-95,-103,-63,-103,-97,-104,-99,-103,-91,-97,-87,-106,-55,-41,9,
-4,0,-10,-10,-64,-52,-83,-66,-132,0,-123,-48,-144,-70,-60,-38,-28,0,0,0,0,0,
-81,0] This model game is a very nice application of Black's light square
strategy. This strategy is possible in view of the weakened light squares on
the queenside.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 O-O 5. Nf3 c5 6. dxc5 Na6
7. e3 Nxc5 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8c8] This is another natural
way of handling the position. Black is planning to proceed with ...Bb7
followed by ...Rc8 and ...d7-d5. In my opinion, this universal setup works in
all the cases when Black is allowed to recapture on c5 with a knight.
Therefore, you can always go for it when you cannot see a more promising
option.} ({As we have seen in the game of Gipslis, the move} 9... a5 {is also
quite promising in this position.}) 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Rc8 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Gc8c3,Gd7d5] White should already decide how to deal with the annoying
opposition along the c-file. Black's next move is going to be ...d7-d5.} 12. b4
{This active move is White's most natural continuation. We should understand,
however, that now the squares c4 and b3 are very weak. The next couple of
moves is quite logical.} Nce4 13. Qb3 d5 14. Bb2 Qe7 {Even though this move
is perfectly natural, I find it a bit less straightforward.} ({The optimal way
of applying the light square strategy would have been} 14... dxc4 15. Bxc4 Bd5
$1 {Ideally, Black should exchange all white minor pieces that can control the
light squares. In our dream position, White will be left with his useless
dark-squared bishop against the black knight on c4.  A possible follow-up
would be} 16. Bxd5 Qxd5 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 18. Rac1 f6 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rc4][%cal
Ga7a6,Gb6b5,Ge6e5,Ge4d6,Gd6c4] A very important move in Black's strategy. The
idea is to restrict the bishop by means of ...e6-e5. Afterwards, Black can
consider rerouting e4-knight to c4 via the d6-square.}) 15. h3 Nd6 {A good
positional decision. By putting pressure on c4, Black wants to provoke cxd5.}
16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Qd1 Nfe4 {[%cal Gd5c4] Black keeps playing in an optimal way.
Besides the usual positional threat of ...Bc4, he is ready to carry out the
typical idea ...f7-f6 followed by ...e6-e5.} 18. Rc1 Rxc1 19. Qxc1 Rc8 20. Qa1
f6 21. Rc1 Bc4 22. Bxc4 Nxc4 {Everything is going according to the plan. After
a series of precise moves, Black managed to occupy the important c4-square. It's
already obvious that the bishop is problematic. Nevertheless, White's position
remains perfectly defendable.} 23. Qa2 ({Probably a bit more precise would
have been} 23. b5 {taking the control of the c6-square and preventing Black
from playing ...b6-b5.}) 23... b5 24. Nd4 a6 25. Nb3 $6 {This move is already
a step in the wrong direction. White should have resorted to dynamic means in
order to challenge Black's static advantage.} ({More to the point would have
been} 25. a4 Qxb4 26. axb5 axb5 27. Nxe6 $13 {with an unclear position.}) 25...
Rd8 26. Qb1 Ned2 {Black follows his main strategy - exchange all minor pieces
that are capable of controlling the light squares.} 27. Nxd2 Rxd2 {Mission
completed. Now, the c4-knight will be fighting against the passive bishop.} 28.
Bc3 Rd7 29. Rd1 Qd8 30. Rxd7 Qxd7 $15 {From the computer's perspective, White's
position is fully defendable. In a practical play, however, Black is a lot
better. White cannot oppose our play on the light squares.} 31. Qc1 Qd3 32. g3
Kf7 33. Kg2 Qf5 (33... h5 $19) 34. Bb2 Qe4+ 35. Kg1 Qd3 36. Bc3 Kf8 37. Kg2 Ke7
38. g4 Qe2 39. Bd4 Qa2 40. Bc5+ Ke8 41. Qd1 Qd2 42. Qb3 Qd5+ 43. Kg3 Kf7 44. a4
Qe5+ 45. Kg2 Qd5+ 46. Kg3 h5 47. axb5 axb5 48. gxh5 Qh1 49. Qc2 Qg1+ 50. Kf3 f5
51. Qa2 Qd1+ 1/2-1/2

