{[%evp 0,72,18,-22,-11,-24,5,-4,22,-25,6,-3,6,4,4,-8,-16,-27,-33,-33,-33,-33,
-35,-64,-67,-81,-81,-85,-74,-80,-27,-21,-26,-40,-35,-101,-130,-94,-94,-94,-91,
-114,-103,-184,-104,-182,-188,-182,-94,-124,-124,-106,-106,-106,0,-130,-185,
-390,-188,-197,-141,-219,-219,-381,-379,-476,-425,-420,28,-517,-533,-1259,
-1359,-1359,-1439] When it comes to using White's inferior development, the
following blitz game of Vincent Keymer is very instructive as well.} 1. c4 Nf6
2. Nc3 e6 3. d4 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Nf3 Na6 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5
9. b4 Nce4 10. Qd4 {So far this game follows my encounter with Iotov. Now,
instead of Iotov's 10...a5, Keymer played} d6 {[%cal Ge6e5] which is a bit
more precise since White cannot play g2-g4.} 11. Nd2 $6 {This passive move
only makes Black's initiative stronger.} ({White's problem is that} 11. g4 $4 {
will be answered with} e5 12. Qd3 Bxg4 $17 {when White does not have any
compensation for the pawn.}) ({Contrary to my game with Iotov, in this position
} 11. Ng5 {would have been more sensible since the black knight cannot retreat
to c5. Nevertheless, White's position remains difficult. An illustrative line
would be} e5 12. Qb2 a5 $1 {Never forget about this thematic move which often
allows us to create targets on the queenside.} 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. g3 {White
wants to develop his bishop with a tempo.} axb4 15. Bg2 {This pawn sacrifice
is forced.} ({A typical problem in such positions is that after} 15. axb4 $4
Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Qb6 $19 {Black is simultaneously targeting the pawns on b4 and
f2. White can already resign.}) 15... bxa3 16. Rxa3 Bf5 $17 {White does not
have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11... e5 12. Qd3 Bf5 {Black is
playing all the moves with a tempo. White's position is already undefendable.}
13. Nxe4 Bxe4 (13... Nxe4 {would have been possible as well.}) 14. Qd2 a5 {
This typical move turns out to be a bit slow for this position. Such an
inaccuracy, however, is quite typical for a blitz game.} ({More to the point
would have been} 14... Rc8 15. e3 Bf5 {[%cal Gf5e6] followed by ...Be6. White
cannot complete the development in view of the vulnerable c4-pawn.}) 15. f3 Bg6
16. e4 axb4 17. Qxb4 $2 {This is already a decisive mistake.} ({White should
have played} 17. Be2 {claiming some compensation for the pawn.}) 17... Nxe4 $1
$19 {This is the point! Now Black is winning.} 18. fxe4 Qh4+ 19. Kd1 Qxe4 20.
Bd2 Rfc8 21. h3 d5 22. Be2 Qxg2 23. Re1 Qe4 24. Rc1 d4 25. Bg4 Qd3 26. Rxe5 Re8
27. Qb5 Qf1+ 28. Be1 Qd3+ 29. Bd2 f6 30. Be2 Qxh3 31. Qd5+ Kh8 32. Rxe8+ Rxe8
33. Qf3 Qe6 34. c5 d3 35. Bxd3 Qb3+ 36. Rc2 Bxd3 0-1

