{In the next two examples, we shall examine an interesting line that White
occasionally uses.  The starting position arises after} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Bf4 {White develops his dark-squared bishop
to the optimal f4-square. Additionally, he is planning to answer ...Na6 with
Bd6. The drawback of this approach is that White neglects the kingside
development. Black can force the transition into a favourable endgame. The
next couple of moves is quite logical -} Na6 7. Bd6 Re8 8. a3 Qa5 $1 {This
precise move immediately solves Black's problems. Actually, this is pretty
much the only concrete thing that you should know about the line with 6.Bf4.
The rest is an understanding of the pawn structure.} ({White's idea can be seen
in the line} 8... Bxc5 $2 9. Bxc5 Nxc5 10. b4 {[%csl Ra6,Ge4][%cal Gc3e4,Gc2e4]
when the black knight will be forced into the inferior a6-square.}) 9. Rc1
Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Ne4 {Without this key move, Black's concept
wouldn't have been possible.} 12. Rc2 {This retreat is considered to be a bit
more precise than 12.Rc1. The idea is that in some of the lines it's important
to control the b2-square.} ({The importance of the b2-square can be seen after
} 12. Rc1 Naxc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 Na4 $1 {The vulnerable b2-square makes
this move more attractive than the usual ...Ne4.} 15. e3 a5 $1 {Once again we
see this thematic way of using White's overextended queenside. The a8-rook
immediately starts playing.} 16. Bd3 $6 {White allows his opponent to make use
of the b2-square.} (16. Be2 axb4 17. axb4 d6 18. Nf3 Kf8 {[%cal Gf8e7] An
important prophylactic move. At any moment, Black is ready to support the
d6-pawn by means of ...Ke7.} 19. O-O Bd7 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gf8e7] Black is
ready to follow with ...Ke7 and ...Rfc8. His counterplay is based on the
vulnerable white queenside pawns.}) 16... axb4 17. axb4 Nb2 {Only now it
becomes clear why the b2-square is so important.} 18. Bc2 $2 {This losing move
was played in the only game where this position occurred.} ({White should have
played} 18. Be2 {when a possible follow-up would have been} b6 19. Nf3 Bb7 20.
O-O Ra4 21. b5 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Rc8 $15 {White will be fighting for a drawn until
the end of the game.}) 18... Nxc4 19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Rxc4 {This position
occurred in the game 0-1 (25) Koenig, O-Baerwinkel, T (2155) Crailsheim 1999. At
this point, Black should have played} Ra1+ 21. Kd2 Rf1 $19 {with a decisive
advantage.}) 12... Naxc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 {As a matter of fact, this endgame is
even more comfortable for Black. The reason is White's overextended queenside.
Besides putting pressure on c4, Black can try to utilize the weak b3-square.
For example, fixing the queenside with ...a7-a5-a4 is quite a thematic idea
for such positions.} 14. Nf3 {This modest continuation is designed to complete
the development. On the other hand, Black has now enough time to carry out his
positional ideas.} ({White's most ambitious approach is} 14. b4 Ne4 15. f3 Nf6
16. e4 {It turns out, however, that White's development is not enough to
sustain the captured space. Therefore, Black can strike with} d5 {The most
logical follow-up will be} 17. e5 Nd7 18. f4 dxc4 19. Bxc4 Nb6 20. Nf3 Bd7 $15
{Black's position is slightly preferable. Besides the natural ...Rec8, Black
can also undermine White's queenside by means of ...a7-a5.}) 14... b6 {[%csl
Rc4][%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gc8a6] A very nice multipurpose move. Besides the normal
...Bb7, Black can consider focusing on the c4-pawn by playing ...a7-a5-a4
followed by ...Ba6.} 15. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4b5,Gb5d6] Planning to bring the knight
all the way to d6. This manoeuvre, however, is dubious for two reasons: 1) It
takes way too much time 2) The knight is actually not stable on d6} a5 $1 {
I like this positional decision by Karpov. He is even not trying to control
the b5-square. Instead, fixing the queenside with ...a5-a4 is more important.}
16. Nb5 Rd8 17. Nd6 Bb7 18. Nxb7 Nxb7 {Even though there are pawns on both
wings, a subtle endgame expert like Karpov understands that in this position
the knight is superior to the bishop. The point is that the bishop is heavily
restricted by the c4-pawn.} 19. e3 Rac8 20. Bd3 Nc5 21. Be2 a4 $1 $17 {A
thematic way of fixing the queenside. Black has the following winning plan in
this position: 1) Double the rooks on the c-file by means of ...Rc5 and ...
Rdc8 2) Increase the pressure on c4 by putting the knight on a5 3) Bring the
king to e7 in order to secure the d7-pawn 4) Start advancing the kingside
pawns in order to create a second weakness 5) Combine the attack on both
weaknesses and win the game. I strongly advise you to examine the game until
the end (without using engines) and see how Karpov managed to implement this
long-term plan.} 22. f3 Nb3 23. Bd3 Rc5 24. Ke2 Rdc8 25. Rc3 Na5 26. Rhc1 Kf8
27. Kf2 Ke7 28. Ke2 h6 29. Ke1 Rh5 30. h3 Rhc5 31. Kf2 Nb3 32. R1c2 d6 33. Ke1
g5 34. g3 R5c7 35. Bf1 f5 36. Kf2 Rf8 37. Bg2 f4 38. Bf1 Rc5 39. Bd3 fxe3+ 40.
Kxe3 Re5+ 41. Be4 Nc5 42. Kd4 Nb3+ 43. Kd3 Kd7 44. Ke3 Nc5 45. Kd4 Rc8 46. Rf2
Nb3+ 47. Kd3 Rf8 48. Rfc2 h5 49. Ke3 Nc5 50. Kd4 g4 51. Re3 gxf3 52. Bxf3 Nb3+
53. Kd3 Rxe3+ 0-1

