{[%evp 0,84,39,17,17,6,6,6,23,-14,2,2,11,-11,-11,-9,-9,-9,-9,-13,4,6,-5,3,2,
-12,-8,-8,-8,-8,-8,-8,-8,0,0,0,-3,-11,-3,-14,0,-2,0,-22,-21,-21,-21,-30,-30,
-28,-28,-23,-35,-31,-15,-33,-25,-81,-37,-10,-5,-10,0,0,-7,3,9,0,0,-42,-42,-54,
-37,-91,-58,-169,-138,-181,-169,-161,-161,-170,-170,-176,-154,-238,-176] In
this game, we shall how powerful the Hedgehog setup can be against the line
with 6.Bf4. We are already familiar with the first 14 moves.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Bf4 Na6 7. Bd6 Re8 8. a3 Qa5 9. Rc1
Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Rxc3 Ne4 12. Rc2 Naxc5 13. Bxc5 Nxc5 14. b4 Ne4 15. e3
{Instead of playing f2-f3 followed by e2-e4, White is planning to first
develop some pieces.} b6 {This move is played with the idea to meet Bd3 with ..
.Bb7.} ({Obviously, the standard} 15... a5 {is perfectly playable as well.})
16. Bd3 Bb7 17. f3 Nf6 18. Ne2 a5 19. Kd2 axb4 20. axb4 Rec8 21. e4 d6 {
Finally, we have reached a position which is quite similar to the Hedgehog.
Even though such positions are objectively equal, I usually prefer playing
with Black. The thing is that White's overextended position requires a higher
degree of precision. At the same time, Black's d6-pawn is not a real weakness.
He can easily defend it by putting the king on e7.} 22. Nd4 Kf8 23. Nb5 Ke7 {
It turns out that White cannot increase the pressure on d6. At the same time,
he needs to reckon with ideas such as ...Ra4 and ...Nd7-e5.} 24. Re1 {[%cal
Gb5d6,Ge4e5] Introducing the threat of Nxd6 followed by e4-e5.} Nd7 {[%cal
Gd7e5]} 25. f4 Ra4 ({Every Najdorf/Boleslavsky player would also consider the
thematic} 25... g5 {which is designed to create new targets on the kingside.}
26. g3 {In order to keep control of the e5-square, White allows the opening
of the g-file.} ({In case of} 26. fxg5 Rg8 27. h4 h6 {White cannot hold his
kingside. The game might follow with} 28. gxh6 Rxg2+ 29. Re2 Rg3 $15 {when
White needs to play very dynamically in order to compensate for his static
problems. The pawns on the h-file a doomed. Black is already slightly better.})
26... gxf4 27. gxf4 Rg8 {Black can already combine threats on both wings. It
will be very difficult for White to handle this overextended position.}) 26.
Rb1 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5] Black starts preparing ...g7-g5. We cannot win the game
only on the queenside!} 27. Nc3 Ra3 28. Kc1 {[%cal Gc1b2] White is planning to
kick the rook back with Kb2. Black, however, is just in time to carry out the
thematic} g5 29. Kb2 Raa8 30. g3 gxf4 31. gxf4 Rg8 {Even though the position
remains objectively equal, it's difficult for White to control so many
vulnerable points. After some mutual inaccuracies, Black managed to win.} 32.
Rf2 Rg4 33. Be2 Rh4 34. Re1 Nf6 35. Bd1 Rc8 36. Kb3 Ba6 37. Be2 Rh3 38. Bf1
Bxc4+ 39. Bxc4 b5 40. e5 dxe5 41. fxe5 bxc4+ 42. Kb2 Nd7 0-1

