1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Nf3 Na6 7. g3 $1 {
This is the most challenging line connected with 6.Nf3. We can also say, that
nowadays this is probably White's top choice against the system with 4...c5.
He is planning to put long-term pressure on the long diagonal.  My
suggestion against this line would be} Nxc5 8. Bg2 Nce4 {[%cal Gb4c3] With his
last move, Black is planning to spoil White's pawn structure with ...Bxc3. In
this way, we get a static advantage that would compensate for the pressure
generated by the Catalan bishop.} 9. O-O {This is White's top choice.} ({
The alternative is} 9. Bd2 {In this case, however, Black does not experience
any problems on the road to equality. The most straightforward solution seems
to be} Nxd2 10. Nxd2 d5 {The bishop pair as well as the good central control
give Black nice play.} 11. O-O ({In case of} 11. a3 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 b6 13. cxd5
Bb7 $11 {the position is completely equal. Black even managed to win in the
game 0-1 (48) Lokotar, E (2330)-Barsov, A (2450) Haarlem 1994}) 11... d4 {
Even though Black has other decent continuations, gaining space in the centre
is by far the most ambitious approach.} 12. Nce4 e5 13. a3 Bxd2 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6
15. Qxd2 Re8 $132 {Black's central space advantage compensates for White's
queenside majority. The position is pretty balanced.}) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 d5 {
I find this continuation the easiest practical solution. The idea of
this move is to stabilize the e4-knight and to bring the light-squared bishop
into play. Despite getting rid of the doubled pawns, White needs to reckon
with the weakness on c3.} 11. Ng5 {The idea to exchange Black's most active
piece is quite logical.} ({Another straightforward attempt is} 11. cxd5 exd5
12. c4 {Having the bishop pair, White logically wants to open up the position.
On the other hand, Black can capitalize on the slightly exposed white queen. A
logical follow-up would be} Bf5 {[%cal Ga8c8]} 13. Nh4 Be6 14. cxd5 Qxd5 {
For the time being, the black knight is quite stable on e4. Black is ready to
proceed with ...Rc8 on the next move. Another important element in the
positions is the pawn structure. Given the possibility to create a distant
passed pawn on the queenside, Black would have good perspectives in the
endgame. Obviously, exchanging one of the white bishops is more than welcome
for us.} 15. Bb2 Rfc8 16. Qd1 {This game was played in a correspondence game.
White has nothing against playing an endgame.} ({An alternative is} 16. Qb1 {
This position occurred in the game ½-½ (25) Gretarsson, H (2550)-Wells, P 
(2419) Cardiff 2016. At this point, Black should have played} Qc4 17. Bxf6 Nxf6
18. Qxb7 Qxe2 $11 {with full equality.}) 16... Rc4 17. Nf3 Rac8 18. Nd4 Rb4
$132 {Black enjoyed sufficient counterplay in the game ½-½ (30)
Woelfelschneider,P (2277)-Gutierrez Dopino,J (2194) ICCF email 2017}) ({
Another way of challenging the knight is} 11. Nd2 {In my opinion, Black's most
precise reaction is} Nxd2 12. Bxd2 dxc4 {Black wins a pawn as compensation for
White's bishop pair. White's most ambitious way of handling the position is}
13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rab1 $1 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gb1b5] A very strong
move. White not only ties the c8-bishop to the defence of the b7-pawn but is
also planning to transfer the rook to the kingside by means of Rb5-h5.} Rb8 {
[%cal Gc8d7] Black is ready to proceed with ...Bd7.} 16. Rb5 e5 {Obviously, we
cannot allow Rh5 followed by the manoeuvre Qc1-h6.} 17. Qc1 {[%cal Gc1h6]} Kg7
18. f4 {This position occurred in the game Leenhouts, K (2483)-L'Ami, E (2636)
Dieren 2018. Now, the most precise reaction would have been} Re8 $1 {The
sequence} 19. fxe5 Rxe5 20. Qf4 Qe7 21. Rxe5 Qxe5 22. Qxe5 fxe5 23. Bd5 f6 24.
Bxc4 Bh3 $15 {leads to an endgame where Black is slightly better in view of
his superior structure.}) ({A possible move is} 11. Bf4 {just keeping the
tension. My suggestion would be} b6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ga8c8] Obviously, the
development of the light-squared bishop is our priority. If allowed, Black
will overtake the initiative by means of ...Ba6 and ...Rc8.} 12. cxd5 exd5 13.
Nd4 ({In case of} 13. c4 Ba6 14. cxd5 Rc8 15. Qb2 Nxd5 $132 {Black has decent
counterplay in view of his active minor pieces.}) 13... Ba6 14. f3 Nc5 $132 {
Black's better pawn structure provides sufficient compensation for the bishop
pair. The pawns on c3 and e2 are perfect targets.}) 11... Nd6 12. cxd5 exd5 13.
Ba3 {Even though Black is objectively fine, this move is a good practical
decision for a blitz game.} ({A high-profile game saw} 13. Rd1 {1-0 (24)
Mamedyarov, S (2761)-Topalov, V (2767) Beijing 2013. Now, Black should have
played} h6 14. Nh3 Bxh3 15. Bxh3 Re8 $132 {We are already familiar with this
pawn structure. Given the fact that there are good squares for the black
knights (e4 and c4), White's bishop pair is neutralized. The vulnerable
d5-pawn is compensated by the weakness on c3. Additionally, Black has
a promising play on the semi-open e-file.}) 13... Bf5 $2 {This natural move
turns out to be a tactical mistake.} ({Black should have gotten rid of the pin
by playing} 13... Re8 {when a possible follow-up would be} 14. Rfd1 Bf5 15. Qb3
h6 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nf3 Be4 $15 {I would even take Black here. Contrary to
the c3-pawn, Black's isolani is not a weakness at all.}) 14. Qb3 $6 {White
returns the favour.} ({After the energetic} 14. e4 $1 Bg6 (14... Nfxe4 15. Nxe4
Bxe4 16. Bxe4 $18) 15. Qb3 $16 {Black would have been in trouble.}) 14... h6
15. Nh3 Bxh3 16. Bxh3 Re8 17. e3 Nc4 18. Rad1 Qc7 19. Rd4 Ne4 20. Bc1 Rad8 21.
Rfd1 Na5 22. Qc2 Qxc3 23. Qxc3 Nxc3 24. R1d2 Nc4 25. Rc2 Ne4 26. Bg2 b5 27. a4
a6 28. axb5 axb5 29. f3 Nc5 30. e4 Nb3 31. Re2 Nxd4 0-1

