{[%evp 0,79,25,25,27,27,27,6,28,8,31,35,23,25,6,7,28,0,12,1,8,8,15,2,5,-1,21,
29,19,6,44,8,10,0,-17,-10,6,-13,20,-34,-34,-27,-23,-23,0,-10,0,-12,-10,-32,-28,
-56,-50,-71,-72,-88,-85,-135,-87,-94,-77,-90,-81,-96,-82,-80,-92,-154,-206,
-204,-168,-135,-63,-73,-42,0,0,-568,-514,-760,-781,-796] From this game, we
will start examining Black's Hedgehog setup. Hedgehog positions occur very
often in the line 4.Qc2 c5. In my comments on the following games, I will
present the most important must-know ideas. If you want to really go deeper
into the Hedgehog structure, I would suggest that you study the Modern Chess
camp "Understand the Hedgehog".} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 ({Our move order will be} 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 8. e3 Bb7 9. Be2
Be7 10. O-O {when we get exactly the position from the game.}) 2... e6 3. c4 b6
4. a3 Ba6 5. Qc2 Bb7 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Be7 10. Nc3 d6 {
The Hedgehog is already on the board. With a bishop on c1 and a pawn on e3,
White has chosen a rather modest setup. Even though the c4-pawn provides him
with a slight space advantage, White struggles to find constructive ideas in
this kind of structure. Usually, in Hedgehog positions, Black creates
counterplay either with ...d6-d5 or ...b6-b5. In most cases, the
advance ...d6-d5 will lead to simplifications and dry positions. Therefore,
the most ambitious plans are usually connected with the break ...b6-b5. An
important element in this structure (especially when resulting from 4.Qc2
Nimzo-Indian) is the pressure on c4. By putting pressure on the vulnerable
c4-pawn, Black tries to induce the advance b2-b3 which makes the c3-knight a
bit vulnerable. After b2-b3, both ...d6-d5 and ...b6-b5 are more effective.} {
The next couple of moves is logical and typical for the Hedgehog setup.} 11.
b3 Nbd7 12. Bb2 a6 13. Rfd1 Rc8 14. Rac1 Rc7 $1 {[%cal Gd8b8] A very deep move.
In Hedgehog structures, the queen usually belongs to b8. By putting the queen
on b8 we not only avoid all kinds of oppositions with the white rooks but also
support the advance ...b6-b5.} 15. Ne1 {[%cal Ge2f3] With this move, White is
planning to exchange the light-squared bishops via f3. In this way White
trades off his passive bishop but makes it easier for Black to carry out the
advance ...b6-b5.} Qb8 16. Bf3 Rfc8 {The opposition on the c-file can be very
annoying for White. The advance ...b6-b5 is already in the air.} 17. Qb1 b5 {
Remember this thematic break. After deflecting the c4-pawn, Black will build a
central superiority with the advance ...d6-d5. In the concrete position,
however, this advance is slightly premature in view of tactical nuances.} ({
Black could have started with a generally useful move such as} 17... h6 {
and play ...b6-b5 under favourable circumstances.}) ({The attempt to carry out
...b6-b5 after} 17... Bxf3 18. Nxf3 b5 {runs into} 19. cxb5 axb5 20. Nd4 $16 {
with an obvious advantage for White. Before playing ...b6-b5, you should pay
attention to 2 factors: 1) the potentially vulnerable b5-pawn 2) the weak
c6-square In this concrete case, White cannot easily hold the queenside.}) 18.
cxb5 axb5 19. Bxb7 $6 {Playing into Black's hand.} ({White should have played} 
19. Be2 {immediately targetng the problematic b5-pawn. The following sequence
seems to be pretty forced -} Bc6 20. Nc2 Qb7 21. Bf1 Ne5 22. Nd4 b4 23. axb4
Qxb4 24. Ncb5 Bxb5 25. Bxb5 $14 {White enjoys a slight advantage in view of
the bishop pair.}) 19... Qxb7 20. Nd3 d5 {Black has achieved his dream
position. His central control as well as harmoniously placed pieces make
provide him with a pleasant advantage. The next step is to provoke the advance
b3-b4 by attacking the a3-pawn. In this case, the c4-square will become a huge
weakness.} 21. Ne2 Ra8 {Played according to the plan. The idea is to provoke
the weakening b3-b4 advance.} 22. Rxc7 Qxc7 23. Nd4 Qb7 24. b4 $2 {This
positional mistake is untypical even for the early Riazantsev. Now, Black gets
access to the c4-square.} ({White should have played} 24. Nb4 $11 {with a
balanced position.}) 24... Ne4 25. Nb3 Nb6 $17 {White's vulnerable queenside
starts telling. Black is already strategically winning. Later on, the German
player managed to convert his advantage.} 26. f3 Nd6 27. Ndc5 Qc7 28. Qa1 Bf8
29. Nd4 Nbc4 30. Bc1 g6 31. Qc3 Bg7 32. Qd3 Qa7 33. Ndxe6 fxe6 34. Nxe6 Re8 35.
Nxg7 Kxg7 36. Qxd5 Nxe3 37. Bb2+ Kh6 38. Qd2 Ndc4 39. Bd4 Nxd2 40. Bxa7 0-1

