{[#] In this game, we shall see how Black should meet White's active setup
based on e2-e4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5
7. Nf3 b6 8. Bg5 ({Another very interesting attempt is} 8. e4 $5 {I remember
that I have analyzed this continuation for White back in 2005 during my
preparation for the Bulgarian championship. Therefore, revisiting all these
positions was very interesting for me.} Ng4 {In my opinion, this is the most
precise and restrictive choice.} 9. b4 {This interesting idea was tried by two
very strong GMs - Sjugirov and Hillarp Persson. Since White won both games,
we should take this move very seriously.} ({More positional attempt is} 9. Bg5
{In this case, Black should react with} f6 10. Bh4 Nc6 {With his last move,
Black shows his intention to fight for the d4-square. In order to do so, he
could play either the direct ...Nd4 or first exchange the f3-knight by means
of ...Nge5.} 11. b4 Be7 12. Bg3 {Pershin,D (2390)-Sammalvuo,T (2416) FIN-chT
1819 2018 (8.4) 1-0 This position occurred in the game} {At this point, Black
could have played} Bb7 13. Be2 Nge5 14. Nxe5 fxe5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc6d4,Gd7d6,
Ga7a5] The firm central control (especially of the d4-square) compensates for
White's better structure. Black can also consider undermining White's
queenside by means of ...a7-a5.}) ({Back in 2005, my preparation for White was
based on} 9. h3 $5 Nxf2 10. Rh2 {when White has two threats - b2-b4 and g2-g3
followed by Rxf2. A correspondence game, however, shows that after} d5 $1 {
Black is doing more than OK.} ({17 years ago, my main line was} 10... Qc7 $6
11. b4 Qg3 12. Ne2 Nd3+ 13. Kd2 Nxb4 14. Nxg3 Nxc2 15. Kxc2 Bb7 16. Bf4 $16 {
After analyzing this position, I have reached the conclusion that Black does
not have enough compensation for the piece.}) 11. b4 ({In the correspondence
game, White played} 11. g3 $2 {but after} dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Qc7 $1
14. Bf4 Bb7 $19 {Pitkaenen,J (2459)-Gerbich,V (2450) ICCF GMN/032 email 2011
0-1 it turns out that Black is winning.}) 11... dxe4 $1 {This is the point!}
12. bxc5 Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 exd3 14. Qf2 Nd7 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation
for the piece.}) 9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 Bh4 11. h3 {Sjugirov,S (2663)-Tregubov,P 
(2592) Wch Rapid St Petersburg 2018 (13) 1-0} {Now, Black's most precise
continuation is} Nf6 $1 $146 {The following sequence seems to be pretty forced
-} 12. Nxh4 Nh5 13. Nf3 Ng3+ 14. Kf2 Nxh1+ 15. Kg1 Ng3 16. Bd3 Nc6 17. Bf4 {
In return for the exchange, White managed to develop a dangerous initiative.
Now, Black should be ready to return the material by playing} Nh5 18. Bd6 Qf6
19. Rf1 Qh6 $132 {The position remains unclear but Black has a lot of
counterplay.}) 8... Bb7 9. e4 {This is by far the most aggressive and
ambitious choice.} ({Another aggressive setup is} 9. O-O-O {Since White is
planning to quickly expand by means of e2-e4-e5, Black does not have time to
build his classical Hedgehog setup. The best reaction is} Nc6 ({Some strong
players went for} 9... h6 {immediately clarifying the position of the
dark-squared bishop. Nevertheless, after} 10. h4 {it's not easy to handle
Black's position over the board. Even though the move h2-h4 has never been
played so far, it's a standard approach in such positions.}) 10. e4 h6 $1 {
We play this move only after e2-e4!!! The reason is that White cannot
sacrifice the bishop since the e4-pawn closes the way of the queen.} 11. Bh4 {
White has nothing better than going for this retreat.} ({In case of} 11. Bf4 {
the most precise reaction is} Nh5 {In this line, we should always drive the
bishop away from the diagonal h2-b8.} 12. Bd2 Qb8) ({Taking the pawn with} 11.
Bxf6 $2 Qxf6 12. Rxd7 {is a bad idea. The strong bishop pair as well as the
superior development provide Black with fantastic compensation for the pawn.
For instance, after} Rab8 13. Kb1 Rfd8 14. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $17 {Black has a huge
advantage. He is ready to follow with ...Nd4 on the next move.}) ({It's very
important that} 11. h4 $2 {loses by force -} hxg5 12. hxg5 Ng4 13. e5 {The
only way to play for compensation.} g6 14. Qe4 {Planning to bring the queen to
the kingside. It turns out, however, that White does not have time for this
operation.} ({In case of} 14. Ne4 {Black has} Nd4 $1 {when we are just in time
to eliminate White's dangerous central knight.} 15. Nf6+ ({The alternative} 15.
Nxd4 {does not help either. After} Bxe4 16. Qxe4 Nxf2 17. Qh4 Nxh1 18. Bd3 Nf2
19. Qxf2 Qxg5+ $19 {Black is winning.}) 15... Nxf6 16. Nxd4 Ne4 $19 {White
does not have any compensation for the piece.}) 14... Ncxe5 $1 {An elegant
refutation of White's idea.} 15. Qxb7 Nxf3 16. Qxf3 Qxg5+ 17. Kb1 Nxf2 $19 {
Black is clearly winning.}) 11... Be7 12. e5 {The most logical attempt.
Against everything else, Black will proceed with ...Na5 and ...Rc8.} Ne8 {
Now, this move works very well for Black. Without the inclusion of the moves ..
.h7-h6 Bh4, White could have now obtained a huge advantage with h2-h4 or Be3.}
13. Bxe7 {After the exchange of the bishops, White will be trying to make use
of the weak d6-square.} ({A serious alternative is} 13. Bg3 {Having a space
advantage, White avoids exchanging pieces. On the other hand, this bishop is
rather passive on g3. Besides not participating in the attack, it stands in
the way of the kingside pawns.} {Black should play} a6 $1 {[%cal Gb6b5]
immediately creating a queenside counterplay based on the advance ...b6-b5.}
14. h4 b5 $1 {Black will play this move against pretty much everything.} 15.
Ng5 {This is the point of h2-h4. It turns out, however, that Black has enough
defensive resources.} ({Taking the pawn with} 15. cxb5 axb5 16. Bxb5 {is very
dangerous. Black can play} Nc7 17. Bd3 Na5 $17 {[%cal Gc7d5] with ...Nd5 to
follow. White's position is very dangerous in view of his vulnerable king.})
15... hxg5 16. hxg5 Bxg5+ 17. Kb1 f5 18. exf6 Bxf6 $15 {In my opinion (and
according to the computer), White's compensation is not fully sufficient.})
13... Qxe7 14. Qd3 Rd8 15. Ne4 {Serper,G (2574)-Zhang,Z (2636) Cap d'Agde-B
rapid 2000 (1) 0-1 This position was reached in the game} {At this point,
Black should have played} f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 17. Nd6 Na5 {with a slightly better
position. It's clear that the d6-knight is unstable. Black's immediate threat
is ...Bxf3 followed by ...Ne8. Also, the c4-pawn might become vulnerable in
some lines.}) 9... Be7 ({In my opinion. better move order is} 9... h6 {
immediately clarifying the position of the bishop.} 10. Bh4 Be7 {with ...Nh5
to follow.}) 10. Rd1 h6 11. Bh4 {With this move, White transposes to the main
line.} ({Black's imprecise move order gave White the additional option of} 11.
Bf4) 11... Nh5 {This is a key move in our strategy. Never forget it.} 12. Bxe7
{The most logical continuation.} (12. Bg3 {can be met by} Nc6 {The move ...Nc6
is usually connected with ...Rc8 and possibly ...Na5. Note that when our pawn
is still on d7, the advance ...f7-f5 is also always on the table.} ({A sharp
alternative is} 12... f5 $5) 13. Be2 ({White is not ready for the ambitious} 
13. e5 {Sokolov,I (2690)-Kurajica,B (2540) Sarajevo Bosnia 34th 2004 (8) 1-0
which occurred in the game} {At this point, Black could have played} Qb8 {
targeting the e5-pawn. A possible follow-up could be} 14. Rxd7 Bc8 15. Rd1 Nxg3
16. hxg3 Nxe5 $17 {Black has an obvious advantage in view of his bishop pair.})
({The natural} 13. Bd6 {is not attractive at all. As often happens in this
structure, Black can ignore the blockade on d6.} Bxd6 14. Rxd6 {Szoen, D (2452)
-Gasanov, E (2498) Najdorf Memorial op-A 2007 (9) 1-0 This position occurred in
the game} {At this point, Black can opt for the typical} f5 {when after} 15. e5
g5 $17 {the kingside expansion cannot be underestimated. The e5-pawn is
already in danger. In case of necessity, we can always protect the d7-pawn by
means of ...Rf7.}) 13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 Rc8 {Black is ready for his counterplay
based on ...Na5. Note that establishing a blockade by means of} 15. Nb5 a6 16.
Nd6 {is again not dangerous for Black. After} Bxd6 17. Rxd6 Na5 $132 {[%csl
Rc4,Re4][%cal Gc8c2] We have sufficient counterplay in view of White's
overextended position.}) 12... Qxe7 13. Be2 {This natural move is the most
common continuation.} ({The main alternative is} 13. Qd2 {putting pressure on
d7 and taking the f4-square under control. The drawback of this move is that
White neglects the development. Once again, Black can try the thematic} f5 {
which is the most aggressive reaction.} ({The alternative} 13... d5 {is
completely possible as well.}) 14. Qe3 {White's best reaction allowing him not
to get worse.} ({After} 14. Bd3 {Black can use the opposition along the e-file
by means of} fxe4 15. Bxe4 d5 {The following sequence is a good illustration
of the possibilities in this position.} 16. Bb1 dxc4 17. Qc2 Rf5 $1 18. Nd4 Nf4
19. Nxf5 exf5+ 20. Ne2 c3 21. bxc3 Nd7 $17 {Black has fantastic compensation
for the exchange in view of his better development and the vulnerable white
king.}) 14... fxe4 15. Nxe4 d6 16. Nxd6 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nd7 $132 {White's
vulnerable king provides Black with an excellent counterplay.}) 13... Nf4 14.
O-O f5 $1 {Remember this typical idea! You should always consider it in
positions with a pawn on d7.} 15. e5 $2 {This move leads to a very difficult
position for White. In this structure, White's e5-pawn is often quite
vulnerable.} ({More promising would have been} 15. Rfe1 {when after} fxe4 16.
Nxe4 Na6 $132 {The position is balanced.}) 15... g5 $1 {[%cal Ge7g7] This very
strong move practically refutes White's entire concept. Besides gaining
kingside space, Black is ready to increase the pressure on e5 by means of
simple moves such as ...Qg7 and ...Nc6.} 16. Qd2 Qg7 17. h3 Nxe2+ $6 {This is
an inaccuracy. The f4-knight is way too strong to be exchanged for the useless
bishop. Since the rest of the game is not instructive for us, I will the
remaining moves without comment.} ({Black should have played} 17... Nc6 18.
Qxd7 Rf7 19. Qd2 Nxe5 $19 {with a winning attack. Ideas like ...Nxg2 and ...
g5-g4 are always in the air.}) 18. Qxe2 g4 19. hxg4 fxg4 20. Nd4 Bf3 21. Qe3
Bxd1 22. Rxd1 Nc6 23. Nxc6 dxc6 24. Rd6 Rae8 25. Ne4 Qxe5 26. Qxh6 Re7 27. Qg6+
Rg7 28. Qxe6+ Qxe6 29. Rxe6 Rd8 30. Rxc6 Rd1+ 31. Kh2 g3+ 0-1

