{[%evp 0,138,25,24,24,6,13,16,24,2,15,2,8,19,-9,23,8,7,18,15,15,7,-6,-5,43,19,
19,19,19,16,29,9,15,5,23,19,19,15,26,15,29,11,22,21,22,19,34,13,2,10,9,4,0,-4,
6,-15,-6,-17,-34,-29,-36,-51,-73,-77,-70,-80,-28,-30,-43,-26,-26,-43,-26,-26,
-12,-76,-86,-132,-139,-213,-211,-208,-220,-213,-132,-163,-174,-176,-178,-201,
-190,-208,-191,-188,-205,-190,-164,-191,-171,-208,-194,-189,-186,-175,-140,
-136,-136,-256,-254,-298,-190,-252,-246,-251,-255,-253,-251,-258,-254,-284,
-259,-404,-338,-351,-342,-383,-335,-324,-332,-337,-320,-2120,-2809,-2237,-3063,
-29993,-29994,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29998] Now, we shall take a look at one of
my blitz games. Despite the fast time control, I handled the Hedgehog in an
instructive way.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 {
This is considered to be White's main move. By forcing ...Bxc5, White prevents
Black from taking on c5 with a knight.} Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 {This move indicates
Black's intention to play a Hedgehog type of position. If allowed, he will
play proceed with ...Bb7, followed by ...Be7, ...a7-a6, and ...d7-d6. This
setup works very well almost always when the white bishop is not on f4.  White
has 2 main moves in this position - 8.Bg5 and 8.Bf4.} 8. Bg5 {This is the less
dangerous setup. Compared to 8.Bf4, now the game is more positional.} Bb7 9. e3
{With this modest move, White can hardly fight for an advantage.} ({Later, we
will also deal with} 9. e4 {which is definitely more ambitious.}) 9... h6 {
I always prefer to clarify the position of the white dark-squared bishop.
Black usually tries to exchange pieces by means of ...Be7 followed by ...Nh5.
With a bishop on g5, we should always reckon with the idea of h2-h4.} 10. Bh4
Be7 11. Be2 Nh5 {This is a key move in Black's strategy. The exchange of the
bishops will reduce the impact of White's space advantage. Also, given the
fact that Black will opt for a Hedgehog type of structure, he needs to prevent
White from putting his bishop on the diagonal h2-b8.} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. O-O Nf6
14. Rfd1 d6 {Finally, we have reached the Hedgehog structure. Apart from
attacking the d6-pawn, White does not have constructive ideas. As we will see,
however, Black has enough resources to defend this pawn.} 15. Nd4 Rd8 16. Bf3 {
Just like in the game Riazantsev - Hoffman, White goes for the exchange of the
light-squared bishops. Hence, Black will now be trying to carry out the
advance ...b6-b5.} a6 17. Rac1 Bxf3 18. Nxf3 Nbd7 19. Nd4 Rdc8 {Given the fact
that in the future Black is planning to execute the advance ...b6-b5, the
b8-square should be reserved for the other rook.} 20. Qe2 Ne5 {Another
important move. As we have already discussed, in this pawn structure, Black
often tries to provoke the advance b2-b3. In this way, the c3-knight becomes
more vulnerable.} 21. b3 Qb7 {This is the perfect spot for the queen. Besides
being active, from this position, the queen also supports the advance ...b6-b5.
White decided to radically prevent Black's idea by playing} 22. a4 {This move,
however, makes the queenside even more vulnerable. Now, Black is already
interested in opening the position up by means of ...d6-d5. Therefore, I played
} Rd8 {At this point, my opponent decided to force the transition into an
endgame by means of} 23. Nf3 Nxf3+ 24. Qxf3 Qxf3 25. gxf3 {We have the same
pawn structure as in the game Marta Bartlel - Igor Kovalenko. After making
sure that the d6-pawn is sufficiently protected, Black can fix the kingside
structure by means of ...g7-g5. Later on, the knight can be transferred to e5.
On the other hand, White does not have any constructive ideas.} Kf8 26. f4 ({
Probably a better idea would have been to fight for a draw in a rook endgame
by playing} 26. Ne4) 26... Ke7 27. Kf1 g5 $1 {From the previous game we know
that when White's kingside structure is compromised. the pawn play is very
effective. Besides reducing White's central control, with my last move, I try
to secure the e5-square for the knight.} 28. fxg5 hxg5 29. Rd4 Rac8 30. e4 $6 {
Positionally speaking, this move is dubious since it weakens the dark squares
on the kingside.} Ng4 31. Kg2 Ne5 32. Rcd1 Rc6 {Now, the d8-rook is free to
operate on the kingside.} 33. h3 Rg8 34. Ne2 Rb8 {Reminding White that the
threat of ...b6-b5 is real.} 35. Nc3 Ng6 {Now, the f4-square might become an
issue.} 36. Ne2 b5 $1 {Finally, Black manages to execute this thematic advance.
We can see a classical application of the principle of two weaknesses.} 37.
axb5 axb5 38. Ra1 bxc4 39. Ra7+ Kf6 40. Rxc4 Rxc4 41. bxc4 Rc8 {This move is
enough for a winning advantage.} ({Even more precise would have been} 41...
Nh4+ 42. Kh2 Rb2 $19 {when Black is winning on the spot.}) 42. Rd7 Rxc4 43.
Rxd6 Rxe4 $19 {Black is winning. Later on, I managed to convert my advantage.}
44. Ng1 Nh4+ 45. Kf1 Ra4 46. Rd1 Ra3 47. Re1 e5 48. Rb1 Kf5 49. Rd1 f6 50. Rb1
Ng6 51. Ne2 Rxh3 52. Ng3+ Kg4 53. Rb4+ Nf4 54. Rb6 Rh6 55. Ra6 e4 56. Kg1 Kf3
57. Ra3+ Nd3 58. Nf1 Rh4 59. Nh2+ Kf4 60. f3 f5 61. fxe4 fxe4 62. Ra4 Rh3 63.
Nf1 Ne5 64. Nd2 Nf3+ 65. Kg2 Rh2+ 66. Kf1 Nxd2+ 67. Kg1 Nf3+ 68. Kf1 Kg3 69.
Ra2 Rh1+ {0-1 Black wins.} 0-1

