{From this model game, we start dealing with White's most dangerous system - 8.
Bf4. This example, shows how Black should handle the position when White does
not play in a very ambitious way.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5.
dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5 7. Nf3 b6 8. Bf4 {The bishop is very actively placed on f4.
Therefore, it's more difficult for Black to build his Hedgehog setup. Instead,
after quickly developing the queenside, he should go for an active piece play.
Moves like ...Bb7, ...Nc6 and ...Rc8 are always on the agenda. Another
common idea is ...Nh5 which is designed to chase the bishop away from the
diagonal h2-b8. Note that under favourable circumstances, Black can return to
his Hedgehog setup.} Bb7 9. Rd1 {White usually includes this active move. The
rook is very well placed on d1 in this structure. The only slight drawback is
that plans with 0-0-0 are no longer on the table.} ({The immediate} 9. e3 {
is quite playable as well. Now, Black's typical reaction is} Nh5 {Once again,
we see this important move.} 10. Bg3 ({Another interesting continuation is} 10.
Bg5 Be7 {After exchanging the dark-squared bishops, Black can go for his usual
Hedgehog setup. White, however, can play} 11. h4 {Maletin,P (2584)-Vitiugov,N 
(2720) RUS-chT 18th 2011 (10) 0-1 planning to castle long. This position
occurred in the game} {Now, instead of the game continuation 11...h6, my
suggestion would be} Nf6 {when} 12. O-O-O {can be met by} Nc6 $132 {[%cal
Ga8c8,Gc6a5] Black is ready for his usual counterplay based on ...Rc8, and ...
Na5.}) 10... Be7 {In my opinion, this is the simplest continuation. Black is
going to take on g3 when White has no longer attacking chances on the kingside.
Meanwhile, he is ready to prepare the queenside counterplay with ...Nc6
followed by ...Rc8.} 11. Rd1 h6 $1 {Another typical move in this setup.
Besides taking the g5-square under control, Black makes sure that after the
eventual ...Nxg3, the recapture hxg3 will not come with a tempo.} 12. Be2 Nc6
13. Rd2 {[%cal Gc2d1] White is planning to increase the pressure on d7 by
means of Qd1. So far, we have seen that the defence of this pawn is never a
big problem for Black.} Rc8 14. Qd1 Nxg3 15. hxg3 ({Of course, after} 15. Rxd7
$4 Nxh1 16. Rxd8 Rfxd8 $19 {Black has decisive material advantage.}) 15... Nb8
{Suddenly, it turns out that White does not have constructive ideas. At the
same time, Black is going to obtain a decent version of the Hedgehog by
playing ...a7-a6 and ...d7-d6.} 16. g4 {This is a bit overambitious. White
cannot execute g4-g5 under favourable circumstances.} ({As usual, the blockade
on d6 is not solid. For instance, after} 16. Nb5 a6 17. Nd6 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 Qc7 {
[%cal Gb7d5] The d6-rook is vulnerable and White should reckon with the threat
of ...Bd5. It's important that} 19. Qd4 {attacking b6 is not dangerous in
view of} Nc6 20. Qd2 Rfd8 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge6e5,Gc6d4] Once again, White should
pay attention to the d6-rook. Black has two main ideas - ...e6-e5 followed by .
..Nd4 and ...Ne7 followed by either ...Nd5 or ...Bd5.}) 16... a6 17. Qb1 Qc7 {
Black's plan is clear. He will follow with ...d7-d6 and ...Nd7. Then a
possible idea would be ...Bxf3 followed by ...Ne5. As usual, the c4-pawn turns
out to be pretty vulnerable.} 18. Bd3 $6 {This move is just a waste of time.}
Rfd8 19. Rh5 Bf6 20. Rc2 {After this passive move, White is clearly worse.} ({
Instead, he should have preferred the active} 20. g5 {Nevertheless, after} Bxf3
21. gxf3 Bxg5 22. f4 Bf6 $15 {White does not have enough compensation for the
pawn.}) 20... d6 $17 {Riazantsev,A (2714)-Landa,K (2646) FRA-chT Top 12 2012 
(1.1) 1/2-1/2 Black has a huge advantage. The next move is ...Nd7. Afterwards,
he can proceed with ...Bxf3 followed by ...Ne5. The c4-pawn is a huge problem.}
) 9... Nc6 10. e3 Nh5 11. Bg5 {When White does not have the option of castling
long, this move is harmless.} ({In case of} 11. Bg3 {Black goes for the usual}
Be7 {Once again, the aggressive} 12. Nb5 {is not dangerous.} ({After} 12. Be2
h6 {we transpose to the game Riazantsev - Landa.}) 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 h6 14.
g4 {This active move is not threatening at all. Unfortunately for White, g4-g5
never works. Black can start his queenside play with} Rc8 15. Qd2 {Van Wely, L 
(2625)-Banikas, H (2582) EU-ch 10th Budva 2009 (4) 1/2-1/2 This position
occurred in the game} {Now, Black could have played the thematic} Na5 {
immediately putting pressure on c4. A possible follow-up would be} 16. Qxd7 Bf6
(16... a6 {is possible as well.}) 17. Nxa7 Qxd7 18. Rxd7 Ra8 19. Nb5 Bxb2 $132
{Black's bishop pair and better development provide plenty of compensation for
the pawn.}) 11... Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {I played this move in order to get a
fighting position. At this point, I was planning to proceed with ...Rac8
followed by ...Na5.} ({Another option is} 12... Nxe7 {[%cal Gh5f6,Ga8c8,Gd7d5]
when Black manages to equalize without effort. In this case, he can prepare ...
d7-d5 by playing ...Rc8 and ...Nf6.}) 13. Be2 Rac8 14. Qb1 Nf6 15. O-O Na5 {
I really like playing against the c4-pawn in this kind of position. Now, White
should accept a passive position.} 16. Nd2 Rfd8 {Black activates his pieces
and keeps all the options open. Depending on the position, he can play either .
..d7-d6 or ...d7-d5.} 17. b4 Nc6 ({Another option would have been} 17... Nxc4
18. Nxc4 d5 19. Nxb6 axb6 20. Rc1 {when the position is objectively equal.})
18. Nde4 d6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Ne4 Qg6 {Once again, I decided to go for a more
complicated position. Since the e4-knight is vulnerable, he should calculate
some lines.} ({The typical Hedgehog style of play with} 20... Qe7 {was
possible as well. Black is ready to make use of White's overextended queenside
by means of ...Ne5.}) 21. f3 $6 {This move is an inaccuracy since it weakens
White's position.} ({White should have calculated} 21. Rxd6 $1 {when Black has
nothing better than going for the following forced sequence -} Nd4 22. Rxd4
Rxd4 23. Nf6+ Qxf6 24. exd4 Rd8 25. Rd1 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 Qxd4 $11 {with an equal
endgame.}) 21... d5 ({Even better would have been} 21... Ne5 22. Rd4 Bxe4 23.
Qxe4 Qxe4 24. Rxe4 Nc6 {[%csl Re4] The restricted e4-rook will pose serious
problems for White.}) 22. Ng3 $2 {This is already a mistake.} ({Better would
have been} 22. cxd5 exd5 23. Ng3 Qxb1 24. Rxb1 d4 25. Rfd1 $11 {with equality.}
) 22... Qxb1 23. Rxb1 d4 $15 {Black's advantage is obvious. Later, I managed
to convert it into a full point.} 24. exd4 Nxd4 25. Rfd1 Ba6 26. b5 Bb7 27. Bd3
Kf8 28. Kf2 e5 29. Nf5 Ne6 30. Be2 g6 31. Nd6 Rc7 32. Nxb7 Rxd1 33. Rxd1 Rxb7
34. Ke3 Ke7 35. g3 Rd7 36. Rxd7+ Kxd7 37. Kd3 Kd6 38. Kc3 Kc5 39. Bd1 Nd4 40.
Kd3 f5 41. h3 Nxf3 42. Bxf3 e4+ 43. Bxe4 fxe4+ 0-1

