{[%evp 0,67,25,13,0,-13,-24,-23,4,-25,17,-7,-2,32,3,3,27,27,14,14,36,3,19,40,
64,79,76,76,83,51,81,68,73,44,67,60,55,53,53,34,95,76,76,70,65,12,8,-8,107,
-206,26,0,31,15,33,8,-28,-4,0,14,149,165,309,277,307,293,293,468,1058,341] Now,
we shall take a look at White's most aggressive ways of handling the system
with 8.Bf4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 c5 5. dxc5 O-O 6. a3 Bxc5 7.
Nf3 b6 8. Bf4 Bb7 9. Rd1 Nc6 10. b4 {Combined with e2-e4, this is probably
White's most ambitious system against our line.} ({An important alternative is
} 10. e4 {Now, you should know the thematic} Ne7 $1 {[%cal Ge7g6] The knight
is heading to g6.} 11. h3 {At the cost of an important tempo, White makes room
for the bishop.} ({Note that} 11. b4 $6 {will be met by} Ng6 12. Bg3 Be7 $132 {
[%cal Gf6h5,Ga7a5] when White's position is overextended. Black has two
ideas at his disposal - ...Nh5 or ...a7-a5. Very often, he can combine them.})
11... Ng6 12. Bh2 Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] A typical idea for such positions. White
wants to make use of his superior development by employing the advance ...
f7-f5. This advance is quite characteristic for positions with a pawn on d7.}
13. Qd2 {White not only takes the f4-square under control but also puts
pressure on d7. This position occurred in the game 0-1 (41) Bareev, E (2721)
-Ivanchuk,V (2710) Rethymno 2003 CBM 098. Now, Black's most energetic reaction
would have been} f5 $5 {sacrificing the d7-pawn in order to create dynamic
counterplay.} 14. Qxd7 ({After} 14. exf5 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Qf6 $1 $17 {White is in
danger in view of his vulnerable king. Black is ready to follow with ...Nh4.
Obviously, the knight cannot be taken because of ...Qxf3.}) 14... Qxd7 15. Rxd7
fxe4 16. Rxb7 exf3 17. gxf3 Nh4 $132 {Once again, Black has excellent
counterplay.}) ({White's development is not sufficient for the attacking} 10.
Nb5 $6 {Black's most energetic response would be} e5 11. Bg3 {This position
was reached in the game 0-1 Tomaszewski, R-Kengis, E/Moscow 1986/EXT 2002 (36).}
(11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 Bxf2+ 13. Kxf2 Ng4+ 14. Kg1 Nxe5 $132) (11. Bxe5 $6
Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Re8 13. Nd3 Ne4 $17) {And now correct was} 11... e4 12. Ng5 e3 $1
{After this strong move, the white king will never find a safe haven. The
game might continue} 13. fxe3 Re8 14. Nc7 Rc8 15. Nxe8 Qxe8 $19 {when Black's
compensation is sufficient for decisive advantage. White can never solve the
problems related to the vulnerable king and inferior development.}) 10... Be7
11. e4 {In my opinion, this position is critical for the evaluation of the
entire variation. White managed to grab a lot of space. He is now planning to
kick us away from the board. On the other hand, White's position is already
overextended. Also, Black enjoys superior development.} a5 $6 {This thematic
advance is premature now.} ({After many hours of work on this position, I have
reached the conclusion that Black's most precise continuation is} 11... Rc8 $5
{[%cal Gc8c2] Besides creating an annoying opposition along the c-file, Black
is planning to proceed with ...Nh5 followed by ...Qc7.} 12. Be2 {This simple
developing move is actually very challenging. If Black does not obtain
counterplay immediately, he will be doomed to passivity.} ({The ambitious} 12.
e5 {is not dangerous because White is still underdeveloped. Black's typical
way of challenging White's central superiority is} Nh5 13. Be3 f6 14. Qd2 {
We know that in this line Black has sufficient resources to deal with the
pressure on d7.} ({In case of} 14. Bd3 $6 {Black gladly parts with the h7-pawn
in order to obtain a central superiority. For instance, after} Nxe5 15. Nxe5
fxe5 16. Bxh7+ Kh8 17. Be4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 Nf6 $132 {The vulnerable c4-pawn even
makes Black's position practically preferable.}) ({Harmless is} 14. exf6 Nxf6
$132 {when Black has plenty of counterplay in view of his superior development
and White's overextended queenside.}) ({The move} 14. Qd3 {is similar to 14.
Qd2. Black should react in the same fashion -} Nb8 15. Be2 fxe5 16. Nxe5 Qc7 $1
{A key move in Black's strategy. It turns out that White does not have
a comfortable way of supporting the e5-knight.} 17. Ng4 Nf4 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 $132 {
The bishop pair as well as the superior development provides Black with a nice
counterplay.}) 14... Nb8 15. Nb5 {Ambitious but risky since White completely
neglects the development.} ({A more solid alternative would be} 15. Be2 fxe5
16. O-O ({Just like in the line with 14.Qd3, White can play} 16. Nxe5 {Black
will react in the same way -} Qc7 $1 17. Ng4 Nf4 18. Bxf4 Qxf4 19. Qxf4 Rxf4
$15 {After the exchange of the queens, Black enjoys a slight advantage in view
of his powerful bishops.}) 16... Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Rxf3 18. gxf3 Qf8 $44 {with 
excellent compensation for the exchange.}) 15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 a5 {Black is
playing on the entire board. With his last move, he reminds White about his
vulnerable kingside. Even though the position is dynamically balanced, White
vulnerable king and spoiled pawn structure make Black's play easier. For
instance, after} 17. Nd6 axb4 18. Nxc8 Qxc8 19. axb4 Nc6 $132 {Black has 
excellent compensation for the exchange.}) ({In case of} 12. Bd3 {Black
manages to obtain a favourable version of the Hedgehog by means of} Nh5 $1 {
Remember this thematic idea. It's crucial to drive the bishop away from the
diagonal h2-b8.} 13. Be3 Qc7 14. O-O Nf6 15. h3 {This position occurred in the
game ½-½ Kouatly,B-Hjartarson,J/Reykjavik 1993/CBM 035 (17)} {Now, Black
could have played} d6 16. Rc1 Qb8 $11 {with comfortable equality. Since
White has already played b2-b4, Black can consider putting pressure on c4 by
means of ...Nd7 followed by ...Nce5. At the same time, White does not have
a constructive plan.}) ({The idea to secure the f4-bishop by playing} 12. h3 {
is logical but slow. In this case, we should immediately undermine White's
queenside with} a5 13. b5 Na7 $132 {It's not so easy for White to keep his
overextended position under control. The pawns on e4, a3, and c4 are clear
targets. Also, at any moment, White should reckon with the advance ...d7-d5.})
12... Nh5 $1 {Without this typical move, Black's entire concept simply does
not work.} 13. Be3 Qc7 {Black is ready to go for his usual Hedgehog setup
after ...d7-d6. White's only way of challenging Black's construction is} 14.
Nb5 {It turns out, however, that after} Qb8 $1 15. Rxd7 Nf6 {Everything works
fine for Black.} 16. Rd2 $6 {After this inaccuracy, already Black is the one
who is fighting for an advantage.} ({White should have played} 16. Bf4 {when the
following sequence seems to be pretty logical -} Qxf4 17. Rxb7 Rfe8 18. Nxa7
Nxa7 19. Rxa7 Qxe4 20. Qxe4 Nxe4 21. Bd3 Nd6 22. Ke2 e5 $132 {In this endgame,
Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 16... a5 $1 {Black immediately seizes the
opportunity to undermine the queenside.} 17. bxa5 $2 {This is already a huge
mistake.} ({White should have played} 17. e5 {Nevertheless, after} Nxe5 18.
Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qb2 Qf5 $132 {I would still prefer Black.}) 17... Nxa5 18. e5 Ng4
19. Nd6 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Rc5 ({Another possibility would have been} 20... Bxf3 $5
21. gxf3 Rc6 {with an obvious advantage.}) 21. Nxb7 Qxb7 $17 {Black had more
than enough compensation for the missing pawn in the game ½-½ (23) Gladyszev,
O (2455)-Okrugin,S (2350)/Tula 2007/EXT 2008. Actually, White is already in
trouble.}) 12. b5 Na7 13. Be2 {[%csl Ra7] Now, Black does not have a comfortable
way of bringing the a7-knight into play.} Nh5 ({The pawn is untouchable. After
} 13... Bxa3 $2 14. e5 Ne8 15. Ng5 g6 16. h4 $18 {White has a winning attack.})
14. Bc1 Qc7 15. O-O d6 16. Nd4 Nf6 17. f4 $18 {[%cal Gf4f5] White is
strategically winning. His next move is going to be f4-f5, provoking the
weakening advance ...e6-e5. Later on, Gurevich won the game, not without
adventures.} Nd7 18. f5 e5 19. f6 exd4 20. fxe7 Rfe8 21. Rxd4 Rxe7 22. Qd2 Nc5
23. Rxd6 Bxe4 24. Nd5 $4 Bxd5 $4 (24... Qxd6 25. Nf6+ Qxf6 26. Rxf6 gxf6 $17)
25. Qxd5 Rae8 26. Bg4 Re5 27. Rd7 Nxd7 28. Qxf7+ Kh8 29. Bxd7 Qc5+ 30. Kh1 Ra8
31. Bb2 Rg5 32. h4 Rg3 33. Be5 Rg6 34. h5 1-0

