{[%evp 0,80,25,25,27,15,15,15,25,-9,9,6,-7,-11,26,33,66,66,65,42,19,42,36,33,
24,10,36,39,25,34,34,40,56,42,28,5,36,22,13,28,30,30,0,0,-13,-14,-31,-25,-7,
-108,-159,-159,-129,-159,-159,-212,-274,-274,-359,-311,-324,-349,-349,-313,
-359,-355,-355,-352,-363,-427,-457,-493,-307,-356,-316,-375,-376,-458,-446,
-482,-436,-450,-442] At the beginning, we shall take a look at several
examples where White tries to establish a knight on d6. Let's start with a
game I am especially proud of. My opponent is the famous Serbian GM Ivan
Ivanisevic. With a nice play, I managed to score an important win.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5
9. Qd2 {By keeping the queen on the d-file, White prepares the manoeuvre Nb5-d6.
The dark-squared bishop will be developed via the a3-square. On the downside,
with his last move, White allows the useful ...b7-b6 advance. Therefore, the
main move is 9.Qf3.} b6 10. Nb5 O-O 11. Nd6 {White managed to execute his idea.
He is now ready to follow up with Bg2. On the other hand, the d6-knight is not as
dangerous as it might seem at the first glance. In this structure, Black
usually manages to play around the knight.} Bb7 $1 {A very important move. We
are never afraid of giving the light-squared bishop for the d6-knight. In the
event of such an exchange, Black can easily put pressure on the c4-pawn.} 12.
f3 ({After} 12. Nxb7 Nxb7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5,Ga8c8] Black already enjoys a
considerable advantage. He can put pressure on c4 by means of simple moves
such as ...Nc6, ...Rc8, and ...Nca5.}) 12... Bc6 13. Ba3 Nba6 {With his last
two moves, Black managed to completely stabilize the queenside. He can already
consider playing in the centre and on the kingside by means of ...f7-f5
followed by ...e6-e5.} 14. Bg2 f5 15. O-O e5 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf8f6] Black is
playing around the "dangerous" d6-knight. Besides that, we can already
question the stability of this knight with simple moves such as ...Qe7 and ...
Rf6.} 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. f4 e4 $1 {This is the right approach. We should prevent
the exchange of the bishops. Otherwise, White will get access to the important
d5-square.} 18. Qd4 Rf6 19. Rd2 Raf8 {[%cal Gf6h6,Gf8f6] Black is already
planning to double his rooks along the 6th rank. The next two moves will be ...
Rh6 and ...Rff6.} {Making sure that Black will never have the idea of ...e4-e3.
Now, however, the d3-square is getting vulnerable.} 20. e3 ({During the game,
I was planning to answer} 20. Nb5 {with} d6 {when the b5-knight is completely
out of play.}) 20... Rh6 21. Rfd1 $6 {Playing into Black's hand.} ({Better
would have been} 21. Nb5 {when Black should play the undesirable} Ra8 {with a
balanced position.} ({With the rook being on h6,} 21... d6 $2 {is not good
since after} 22. Nxd6 {the f5-pawn is not sufficiently protected. For instance,
the move ...Rd8 will be answered by Nxf5.})) 21... Rff6 $1 {Black finally
achieved his goal. White should remove the knight from the d6-square.} 22. Nb5
{White admits the failure of his strategy based on Nd6.} ({In case of} 22. Nc8
{I was planning to proceed with} Qf8 23. Nxa7 Ba4 $17 {when Black is winning
an exchange. The thing is that White cannot move his d1-rook in view of ...Rd6.
}) 22... d6 23. Bf1 Re6 {[%cal Gc5d3] Black is preparing the jump ...Nd3.} 24.
Rg2 $2 {A mistake in a losing position.} Nd3 $19 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black is
already winning. His next move is going to be ...Nac5. Obviously, White cannot
eliminate the d3-knight because the black bishop will become a monster. Later
on, I managed to convert my advantage without difficulties.} 25. g4 fxg4 26. f5
Ref6 27. Rxd3 exd3 28. Rxg4 Nc5 29. Bxc5 bxc5 30. Qxd3 Qe5 31. Rf4 g5 32. Rf2
Be4 33. Qe2 a5 34. Nd4 cxd4 35. exd4 Qe8 36. Bg2 Bc6 37. Bxc6 Qxc6 38. Qe7 Qc8
39. Qe4 Rh4 40. Qd5+ Kg7 0-1

