{In this game, we shall see what happens when White exchanges his knight for
the b7-bishop. The first 11 moves repeat my games against Ivanisevic.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3
Nc5 9. Qd2 b6 10. Nb5 O-O 11. Nd6 Bb7 12. Nxb7 $6 {As I have mentioned in my
comments to the previous example, Black has an easy game after this exchange.
He just needs to extinguish White's temporary initiative.} Nxb7 13. Ba3 Re8 14.
Bg2 Nc6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5] Quite soon, White will run out of active moves. At
the same time, Black is ready to proceed with his standard plan - ...Rc8
followed by ...Nca5.} 15. Rd1 {This is the only possible way to keep the
initiative going. As it will become clear in a while, however, the attack on
d7 is just an illusion.} ({It's very important to understand that in the
structure arising after} 15. Bxc6 $2 dxc6 $19 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gb7a5] White is
positionally lost. Black is ready to follow with ...c6-c5 and ...Na5. In this
case, White cannot protect the c4-pawn. If needed, Black will add the queen to
the attack on the pawn..} {The advance} 16. c5 {is well met by} Na5 $19 {
[%cal Gb6b5,Ga5c4] when Black is ready to proceed with ...b6-b5 and ...Nc4.
The useless bishop cannot prevent Black from executing his light square
strategy.}) 15... Qf6 {It turns out that White cannot take on d7 since the
c3-pawn is hanging.} 16. O-O Rad8 {There is nothing wrong with this natural
move.} ({I would have probably preferred} 16... Red8 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5]
keeping the c8-square available for the other rook. Even though the computer
gives equality, Black play is a lot easier. If White does not manage to play
dynamically enough, he will just end up in a clearly worse position in view of
his structural weaknesses.}) 17. Qf4 $6 {This move is already an inaccuracy.
Having a better structure, Black will gladly exchange the queens.} ({Better
would have been to keep the tension by means of a move such as} 17. Qc2) 17...
Qxf4 18. gxf4 Nba5 19. c5 Nc4 {The black knight reached the perfect c4-square.
White should handle this position very carefully.} 20. Rxd7 $2 {This is a step
in the wrong direction.} ({White should have played} 20. Bc1 bxc5 21. Rxd7 Rxd7
22. Bxc6 Ree7 23. Bxd7 Rxd7 $15 {when Black is better but White's position
should be holdable.}) 20... Rxd7 21. Bxc6 Rdd8 22. Bxe8 Nxa3 23. Ba4 bxc5 {
It turns out that in this position the knight is a lot stronger than the
bishop. The threat of ...Rd2 is very annoying.} 24. e3 Kf8 {[%cal Gd8d2]
centralizing the king and ruling out any back rank mates. Black is ready to
follow with ...Rd2.} ({In case of the immediate} 24... Rd2 {White can play} 25.
Rd1) 25. Rd1 $2 {A decisive mistake in a difficult position.} Rxd1+ 26. Bxd1 a5
$19 {The endgame is completely lost for White. The thing is that he cannot
protect his queenside pawns.} 27. Bb3 c4 28. Ba4 Ke7 29. Kf1 Kd6 30. Ke1 Nb1
31. Bc2 Nxc3 32. Bxh7 g6 33. f3 Nxa2 34. Kd2 c3+ 35. Kd3 Nb4+ 36. Kxc3 Nd5+ 37.
Kb3 Nf6 38. Bxg6 fxg6 39. Ka4 Nd5 0-1

