{[%evp 0,65,38,14,30,28,28,4,59,15,2,2,14,-9,28,52,69,69,54,55,95,10,10,14,7,
14,7,0,3,-4,-16,-16,6,-32,-12,7,-2,-31,-21,-9,-10,0,25,7,67,8,0,0,53,53,54,47,
54,54,54,54,74,72,179,195,545,581,554,560,557,583,608,357] In this example, we
shall see how Black should handle the structure after the exchange of the
light-squared bishops.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 ({Obviously, our move order will be} 
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 {reaching the game
position.}) 2... e6 3. c4 c5 4. Nc3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. g3 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 b6 10. Nb5 {This move is not very challenging. With a queen on
e3 (instead of d2), the idea of installing a knight on d6 is even less
attractive.} O-O 11. Bg2 {With this move, White forces the exchange of the
light-squared bishops. I believe that the position arising after} Bb7 12. Bxb7
Nxb7 {is clearly in Black's favour. This time, White does not even have the
bishop pair as compensation for the spoiled pawn structure. His only
consolation is the temporary piece activity. In order to maintain some kind of
balance, White should be extremely creative. On the other hand, Black's plan
is crystal clear. Everyone who has been following the lecture so far will be
able to automatically play the moves ...Nc6-a5 and ...Rc8. The following
couple of moves are quite natural.} 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Rd1 Nc6 15. O-O Nca5 16.
Qd4 $2 {In fact, this is a decisive mistake since the queen takes the
d4-square from the knight. As we have already pointed out, however, in this
structure, White can easily go wrong.} ({In order to keep the balance, White
should be very creative. A better option would have been} 16. Qd3 {when the
following line is a good illustration of the nature of the position -} Qc8 17.
Bb4 {[%cal Gb5a3] putting pressure on a5 and making the a3-square available
for the knight.} a6 18. Na3 Nc5 19. Qd6 Na4 {[%cal Ga4b2,Ga5c4] Threatening ...
Nxc4 as well as ...Nb2. White should now go for the following sequence -} 20.
Qxd7 Nb2 21. Qxc8 Raxc8 22. Rd7 Naxc4 23. Nxc4 Nxc4 24. Rfd1 $11 {White's
control of the d-file is enough compensation for Black's superior structure.
Nevertheless, the position is still more pleasant for Black.}) 16... d5 $1 {
A very strong move. Now, after ...a7-a6, the White knight does not have the
d6-square.} 17. cxd5 exd5 $2 {This move is unexplainable. Black does not
follow the idea of his previous move.} ({After} 17... a6 $1 18. dxe6 axb5 19.
exf7+ Kxf7 20. Qf4+ Qf6 $17 {White's position is almost lost.}) 18. Qg4 {
The position is already unclear. Later on, Ftacnik even managed to win the
game.} a6 19. Nd4 Re4 20. Qh5 Qd7 21. f3 Ree8 22. e4 Nc4 23. Bc1 Re5 24. Nf5
Nbd6 25. Bf4 Nxf5 26. Bxe5 Nfe3 27. Qg5 f6 28. Bxf6 Nxf1 29. Bxg7 Qxg7 30.
Qxd5+ Qf7 31. Qxa8+ Kg7 32. Rxf1 Ne3 33. Qxa6 1-0

