{[%evp 0,174,31,30,28,4,4,4,29,-19,-10,-9,-14,9,22,22,55,55,55,69,78,21,19,6,
37,38,8,1,10,10,-17,-17,-13,-8,-8,-1,0,-18,-5,-15,-8,-16,-5,-45,-46,-68,-34,
-28,-21,-19,-23,-21,-16,-29,-22,-40,-9,-4,0,-17,0,0,0,-3,-3,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-6,
-3,-71,-35,-11,-21,-21,-21,-46,-15,-53,-28,-30,-16,-34,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-143,-160,
-115,-131,-147,-147,-162,-169,-183,-111,-142,-111,-107,-106,-108,-101,-105,
-100,-208,-137,-151,-144,-144,-123,-50,0,-83,-71,-153,-111,-153,-165,-177,-151,
-131,-148,-140,-150,-145,-145,-174,-172,-160,-160,-160,-160,-238,-240,-258,
-261,-590,-590,-586,-607,-645,-586,-678,-755,-1034,-209,-320,-424,-481,-539,
-532,-431,-468,-460,-484,-484,-474,-484,-484,-484,-574,-574,-604,-815,-867,
-1109,-1417,-1292] The following example is quite similar to the previous one.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+
8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 {Besides creating an opposition with the black king, with
this move, White is targeting the c5-knight. Black should already reckon with
the threat of Nf5. Even though 9.Qe3 is quite popular in practice, I consider
this move dubious. In fact, with a precise play, Black can fight for an
advantage.} b6 10. Nf5 $2 {When the c5-knight is protected, this move is just
a blow in the air.} ({The usual continuation} 10. Bg2 {will be dealt with in
the next examples.}) 10... O-O 11. Nd6 {White wasted too much time in order to
put a knight on d6. As we know, however, such a knight is not that dangerous.}
Bb7 12. Nxb7 Nxb7 {This position is quite similar to the one from the previous
game. Nevertheless, there is an important difference. Instead of being on d2,
the white queen is now on e3. Hence, White cannot put strong pressure on the
d-file.} 13. Ba3 Re8 14. Bg2 Nc6 {White's temporary initiative is over. Black
can already start working on the c4-pawn. As we know, he is ready to follow
with standard moves such as ...Rc8 and ...Nca5.} 15. Rd1 Qc7 16. Qf4 {We know
that Black will gladly exchange the queens. On the other hand, it's not easy
to provide White with better advice.} Qxf4 17. gxf4 Red8 {I like this move a
lot. Black keeps the c8-square available for the remaining rook. Objectively
speaking, the position remains balanced. In order to prove equality,
however, White should keep finding dynamic resources. Therefore, we can
conclude that Black's position is practically easier.} 18. O-O Nba5 19. Bd6 $1
{The most precise move. Before playing c4-c5, White wants to activate the
bishop. The immediate threat is Bc7.} ({In case of} 19. c5 Nc4 20. Bc1 Rac8 $15
{Black's advantage is out of the question.}) 19... Rac8 20. c5 Nc4 21. Bxc6 dxc6 {
Until this moment, White was playing very precisely. The last move, however,
is a huge mistake. Such mistakes are very common when we need to play very
dynamically in order to compensate for the opponent's static advantage.} 22.
Be7 $2 ({White should have played} 22. Rd4 {when after} b5 23. a4 a6 24. Ra1 {
the position remains balanced.}) 22... Rxd1 $2 {Strangely enough, Black gives
the d-file for free.} ({After the precise} 22... Rd5 $1 23. Rd4 b5 $19 {
[%cal Gc4b2,Gb2a4] White is positionally lost. Black can start playing against
the queenside weaknesses by means of the manoeuvre...Nb2-a4.}) 23. Rxd1 $11 {
The position is now close to equal. Later on, after mutual mistakes, Black
managed to win the game.} b5 24. Rd7 a5 25. Kg2 h6 26. Bd6 a4 27. Kf3 Nd2+ 28.
Ke3 Nc4+ 29. Kd3 Nb2+ 30. Kd4 Nc4 31. f3 Nd2 32. Kd3 Nc4 33. e4 Nb2+ 34. Kd4
Nc4 35. h4 h5 36. f5 exf5 37. e5 g6 38. Be7 Kg7 39. Bf6+ Kf8 40. f4 Kg8 41. e6
fxe6 42. Rg7+ Kf8 43. Rh7 Ke8 44. Bg5 Nd2 45. Ke5 Ne4 46. Kxe6 Nxc5+ 47. Kf6
Nd7+ 48. Kg7 Nf8 49. Rh8 Rc7+ 50. Kf6 Rf7+ 51. Ke5 Kd7 52. Rg8 Kc7 53. Bh6 Nd7+
54. Ke6 Rf6+ 55. Ke7 Rd6 56. Bg7 Rd5 57. Kf7 Rd2 58. a3 Rh2 59. Be5+ Kb6 60.
Rxg6 Rxh4 61. Bd4+ Kb7 62. Ke7 c5 63. Bh8 Nb6 64. Kd6 Rxf4 65. Kxc5 Nc4 66. Bd4
Nxa3 67. Rg7+ Kc8 68. Kc6 Rg4 69. Rc7+ Kd8 70. Rd7+ Ke8 71. Bc5 Rg6+ 72. Bd6
Nc4 73. Rh7 a3 74. Rxh5 a2 75. Rh8+ Kf7 76. Ra8 Rg2 77. Bc5 Rb2 78. Bd4 f4 79.
Kd5 Ne3+ 80. Ke4 Nc2 81. Ra7+ Ke6 82. Ra6+ Kd7 83. Ra7+ Kc8 84. c4 Nxd4 85.
Kxd4 b4 86. Kc5 b3 87. Kb6 Rb1 0-1

