{[%evp 0,60,28,28,28,4,-2,-6,29,31,15,-14,9,9,22,51,69,69,69,69,44,45,45,31,31,
-44,-61,-74,-63,-118,-120,-136,-121,-149,-98,-115,-67,-69,-79,-80,-78,-81,-63,
-103,-95,-147,-144,-159,-154,-167,-159,-240,-230,-251,-251,-314,-252,-266,-254,
-248,-258,-317,-319] In this game, we will see what happens when White plays
in a very passive way. Even though this is just a blitz game, I find it to be
very instructive.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4
Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Nf5 $2 {
This "blitz move" is completely pointless now. White just does not have any
real threat.} ({In the next examples, we will also cover the main continuation
} 12. Qe4) 12... O-O {It turns out that the knight should now go back.} 13. Nd4
Na6 {[%cal Ga6c5] Black wants to establish a solid blockade on the c5-square.
While this is a typical idea, in the concrete case, it is not necessary. Black
can win by simply attacking the c4-pawn.} ({Better would have been} 13... Qc7
14. Qd3 Rc8 $19 {winning the c4-pawn for free.}) 14. Qe4 $2 {One more
pointless move. White is playing for simple tricks.} ({Better was} 14. Ba3 Re8
15. Nb5 {when White at least has some piece activity in return for his
compromised structure.}) 14... Nac5 15. Qg4 Qf6 16. h4 Qg6 {Black correctly
tries to exchange the queens. After such an exchange, White's position will be
completely hopeless.} ({Even better would have been} 16... Na5 {when White
cannot hold the c4-pawn. After} 17. Bg5 Qg6 18. h5 Qe4 $19 {Black is already
winning.}) 17. Qf3 Qe4 18. Ba3 Qxf3 19. Nxf3 Rfc8 $19 {Black is strategically
winning. Later on, he managed to easily convert the advantage.} 20. O-O-O Rc7
21. Nd4 a6 22. Nb3 Ne4 23. Rhf1 Nxc3 24. Rd3 Rxc4 25. Kd2 Ne4+ 26. Ke3 d5 27.
g4 Nec5 28. Nxc5 Nxc5 29. Bxc5 bxc5 30. Rb1 Rxg4 0-1

