{[%evp 0,72,18,27,41,2,-4,-4,7,-23,-8,1,24,18,26,19,27,45,45,24,8,1,1,1,1,11,
11,11,11,11,11,11,11,14,24,-9,-31,-30,-1,-11,-11,-13,-9,-29,-30,-13,-16,-39,
-25,-54,-53,-51,-48,-48,-50,-50,-50,-50,-37,-50,-37,-37,-42,-42,-46,-63,-64,
-100,-96,-95,-97,-347,-347,-346,-356] From this game, we start examining one
very important endgame that occurs quite often. I am sure that you will face
it as well. We are already familiar with the first 11 moves.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3 c5 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3
({An alternative move order is} 9. Qc2 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Qe4 {
when we reach the game position.}) 9... b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Qe4 {
This is by far the most popular move. Black cannot protect the b7-knight
without sacrificing a pawn.} Nc6 {Black is forced to sacrifice a pawn.
Nevertheless, he gets more than enough compensation in return.} 13. Nxc6 dxc6
14. Qxc6+ Qd7 15. Qxd7+ {White is forced to go for the endgame.} ({Avoiding
the exchange of the queens with a move like} 15. Qe4 $6 {is even worse. After}
Rc8 {[%cal Gd7c6] followed by ...Qc6, Black will obviously regain the pawn.}) (
{Another option is} 15. Qb5 $6 {when White wants to exchange the queens on his
terms. In this case, Black can follow with} Nd6 16. Qg5 O-O $15 {with an
obvious advantage.}) 15... Kxd7 16. Ba3 {[%cal Ge1c1] White is planning to use
the position of the black king by castling long. Afterwards, he can double the
rooks along the d-file. With a precise play, however, Black does not have any
problems.} Rhc8 $1 {Putting exactly this rook on c8 is very important. Now the
black king can retreat to e8, without causing coordination problems. The
critical position of the variation arises after} 17. O-O-O+ Ke8 18. Rd4 {
[%cal Gh1d1] White is ready to double the rooks along the d-file. Black has
two equally good ways of attacking the pawn on c4. I strongly advise you to
examine both options. By doing so, you will get a better overall understanding
of the position.} Rc7 {[%cal Ga8c8] This is the simplest approach to the
position. Black is just planning to increase the pressure on c4 by doubling
the rooks along the c-file.} ({Another option which is very much approved by
the computer is} 18... Na5 19. c5 b5 $1 {Almost always the advance c4-c5
should be answered in this way. Black's idea is ...Nc4 on the next move. The
move Bb4 can be answered with ...a7-a5.} 20. Kc2 {This is the most precise
continuation. The king should be ready to go to b3 in the event of ...Nc4.} ({
A GM game saw} 20. Rhd1 $2 Nc4 $17 {when Black had a huge advantage. White is
basically forced to sacrifice an exchange without getting sufficient
compensation in return. 0-1 (56) Lalic,B (2491)-Delchev,A (2656) Balaguer 2005}
) 20... Nc4 21. Kb3 Nxa3 22. Kxa3 Rxc5 $15 {As we will see in the next example,
this type of endgame is better for Black. White needs to work very hard in
order to make a draw.}) 19. Rh4 {[%cal Gh1d1,Gd1d4] White is freeing the
d4-square for the other rook. Holding the c4-pawn until the end, however, is
hardly a good strategy.} h6 20. Rd1 Rac8 21. Rdd4 f6 {[%cal Ge8f7] Freeing the
f7-square for the king.} ({Another standard way of handling the position is} 
21... Na5 22. c5 b5 {[%cal Ga5c4] planning the typical ...Nc4. In order to
equalize, White should play dynamically -} 23. Rd6 Nb7 24. Ra6 Nxc5 25. Bxc5
Rxc5 26. Rxa7 Rxc3+ $11 {with a draw.}) 22. Rhe4 Kf7 23. f4 Na5 24. c5 f5 25.
Re3 b5 {[%cal Ga5c4,Ga7a5] Once again, Black is creating the typical threat of
...Nc4 followed by ...a7-a5.} 26. Red3 $6 {This inaccuracy allows Black to
obtain a static advantage.} ({White could have achieved a draw by applying the
following typical motif -} 26. Bb4 Nc4 27. Rf3 a5 28. a4 $1 {This is the most
effective way of undermining the construction Nc4 + b5. Remember this typical
idea!} axb4 29. cxb4 {The position is completely equal. One way to force the
draw is} Rb8 30. axb5 Na5 31. bxa5 Rxb5 32. a6 Rcxc5+ 33. Kd2 Rb2+ 34. Ke1 Ra5
$11 {with full equality.}) 26... Nc4 27. Bb2 a6 $15 {Black already enjoys a
slight but stable advantage.} 28. Rd7+ Rxd7 ({More precise would have been} 
28... Ke8 {preventing the invasion of the white rook.}) 29. Rxd7+ Kf6 30. Kc2
Rxc5 31. Bc1 Rc6 32. Kd3 $6 {This careless move allows Black to obtain a
serious advantage.} ({Better would have been} 32. Ra7 {when White's position
is completely holdable.}) 32... e5 33. e4 fxe4+ 34. Kxe4 Re6 35. Ra7 $4 {
After this decisive mistake, Black is winning.} ({White should have played} 35.
fxe5+ Rxe5+ 36. Kd3 {Even though Black's position remains preferable, the draw
shouldn't be a problem.}) 35... exf4+ 36. Kxf4 Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3,Gg7g5] White
resigns since there is no defence against the double threat - ...Nd3 and ...
g7-g5.} 0-1

