{[%evp 0,128,14,15,15,-4,4,4,33,33,33,12,18,21,33,18,33,33,33,27,27,27,27,27,
24,24,10,1,1,1,1,1,1,11,-5,-27,-22,-22,0,-9,-7,-23,-34,-53,-45,-50,-45,-37,-60,
-57,-48,-51,-50,-61,-51,-68,-56,-59,-53,-73,-63,-82,-72,-79,-74,-75,-64,-64,
-64,-60,-54,-42,-40,-54,-106,-98,-87,-96,-88,-88,-20,-24,-20,0,0,0,0,-21,0,0,0,
0,0,0,0,0,18,-28,-22,-23,-32,-17,-32,-167,-168,-194,-211,-209,-221,-221,-211,
-197,-196,-196,-202,-229,-265,-265,-281,-283,-270,-270,-285,-279,-295,-285,
-285,-303,-300,-338,-359] This very instructive game shows the optimal way of
handling the typical 4 rook endgame that often occurs in this line. The first
18 moves repeat the previous game.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5.
g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7
Nxb7 12. Qe4 Nc6 13. Nxc6 dxc6 14. Qxc6+ Qd7 15. Qxd7+ Kxd7 16. Ba3 Rhc8 17.
O-O-O+ Ke8 18. Rd4 Rc7 19. Kc2 {This time, White is not trying to protect the
c4-pawn. He is ready to sacrifice it by means of c4-c5. The position of
interest arises after} Rac8 20. c5 Nxc5 21. Bxc5 Rxc5 {This kind of endgame is
very typical. It's not as equal as it might seem! In fact, White should fight
for a long time in order to achieve a draw. Note that we cannot win the game
by only playing against the queenside weaknesses. Black should try to create
at least one extra target on the kingside. For that purpose, under favourable
circumstances, he will start advancing the kingside pawns. Since the h2-pawn
is far away from the queenside, it will be our perfect target. In any case,
Black wants to play ...g7-g5 followed by ...h7-h5-h4. Afterwards, he will
decide whether to fix the h2-pawn by means of h4-h3 or open the h-file by
playing ...hxg3.} 22. Rd3 Rc4 {I like this move. Being on the 4th rank, the
rook will support the advance ...h7-h5-h4.} 23. Rhd1 R8c7 24. Kb3 b5 25. Re3 {
In my view, this move is a bit pointless.} ({Better would have been} 25. h4 {
preventing Black from gaining space by means of ...g7-g5.}) 25... Ke7 26. Kb2
a6 27. Rdd3 ({Once again, more logical would have been} 27. h4) 27... g5 $1 {
[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4] This classy move is typical for many similar endgames.
Besides gaining space on the kingside, Black prevents the advance h2-h4.
Therefore, in the future, the h2-pawn might become a weakness.} 28. h3 h5 29.
Kb3 {White has nothing to do. He is doomed to passivity.} f6 30. Kb2 e5 {
Black keeps improving his kingside position. White should already reckon with
ideas such as ...e5-e4 followed by ...f6-f5.} 31. Rd4 Rd7 {A good positional
decision. Black wants to exchange White's only active piece.} 32. Rxd7+ $6 {
This is the wrong way of exchanging. Now, White will have a lot of
difficulties creating counterplay.} ({After} 32. Rxc4 bxc4 33. Kc2 Ke6 $15 {
[%csl Re3] White's position is probably holdable but difficult in view of the
passive rook.}) ({The computer suggests} 32. f4 {which is the most dynamic
solution. The following sequence is pretty forced.} Rdxd4 33. cxd4 gxf4 34.
gxf4 Rxd4 35. fxe5 Rd2+ 36. Kb3 f5 37. e6 {This is forced. Otherwise, Black
will play ...Ke6.} Rd6 38. Re5 Rxe6 39. Rxf5 Re3+ 40. Kb4 Rxh3 $15 {White's
activity should be enough for a draw. Nevertheless, Black can still pose
practical problems.}) 32... Kxd7 33. Rd3+ Ke7 {This move is designed to
prevent Rd8. Nevertheless, I find it a bit passive.} ({Better would have been} 
33... Ke6 34. Rd8 h4 {when} 35. Ra8 $2 {is weak in view of} Re4 $1 36. Rxa6+
Kf7 37. gxh4 Rxe2+ 38. Kc1 gxh4 39. a4 bxa4 40. Rxa4 Rxf2 $19 {Black is
winning because of his connected passed pawns.}) 34. Kb3 h4 35. g4 Rf4 36. Rf3
$2 {This is a blunder.} ({White should have played} 36. f3 {when after} e4 37.
Rd4 Ke6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge4f3] he needs to find the only move} 38. c4 $1 {making
sure that ...Ke5 will be answered with Rd5. After} f5 39. gxf5+ Kxf5 40. Rd5+
Ke6 41. Rd4 $11 {The draw is obvious.}) 36... Re4 $2 {Black makes a huge
mistake in return.} ({The pawn endgame arising after} 36... Rxf3 37. exf3 {
is winning for Black because of the kingside breaks. He will follow with} f5
38. Kc2 (38. gxf5 e4 $19) 38... e4 39. Kd2 exf3 40. Ke3 fxg4 41. hxg4 Kd6 42.
Kxf3 Ke5 $19 {Black is winning.}) 37. e3 Ke6 38. a3 $11 {The position is
already equal. Despite the passive white rook, Black cannot make any progress.}
Rc4 39. Rf5 e4 40. Kc2 Rc6 41. a4 b4 42. c4 Rxc4+ 43. Kb3 Rc1 44. Ra5 Rb1+ 45.
Kc4 b3 46. Rxa6+ Kf7 47. Rb6 Ra1 48. Rxb3 Rxa4+ 49. Kd5 Ra2 50. Kxe4 Rxf2 51.
Rb8 Kg7 52. Ra8 Rh2 53. Kf5 Rxh3 54. Ra7+ Kh6 55. Kxf6 Rf3+ 56. Ke5 Rxe3+ 57.
Kf5 Rf3+ 58. Ke5 Rf4 59. Ra6+ Kg7 60. Ra7+ Kf8 61. Ra8+ Ke7 62. Ra7+ Kd8 63.
Rg7 Rxg4 64. Kf5 Rg3 0-1

