{[%evp 0,81,28,24,24,4,14,15,24,4,14,14,21,22,18,23,68,68,68,68,21,26,26,21,21,
-2,50,20,44,0,1,5,27,17,-11,12,12,17,13,20,0,-43,31,-20,11,-17,0,-37,-11,6,51,
92,73,130,117,79,142,82,88,94,94,138,127,149,154,153,157,170,170,166,169,193,
199,193,199,193,196,196,269,288,303,308,356,309] This example shows that even
if White manages to play Nf5 under favourable circumstances, Black does not
have any problems.} 1. Nf3 ({Obviously, our move order will be} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 {reaching the game position.})
1... Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. g3 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Ba3 {White parted with his
bishop pair but tries to create an active piece play. He will increase the
pressure with moves such as Rd1 and Nf5. As often happens in this line,
however, it turns out that White's initiative is only temporary.} Nc6 13. Rd1
Nca5 $1 14. Nf5 {Even though this knight jump is a recurring motif, Black
almost never needs to be afraid of it.} ({A very important alternative is} 14.
Qe5 Qf6 15. Qb5 {putting an annoying pressure on d7.} ({After} 15. Qc7 Qd8 $11
{White has nothing better than repeating the position with Qe5.}) {Without
fearing ghosts, Black should go for the cold-blooded} 15... Rc8 $1 16. Qa6 {
This is the most challenging continuation.} ({After} 16. Bb4 Nc5 17. Bxa5 bxa5
18. Qxa5 O-O $132 {Black will soon regain the pawn.}) ({The tempting} 16. Nf5
$2 {is a huge mistake since after} Rc7 $1 $19 {White's position is falling
apart.}) 16... d6 $1 {This move easily solves all the problems. Completing the
development is Black's first priority. Most likely, the queenside pawns will
be exchanged.} 17. Nb5 ({Harmless is} 17. Qb5+ Kf8 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7] when
Black can connect the rooks by means of ...g7-g6 followed by ...Kg7.}) 17...
O-O 18. O-O Nc5 $1 {The last important move. Now, White should go for the
following sequence} 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. Nxa7 Rb8 21. Rd6 Qxc3 22. Rxb6 Rxb6 23.
Qxb6 Qa3 24. Nb5 Qxa2 25. Qxc5 Nxc4 $11 {with an obvious draw.}) 14... Qf6 15.
Qd3 $1 {This intermediate move attacking d7 is very important. Otherwise,
White's position is falling apart. The next sequence is quite logical} Rd8 16.
Nd6+ Nxd6 17. Bxd6 Nb7 18. Bc7 Nc5 19. Qe3 Rc8 20. Bd6 {So far White was
developing the initiative in the most precise way. In such positions, however,
only the computer can keep playing all the dynamic moves. I consider White's
last move to be a slight inaccuracy.} ({Better would have been} 20. Be5 Qg6 21.
O-O {when Black should probably repeat with} Qe4 22. Qg5 Qg6 $11) 20... Qd8 {
I don't like this passive move after which White is slightly better.} ({
Black should have played} 20... Nb7 {making use of the vulnerable d6-bishop. A
possible follow-up would be} 21. O-O Rxc4 22. Bb4 Rc7 23. Rd2 d6 $1 24. Bxd6
Nxd6 25. Rxd6 O-O $15) 21. Qe5 f6 22. Qh5+ g6 23. Qf3 Kf7 24. O-O Rc6 25. Rd4
e5 26. Bxe5 Re8 27. Rfd1 Qe7 28. Rd5 Kg8 29. Bd6 Qxe2 30. Qxe2 Rxe2 31. Bxc5
Rxc5 32. Rxd7 Rxa2 33. Rb7 Rc8 34. Rdd7 a5 35. Rg7+ Kh8 36. Rxh7+ Kg8 37. Rhg7+
Kh8 38. Rxg6 a4 39. Rxf6 a3 40. Rfxb6 Rf8 41. Rb8 1-0

