{[%evp 0,33,23,27,32,4,6,6,30,26,36,21,38,9,21,0,52,52,52,11,11,11,11,11,11,11,
11,4,4,-45,-47,-29,23,-294,-305,-332] The following game is a funny example of
playing Nf5 in the most inappropriate moment.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
Nf3 c5 5. g3 Ne4 ({Our move order is} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 {reaching the game
position.}) 6. Qd3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qc2 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11.
Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Qe4 Nc6 13. Ba3 {As we already know, this move is far more
dangerous in combination with Rd1 and Qe3. In this concrete case, Black can
easily achieve good piece coordination.} Rc8 14. O-O Nca5 {Immediately
starting the typical play against the c4-pawn.} 15. Rfd1 Nc5 {Even though this
move is slightly premature, it helped Black to quickly win the game.} ({
The computer suggests the following sequence} 15... Nxc4 16. Bb4 Nc5 17. Nf5 $1
O-O 18. Nh6+ gxh6 19. Qxc4 d5 20. Qg4+ Qg5 $13 {With a very precise play White
gets enough compensation for equality. In practical terms, however, playing
with Black is a lot easier.}) 16. Nf5 $4 {This is losing on the spot.} ({
The best would have been} 16. Qg4 O-O 17. Nb5 {keeping some initiative.}) 16...
O-O {It turns out that White is losing a piece.} 17. Nh6+ {After playing this
move, White resigned in view of 17...gxh6.} 0-1

