{[%evp 0,108,24,24,24,-5,-5,5,28,23,30,-15,18,23,24,32,68,68,68,68,21,21,21,21,
21,21,21,21,21,12,23,-22,-20,-38,-38,-36,-55,-73,-66,-58,-12,-38,-51,-56,-50,
-86,-72,-70,-49,-38,-27,-49,-40,-200,-203,-203,-166,-185,-171,-212,-154,-183,
-200,-193,-214,-206,-221,-221,-224,-182,-204,-196,-182,-182,-196,-193,-191,
-191,-178,-168,-171,-177,-166,-182,-150,-161,-154,-153,-147,-144,-140,-224,
-226,-226,-239,-250,-274,-254,-257,-271,-295,-298,-301,-299,-285,-394,-345,
-357,-348,-368,-388] The next example is dedicated to the symmetrical
structure arising after Nxc6 ...dxc6. As we will see, White struggles to
obtain dynamic compensation for the static drawbacks.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 Ne4 ({I remind you that our move order is} 5... cxd4 6.
Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 {reaching the game position.}) 6. Qd3 cxd4 7.
Nxd4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qe3 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Qe4 Nc6 13. Nxc6
dxc6 14. Ba3 {This is the main alternative to the endgame arising after 14.
Qxc6 Qd7 15.Qxd7 Kxd7.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black is already planning to follow
with ...c6-c5 when White's position will be strategically lost.} 15. O-O $2 {
This is already a huge mistake since it allows ...c6-c5.} ({White should have
played} 15. Rb1 $1 {planning to answer 15...c5 with 16.Bxc5! Even after this
move, however, White should keep playing very dynamically in order to prove
some compensation for his spoiled structure. Humans are prone to making
mistakes in such positions.} Rd8 {[%cal Gc6c5] Renewing the threat of ...c6-c5.
Now} 16. c5 {is pretty much the only move.} b5 {[%cal Gb7a5,Ga5c4] This is the
typical reaction to the advance c4-c5. Black is already preparing the typical
manoeuvre...Na5-c4. In order to maintain the balance, White should find the
following sequence} 17. c4 a6 18. O-O O-O 19. Bb2 Nxc5 20. Qe3 Nd7 $132 {
Even though the computer evaluates the position as balanced, White still needs
to prove his compensation for the pawn. This is not easy in a practical game.})
15... c5 {[%cal Gb7a5] White's position is already very difficult. In the long
run, it will be very difficult for him to defend the c4-pawn.} 16. Rad1 O-O 17.
Bc1 Na5 {The most standard move in this pawn structure.} ({Another typical
idea is} 17... Rae8 {preparing a central expansion with ...f7-f5. At some
point, Black can always return to the c4-pawn. A possible continuation would be
} 18. Rd3 f5 19. Qh4 Qc6 20. Rfd1 Rf7 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4] After preventing
any possible invasion on the d-file, Black can consider the advance ...
e6-e5-e4. Additionally, the c4-pawn is doomed.}) 18. Rd3 Qc6 19. Qg4 e5 20.
Rfd1 Qg6 {As it becomes clear from Black's play, exchanging the queens is one
of the major positional ideas in this structure.} 21. Qh4 $6 {This is even
worse than exchanging queens.} ({Better would have been} 21. Qxg6 hxg6 22. Rd7
Nxc4 23. Kg2 $15 {when White at least gets some compensation for the pawn.})
21... e4 22. Rd5 f6 {Even though this move does not spoil the advantage, it's
a bit passive.} ({Better was} 22... Nxc4 23. Rg5 Qf6 24. Qxe4 Qxc3 $17 {
when White does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 23. Qh3 Rfe8 24. Qd7
Nxc4 25. Bf4 e3 26. fxe3 Qe4 27. R1d3 Nb2 28. Rd2 Nc4 29. R2d3 Re7 30. Qc6 Rae8
31. h4 Nb2 32. Rd2 Nc4 33. R2d3 h6 34. h5 Nb2 35. Rd2 Nc4 36. R2d3 Ne5 37. Bxe5
Rxe5 38. Rd6 Rxh5 39. Qxe8+ Qxe8 40. Rd8 Re5 41. Kf2 Kf8 42. Rxe8+ Kxe8 43. Kf3
Re7 44. Rd6 Rd7 45. Re6+ Kd8 46. a4 Rd1 47. Re4 Rf1+ 48. Kg2 Rc1 49. Rg4 g5 50.
Rc4 Kd7 51. Kf3 h5 52. Ke4 Ke6 53. Kd3 Kd5 54. e4+ Ke5 0-1

