{[%evp 0,59,24,24,24,-5,5,-4,25,16,30,-15,24,24,32,33,68,61,61,-15,-3,24,18,-3,
37,11,25,23,24,8,37,0,27,27,34,20,36,24,24,-46,38,23,16,-10,18,27,23,42,35,19,
43,31,32,20,4,-1,86,84,426,422,1133,1149] From this game, we start dealing
with 9.Qf3 which is the most important continuation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qf3 {This is
the most common move on the high level. The idea is to prevent the move ...
b7-b6. In this way, White makes it difficult for Black to develop the
queenside. In my opinion, Black's optimal reaction is} d6 10. Bg2 e5 {Played
according to the classical positional principles. After parting with his
dark-squared bishop, Black puts the central pawns on dark squares. If allowed,
Black can put pressure on c4 by means of simple moves such as ...Be6, and ...
Nbd7-b6.} 11. Nf5 {This is the most straightforward continuation. In the next
examples, we will also examine 11.Qe3 and 11.Nb3.} Qf6 {Black immediately
seizes the opportunity to exchange the queens.} ({The alternative} 11... Bxf5
12. Qxf5 Nbd7 $132 {is perfectly playable as well. Black's superior structure
and stable knights provide enough compensation for White's bishop pair.}) 12.
Ne3 Qxf3 13. Bxf3 {The standard recapture.} ({In one of the next examples, we
will also examine Ivanchuk's} 13. exf3) 13... Be6 14. Ba3 {[%cal Ge1c1]
White's plan is obvious. He will proceed with 0-0-0 followed by doubling the
rooks on the d-file. In this way, he would put maximum pressure on Black's
position. Black needs to fulfil two tasks: 1) safely protect the d6-pawn 2)
secure the stability of the c5-knight Whenever the white knight goes to d5, we
are ready to take it.} Nba6 {With this typical move, Black supports the
c5-knight and is getting ready to defend the d6-pawn by means of ...Ke7 and ...
Rd8.} ({In my opinion, the alternative} 14... Nbd7 $5 {is even more precise.
When possible, I prefer to develop the knight via d7. The knight is more
flexible in this position. Under favourable circumstances, Black can play ...
Nb6. The following line illustrates the nature of the position.} 15. O-O-O Ke7
16. Rd2 Rac8 17. Rhd1 {White managed to achieve his optimal setup. The d6-pawn
is now under tremendous pressure. Fortunately, Black has} e4 18. Bg4 Rc6 {
not only protecting d6 but also getting ready to double the rooks on the
c-file.} {It's instructive to know that} 19. Nf5+ {is well met by} Bxf5 20.
Bxf5 e3 $1 {A strong positional pawn sacrifice. By spoiling White's pawn
structure, Black secures the excellent e5-square for his knight.} 21. fxe3 Rd8
22. Bh3 Ne5 $132 {Black has enough counterplay. White's extra pawn is
meaningless. Also, the bishop pair is completely neutralized.}) 15. O-O-O Ke7 {
In my opinion, this move is more effective in positions with ...Nbd7.} ({
When the knight is on a6, I prefer} 15... O-O-O {[%cal Gf7f5] planning to gain
kingside space by means of ...f7-f5. An illustrative line would be} 16. Rd2 f5
17. Rhd1 Kc7 18. Nd5+ Bxd5 19. Bxd5 Rhf8 $11 {The position is balanced. In my
opinion, however, playing with Black is a bit easier. One of his possible
ideas is to gain space on the kingside by means of ...g7-g5-g4 followed by the
advance of the h-pawn. The queenside position can be improved with ...Na4
followed by ...Nac5. At some point, White will need to reckon with ideas such
as ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5 or ...Nb6.}) 16. Bg2 Rad8 17. f4 f6 18. Rhf1 {[%cal
Gg3g4,Gh2h4] White is planning to gain space on the kingside with g3-g4
followed by h2-h4. On the other hand, Black's position remains very stable.} b6
19. g4 Nc7 $6 {This move is a bit passive.} ({Anand should have preferred the
active} 19... h5 {when after} 20. Nf5+ Kf8 21. fxe5 hxg4 22. exf6 gxf6 $13 {
the play is very unclear.}) 20. h4 $14 {Even though Black's position remains
very solid, White is already slightly better. Later on, Kramnik managed to win.}
g6 21. Kc2 Rhf8 22. Bc6 f5 23. fxe5 dxe5 24. Rxd8 Kxd8 25. gxf5 gxf5 26. Bxc5
bxc5 27. Be4 Ne8 (27... f4) 28. Bxf5 Nd6 29. Bxe6 Rf2 30. Rxf2 1-0

