{This example features a very interesting positional idea by the great
Ivanchuk. The first 12 moves repeat the previous game.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qf3 d6 10.
Bg2 e5 11. Nf5 Qf6 12. Ne3 Qxf3 13. exf3 {This highly original recapture is
designed to quickly gain kingside space by means of f3-f4 and eventually f4-f5.
One of the ideas is to discourage the setup based on ...Be6 followed by ...
Nbd7. Just like Anand, Asrian played} Nba6 ({I would still prefer} 13... Be6 {
In this case, the move} 14. f4 {can be met by} exf4 15. gxf4 Nc6 16. f5 Bd7
$132 {with a complex fight ahead. White's terrible structure gives Black
enough compensation for the bishop pair. If possible, Black can consider
exchanging the light-squared bishops by means of ...Ne5 followed by ...Bc6.})
14. Ba3 Be6 15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. f4 exf4 17. gxf4 {This is the position White
was aiming for. Black should now decide how to deal with the threat of f4-f5.}
f5 {I don't quite like this drastic move. Not only it weakens the e-file, but
also the g7-pawn might become a target.} ({Better would have been} 17... g6 18.
Rd4 Kc7 {with a solid position.}) 18. h4 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh4h5,Gh1g1]
White is already slightly better. He is ready to fix the g7-pawn by means of
h4-h5 and follow with Rhg1.} Rhe8 19. h5 Kc7 20. Rhg1 Bf7 21. Nxf5 Bxc4 22. Bf3
Rd7 23. Nxg7 Rf8 24. f5 Bxa2 25. h6 Re7 26. Kd2 Ne4+ 27. Kc2 Nac5 28. Rde1 Kd7
29. Re3 Bb3+ 30. Kb2 Nd2 31. Bxc5 Rxe3 32. Bxe3 Nxf3 33. Rg3 Bd5 34. c4 Bc6 35.
Bxa7 Ne5 36. Kb3 b5 37. cxb5 Bxb5 38. Bd4 Nc6 39. Be3 Ne7 40. Ne6 Rxf5 41. Nd4
Rd5 42. Kc3 Rc5+ 43. Kd2 Ng6 44. f4 Ke8 45. f5 Ne7 46. f6 Nd5 47. Bg5 Bd7 48.
Bh4 Rc4 49. Rg8+ Kf7 50. Rg7+ Ke8 51. Kd3 Rc1 52. Ke4 Nc3+ 53. Kf3 Rf1+ 54. Kg2
Rf4 55. Re7+ Kf8 56. Bf2 Ne4 57. Bg3 Nxf6 58. Rxd7 Rxd4 59. Rxd6 Rxd6 60. Bxd6+
Kf7 61. Bf4 Kg6 62. Kf3 Ng8 63. Kg4 1/2-1/2

