{Now, we shall examine White's most challenging strategy - putting maximum
pressure on the c5-knight. As it becomes clear, however, Black is in very
good shape in all these lines.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3
cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qd3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nc5 9. Qf3 d6 10. Bg2 e5 11. Nb3 {
This is the most precise retreat. White's main idea is to put pressure on c5
by means of moves such as Ba3 and Qe3. Sometimes, the dark-squared bishop can
even go to e3.} ({An important alternative is} 11. Qe3 O-O 12. Nb3 Qc7 ({
Another option is} 12... Nba6 13. Ba3 Qc7 {transposing to 12...Qc7 13.Ba3}) 13.
Nxc5 ({The other important option is} 13. Ba3 Nba6 14. Nxc5 dxc5 {This strange-looking move seems to be the simplest solution. To some extent, the passive
a6-knight secures the stability of the queenside. At the same time, White's
queenside pawns can easily become a target.} ({The natural} 14... Nxc5 {
is possible as well.} 15. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d6] This is the most challenging
continuation. White creates the threat of Rxd6 followed by Bxc5.} ({After} 15.
Bxc5 dxc5 16. O-O Be6 17. Bd5 Rae8 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6] we get a typical
structure which is usually harmless for Black. After stabilizing the queenside,
Black can consider expanding on the other wing by means of the advance ...
f7-f5.}) {Black's most precise reaction is} 15... Be6 16. Rxd6 Qxd6 17. Bxc5 {
and now is possible} Qc7 $5 $146 {when the simplifications would lead to
equality.} 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Qxa7 ({In case of} 19. Bd5 Bxd5 20. cxd5 Rd8 21.
Qd3 e4 22. Qd4 Qa5 23. O-O Qxa2 $132 {the endgame is pretty balanced.}) 19...
Qxc4 20. Qe3 ({After} 20. O-O Qxe2 21. a4 Bc4 $11 {Black has enough
counterplay.}) 20... Qc7 21. O-O Bxa2 $11 {with equality.}) 15. O-O Be6 16.
Rab1 Rab8 17. Bd5 Rfe8 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc7d7,Gd7a4] It's not clear how White can
further improve his position. The a3-bishop is not better than our knight. At
the same time, Black can already consider playing against White's weak
queenside pawns by means of the manoeuvre...Qd7-a4.}) 13... dxc5 14. O-O Nd7 {
As we have already pointed out, this structure is usually acceptable for Black.
If White does not play dynamically, Black can start putting pressure on c4 by
means of ...Nb6 followed by ...Be6. Therefore, the most challenging move seems
to be} 15. f4 {After opening the f-file, White is planning to put pressure on
f7 by means of Bd5. On the downside, the advance f2-f4 further compromises the
pawn structure.} {In my opinion, Black's most flexible reaction is} Re8 $5 $146
(15... exf4 $143 $6 16. Rxf4 $14 {1-0 Topalov,V (2780)-Aronian,L (2739)/
Morelia/Linares MEX/ESP 2008 (37)}) 16. fxe5 ({Note that} 16. Bd5 {is well met
by} Nf6 $132) 16... Nxe5 {The simplest. Black is now planning to exchange the
light-squared bishops by means of the manoeuvre...Bd7-c6.} ({Another
possibility is} 16... Nb6 $5 17. Qe4 Be6 $5 {immediately putting pressure on
c4.} 18. Qxb7 {The most principled choice.} ({The slow play is not dangerous
for Black. For instance, after} 18. Rb1 Rab8 19. Bf4 h6 20. Rfd1 Nxc4 21. Rxb7
Qa5 $44 {Black has decent counterplay in view of White's queenside weaknesses.}
) 18... Qxe5 19. Bf4 Qxc3 20. Rac1 ({Another option is} 20. Qc7 Rac8 21. Qxa7
Nxc4 $132 {[%cal Gc3d4,Ge6d5] when Black has enough counterplay. His main
positional idea is to exchange the light-squared bishops via d5.}) 20... Qf6 {
and Black´s chances are not worse.}) 17. Ba3 Bd7 $1 {The exchange of the
bishops is more important than the c5-pawn.} 18. Qxc5 Bc6 $15 {White's
terrible structure provides Black with more than enough compensation for the
pawn.}) ({In the event of} 11. Nc2 Be6 12. Ne3 Qa5 $132 {Black has enough
counterplay in view of White's queenside weaknesses.}) 11... Nba6 12. Ba3 Qc7
13. Rd1 Be6 $1 {The simplest way to equality. The harmonious development
of the pieces is more important than the b7-pawn. The following next moves are
quite forced.} 14. Nxc5 Nxc5 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 16. Qxb7 Rc8 {Black's activity, as
well as superior structure, balances White's extra pawn.} 17. Bd5 {Forcing the
transition into a rook endgame is White's best practical chance.} ({Another
rook endgame would arise after} 17. O-O O-O 18. Bd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxc4 20. Qxc4
Rxc4 21. Rxd6 Rxc3 {The position is completely equal.} 22. a4 Rc2 23. e3 Ra2
24. Ra6 Rb8 25. Rxa7 g6 $11 {the draw is obvious.}) 17... Bxd5 18. Qxd5 Qxc4 ({
Another way to the draw is} 18... Qxd5 19. Rxd5 Rxc4 20. Rxd6 Rxc3 $11 {
with full equality.}) 19. Qxd6 Qxc3+ 20. Kf1 {The draw is obvious.} Qc7 $11 *

