{Now we shall take a look at one really challenging option - 7.Qc2.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 c5 5. g3 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Ne4 7. Qc2 {Even though 7.Qd3
is White's most popular choice, 7.Qc2 is the most dangerous one. It's not a
surprise that nowadays this continuation is more popular on GM level.} ({After} 
7. Bd2 {is possible} Bxc3 8. bxc3 b6 9. Bg2 Bb7 {It's not easy for White to
compensate for his spoiled pawn structure. The most active continuation seems
to be} 10. Qc2 Nc5 11. Bxb7 Nxb7 12. Qe4 {We are already familiar with the
following typical pawn sacrifice -} Nc6 $1 13. Nxc6 dxc6 14. Qxc6+ Qd7 15.
Qxd7+ Kxd7 $44 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh8c8] when Black is already better. His next
move is going to be ...Rhc8.}) 7... Nxc3 {In my opinion, this is the simplest
option from a practical point of view.} ({The move 7.Qc2 became fashionable when
White discovered that he can answer} 7... Qa5 8. Bg2 Nxc3 {with} 9. O-O $1 {
It turns out that Black cannot save the knight. The most precise follow-up is}
Nc6 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Nb3 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Rb1 $13 {1-0 (49) Chatalbashev,
B (2537)-Ivanov, M (2389) Banja Vrujci 2017 Even though this position is
completely holdable for Black, I feel that White has an annoying pressure in
return for the pawn.}) 8. bxc3 Be7 9. Bg2 a6 {[%cal Gd8c7,Gd7d6] By playing in
this way, Black claims that his superior structure provides enough
compensation for White's Catalan type of pressure. Black's play is very simple.
He will follow with simple moves such as ...d7-d6, ...0-0, ...Qc7, and ...Nd7.
If White is not precise enough, he can easily find himself in a worse position.
In general, I like situations where my opponent should play dynamically in
order to compensate for the static problems. Humans are prone to commit
inaccuracies in such cases.} 10. O-O {This move will be played almost
automatically by your opponents. Nevertheless, White has other interesting
options as well.} ({The attempt to immediately put pressure on b7 by means of} 
10. Rb1 Qc7 11. Qb3 {deserves serious attention. The following sequence is
pretty logical -} Nc6 12. Nxc6 dxc6 13. Be3 e5 14. O-O O-O {Black's only
problem is that the c8-bishop cannot be developed. On the other hand, White
does not have many active options. Given the fact that White is entirely
focused on the queenside, Black can initiate activity on the other wing. For
instance, a possible follow-up is} 15. a4 Qd7 16. a5 h5 $132 {We can already
imagine Black playing ...Qg4 and ...h5-h4. At some point, even the advance ...
f7-f5-f4 might come. Note that the c8-bishop participates in the game.}) ({
Another computer move is} 10. Qa4 {The point is that very often ...Qc7 can be
met by Nb5. In my opinion, Black should play} Nc6 11. O-O Qc7 {White should
already reckon with ...0-0 and ...Ne5. Therefore, the position is calling for
dynamic measures -} 12. Nb3 d6 13. c5 $1 {This is a recurring motif in such
structures. Piece activity is more important than the material. White wants to
make Bf4 work. The endgame arising after} dxc5 14. Bf4 e5 15. Bxc6+ Qxc6 16.
Qxc6+ bxc6 17. Bxe5 O-O $11 {is balanced. White's better pawn structure is
compensated by the bishop pair.}) 10... d6 11. Rb1 {The most standard move for
this structure.} ({Once again, we should consider the thematic} 11. c5 {
which is designed to open the diagonal h2-b8 for the bishop.} dxc5 12. Nf3 {
This position was reached in the game ½-½ (26) Real de Azua, E (2474)-Delgado
Ramirez, N (2616) Montevideo 2019 Now, the simplest would have been} Qc7 13. Bf4
Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 {White's compensation for the pawn is enough for
equality.}) 11... Qc7 12. Rd1 {White keeps mobilizing his pieces.} ({As I have
already pointed out, in such positions, White can easily go astray. For
instance, in one of my online games, White played} 12. h4 Nd7 13. h5 $6 h6 14.
Rd1 {1-0 (51) Urazayev, A (2429)-Grigorov, G (2507) Chess.com INT 2021 It turns
out that the advance h2-h4-h5 only creates a new target for Black - the
h5-pawn. Now, the simplest would have been} Rb8 $15 {followed by ...Ne5. By
overprotecting the b7-pawn, after ...Ne5 we will be able to answer c4-c5 with .
..Qxc5.} ({In the game I played the immediate} 14... Ne5 {At this point, my
opponent missed} 15. c5 $1 {when Black is forced to recapture on c5 with a
pawn.} dxc5 16. Nf3 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 $44 {White's compensation is enough for
equality.})) 12... Nd7 13. Qa4 {Once again, White introduces the typical
threat of Nb5.} O-O 14. Nb5 {The most logical continuation.} ({Let's take a
look at another example where White didn't manage to create a dynamic play.} 14.
Nb3 $6 Rb8 15. Bf4 g5 {I like this move. The recurring possibility of c4-c5
makes the f4-bishop pretty annoying.} 16. Be3 Ne5 17. Na5 $2 {This is already
a blunder.} ({Better would have been} 17. Nd2 {Nevertheless, after} Bd7 18. Qa3
Bc6 $132 {I would still take Black.}) 17... Bd7 18. Qb4 b5 $19 {Black is
already winning. White drops a pawn without any compensation. 0-1 (47)
Mastrovasilis,A (2537)-Antic,D (2487) Valjevo 2011}) 14... Qb8 15. Nd4 Qc7 $11
{with a repetition.} *

