{We shall now take a look at two games by the Hungarian grandmaster Banusz
where he manages to execute the light square strategy.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({Our move order will be} 4... c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Bd3 O-O 7.
O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 {transposing to the game.}) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O
Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd2f1,Gf1e3] White is
planning to transfer his knight to e3 by means of Re1 followed by the maneuver
Nd2-f1-e3. Note that e3 is the perfect square for the knight in this pawn
structure. From this position, the knight not only prevents the advance ...
f7-f5 but also participates in the potential kingside play that white might
initiate after the advance f2-f4. The problem is that this plan is very
time-consuming.} h6 {[%cal Gf6h7,Gf7f5] We already know this idea from the
previous example. Black is planning to proceed with ...Nh7 and ...f7-f5. I
repeat that h7 is the best retreat square for the knight because later on
Black can maintain his kingside activity by playing ...Ng5.} 12. Re1 Nh7 13.
Nf1 f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 {Remember that we need to exchange all white pieces that
control the light squares. After trading off the bishops, Black should also
try to exchange a pair of knights. At the end of the day, White should be left
with his dark-squared bishop.} 15. Ng3 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 Qd7 {[%cal Gf8f7,Ga8f8]
Black's strategy is crystal clear. After doubling the rooks along the f-file,
he will try to exchange the knights via f5. On the other hand, White does not
have an active plan.} 17. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] A typical move for this pawn structure.
By means of a4-a5, White is going to fix the b7 pawn which might become a
target later. Let's not forget, however, that White's a-pawn can be a target
as well.} Rf7 18. a5 Raf8 19. Ra2 Nf5 20. Nxf5 ({In case of} 20. Ne4 {Black
can challenge the knight with} Nf6 {We see one more benefit from playing ...
h7-h6. In this position, White does not have the option of Ng5.}) 20... Rxf5 {
Black managed to accomplish his desired exchange operations. The next step is
to develop a kingside activity which is based on White's difficulties to cover
the light squares.} 21. Be3 Nf6 $6 {Before going for the kingside activity,
Black should have secured the defence of the b7-pawn.} ({Grabbing space with} 
21... g5 $1 {is a thematic idea in this pawn structure. Besides gaining space,
White also frees the g7-square for the queen. A possible follow-up would be}
22. Rb1 Qg7 23. Rab2 R5f7 $15 {[%cal Gh7f6] The b7-pawn is safely protected
now and White does not have any constructive ideas. Black can now start
organising his kingside play with ...Nf6-g4 (h5). In some cases, advancing the
kingside pawns in order to provoke weaknesses is also a good strategy.}) 22.
Rb1 {[%cal Ga2b2] White starts playing against the only target in Black's
position - the b7-pawn. His next move is going to be Rab2.} Ng4 23. Rab2 {
Now, Black should finally decide how to deal with the b7-pawn. The following
couple of moves is quite logical.} b6 24. axb6 axb6 25. h3 Nxe3 26. Qxe3 {
The arising endgame with heavy pieces is balanced. Without the weakness on b6,
Black would have been obviously better. The game ended in a draw.} Rf4 27. Rxb6
Qf5 28. Rb8 Kh7 29. R1b2 Rf6 30. Rd8 h5 31. Rbb8 h4 32. Rh8+ Kg6 33. Rbg8 Qe4
34. Qd2 Qxc4 35. f3 e4 36. fxe4 Qxe4 37. Re8 Qb1+ 38. Kh2 Qf5 39. Re2 c4 40.
Qe3 Qxd5 41. Qe8+ Qf7 42. Qc8 Qd5 43. Qe8+ Qf7 44. Qc8 Qd5 45. Qe8+ 1/2-1/2

