{[%evp 0,82,25,24,24,13,21,21,21,21,29,26,13,20,26,19,32,32,32,35,50,35,28,33,
33,25,24,29,28,11,8,-8,-5,-18,-16,-21,-21,-23,-31,-28,-14,-17,-22,-41,3,0,3,-1,
-3,-33,-47,-43,-41,-81,-52,-67,-46,-43,-35,-93,-73,-105,-96,-83,-88,-71,-67,
-62,-51,-51,-115,-218,-232,-221,-182,-176,-176,-240,-196,-269,-289,-375,-307,
-298,-294]} {In this game the advance ...f7-f5 was executed at a later stage
of the game. Also, in this example, we shall see how to react when White plays
d4-d5 but delays e3-e4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6.
Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. Rb1 {As we know, putting the rook on b1 is a
recurring idea in this pawn structure. In this case, the exact move order is
not that important for Black's strategy.} e5 10. d5 Ne7 {This is the universal
reaction to d4-d5.} ({In this concrete position, Black could have also played} 
10... e4 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Bc2 exf3 13. Qxf3 Ba6 $132 {with a decent
counterplay.}) 11. Nd2 Rb8 {Black wants to free the c8-bishop. Note that the
advance ...b7-b6 is less desirable since the b6-pawn might become a hook. With
a pawn on b6, the advance a2-a4-a5 become very annoying.} 12. Qc2 {We can now
see the idea behind the delaying of e3-e4. Besides having at his disposal the
diagonal b1-h7, White can also consider the advance f2-f4 at some point.} Bd7 {
[%cal Gd8c8,Gd7f5] Black is planning to exchange the light-squared bishops by
means of ...Qc8 followed by ...Bf5.} ({I would prefer} 12... Ng6 {While
preparing the current lecture, thanks to the strong engines, I have reached
the conclusion that the move ...Ng6 almost always works well in this pawn
structure. Whenever White plays e3-e4, we will be able to make use of the
f4-square. Also, the g6-knight would be able to participate in any kind of
kingside activity.  Let's see what will happen if White plays like in the game.
} 13. h3 {Taking the g4-square under control before the advance f2-f4.} ({
It's important to know that the advance} 13. f4 $2 {will be met by} Ng4 14. Nf3
f5 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black. White should already decide how to
deal with the threat of ...e5-e4.}) 13... Ne8 $1 {Black immediately starts
preparing ...f7-f5. One of the points behind ...Ng6 is that now White cannot
take the h7-pawn. The following sequence is a good illustration of our typical
ideas in this position.} 14. f4 f5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 {Another bonus provided by
the move ...Ng6. We can now take on e5 comfortably with the knight.} 16. Bxf5
Rxf5 17. Rxf5 Bxf5 18. Qxf5 Nf6 $15 {Black has fantastic compensation for the
pawn due to White's passive pieces and numerous weaknesses.}) 13. h3 Qc8 14.
Kh2 Bf5 15. Bxf5 ({White's could have used Black's somewhat problematic
coordination by playing} 15. e4 Bd7 16. f4 exf4 17. Rxf4 Ng6 18. Rxf6 gxf6 19.
Nf1 $44 {[%cal Gc2f2,Gf1g3] with good compensation for the exchange. White can
develop his initiative by means of natural moves such as Qf2, Ng3, and Bh6.})
15... Nxf5 16. e4 Nh4 {The knight is not very stable on this square.} ({
More natural would have been} 16... Ne7) 17. Nb3 Ng6 18. Qe2 h6 $1 {[%cal
Gf6h7,Gf7f5] Black is back on track! With his last move, he starts
preparations for the advance ...f7-f5. He is ready to proceed with ...Nh7
followed by ...f7-f5.} 19. g3 Qd7 20. f3 $6 {This is a serious positional
inaccuracy. White weakens his kingside without any need.} ({Preferable was} 20.
Nd2 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gd2f1] planning to follow with Rg1 and Nf1. Later on, the
knight can be transferred to the perfect e3-square. It's important to mention
that the move ...Nh7 can be met with Qg4.}) 20... Nh7 21. Be3 Rbe8 22. Na5 $6 {
Another dubious positional operation. Provoking ...b7-b6 is pointless here.
The knight has nothing to do on c6 in this position.} b6 23. Nc6 f5 24. Bd2 Ne7
$6 {Exchanging the white knight wasn't necessary at all.} ({Black should have
focused on the kingside -} 24... f4 $1 25. g4 Ng5 {[%cal Gh6h5,Gg8f7,Gf8h8]
Black is ready to proceed with ...h6-h5 followed by ...Kf7, and ...Rh8. The
attack is completely devastating.}) 25. Nxe7+ Rxe7 $17 {Despite his inaccuracy,
Black retains a huge advantage that he eventually managed to convert.} 26. Rb5
Ref7 27. a4 Nf6 28. exf5 Qxf5 29. Rb2 Qh5 30. Kg2 Qg6 31. Be1 Nh5 32. Kh2 Rf6
33. Ra2 Qf7 34. Kg2 Rf4 35. Rb2 e4 36. Kg1 Rxf3 37. Rxf3 exf3 38. Qd3 Qd7 39.
Qg6 Nf6 40. Rf2 Qe7 41. Bd2 Qe4 0-1

