{[%evp 0,80,38,18,26,5,5,6,26,33,32,22,22,12,22,13,32,32,32,30,39,32,32,17,25,
21,21,8,16,15,5,5,4,-14,-13,-8,-5,-24,-24,-21,-51,-29,-21,-42,-28,-45,-35,-43,
-29,-40,-23,-31,-26,-25,-25,-25,-27,-33,-25,-15,-17,-17,-15,-15,-15,-15,-17,
-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-15,-12,0,0,0,0,0] Now, we shall take a
look at an example taken from the practice of the huge Huebner Variation
expert Ferenc Berkes.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({Obviously, we
will start with} 4... c5) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. h3 {
This move shows White's desire to keep the central tension after e3-e4. The
idea is to prevent Black from putting pressure on d4 by creating a pin with ...
Bg4.} e5 10. e4 h6 {When White decides to keep the central tension for a while,
we should stick to the waiting strategy. Remember that the most useful waiting
move is ...h7-h6. In this case, we are always ready to play ...Nh7 followed by
...f7-f5 in case of d4-d5.} 11. Be3 b6 12. d5 {White does not see any
constructive ideas and decides to close the centre. Black, however, is well
prepared for this scenario. The next few moves are quite logical and don't
need comments.} Ne7 13. Kh2 Nh7 14. Nd2 f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Qc2 Bxd3 17. Qxd3
Nf5 {[%cal Gd8h4] Black achieved everything he wanted from the opening. It's
now time to start developing kingside activity. A possible idea in this
direction would be ...Qh4 followed by doubling the rooks along the f-file.} 18.
g4 $6 {This move is positionally very risky in view of the kingside weaknesses.
} ({After} 18. a4 Qh4 $132 {Black has enough counterplay. He will follow by
doubling the rooks along the f-file.}) 18... Nxe3 19. fxe3 Qh4 20. Qe2 Qe7 {
This slightly passive move allows White to consolidate.} ({More precise would
have been} 20... e4 $5 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Rf1 Rxf1 23. Qxf1 Qf6 24. Qxf6 Nxf6
25. Kg3 g5 $15 {when White still needs to play precisely to hold this endgame.}
) 21. Ne4 $11 {The position is very close to complete equality. The game
eventually ended in a draw.} Ng5 22. Qg2 Rab8 23. a4 g6 24. Nxg5 hxg5 25. Qe4
Kg7 26. Kg2 Qd7 27. Qc2 e4 28. Rxf8 Rxf8 29. Rf1 Qe7 30. Rxf8 Kxf8 31. Qb1 Qe5
32. Kh1 Qe8 33. Qc2 Qe7 34. Qb1 Kg7 35. Kg2 Kh6 36. Qc2 Qe8 37. Kh1 Qf7 38.
Qxe4 Qf1+ 39. Kh2 Qf2+ 40. Kh1 Qf1+ 1/2-1/2

