20,-11,-38,-34,-105,-99,-75,-69,-124,-116,-150,-144,-144,-144,-144,-144,-334,
-340,-264,-301,-327,-342,-375,-385,-446,-422,-560,-588,-937,-1010] In the
following game, we shall see a clear illustration of Black's ideas after ...
f7-f5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({We will obviously start with
} 4... c5) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. Qc2 $6 {I don't see
how this move contributes to White's general strategy. Sooner or later, White
will play e3-e4, thus making the battery Q+B less effective.} e5 10. d5 Ne7 11.
e4 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gh5f4,Gf7f5] The right approach to the position. Black
is planning to proceed with ...Nh5-f4-d3 followed by ...f7-f5. The arising
position with opposite-coloured bishops will be very difficult for White.
While the c8-bishop is a monster, White's dark-squared bishop is completely
useless in this pawn structure.} 12. h3 Nh5 13. Kh2 Nhf4 14. Ng1 {White's
intentions become clear. He is planning to drive the knight back by means of
g2-g3. Black, however, has something else in mind. As we already discussed,
the position arising after} Nxd3 15. Qxd3 f5 {is very difficult for White.
Black obtained some dream version of King's Indian Defence. If allowed, he
will proceed with ...f5-f4, followed by the march of the g-pawn.} 16. exf5 Bxf5
17. Qg3 Qa5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] Reminding White that his queenside is vulnerable
as well. The next move will be ...Qa4.} 18. f4 Qa4 19. fxe5 Qxc4 $19 {White's
position is hopeless.} 20. Bf4 Bd3 21. Rf3 Nxf4 22. e6 Rf6 23. Re1 Bg6 24. Ref1
Nxd5 25. Rxf6 Nxf6 26. Qxd6 Qxf1 0-1

