{[%evp 0,98,34,34,18,6,15,15,17,17,12,15,16,12,24,8,36,36,37,29,48,36,36,13,13,
-12,27,4,24,27,73,-1,45,14,15,-55,-185,-227,-150,-150,-150,-152,-110,-110,-94,
-141,-90,-90,-111,-100,-108,-128,-96,-116,-103,-90,-90,-157,-88,-83,-86,-104,
-85,-94,-88,-116,-116,-150,-106,-117,-105,-102,-99,-117,-99,-110,-91,-110,-104,
-113,-118,-208,-219,-221,-235,-229,-244,-244,-257,-262,-73,-274,-250,-296,-321,
-346,-351,-351,-326,-504,-562] This example marks the beginning of the
examination of a very important positional element in the Huebner Variation.
In the next examples, we shall see how powerful and multifunctional might be
such a knight.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({Of course, we will
start with the move} 4... c5) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9.
Nd2 ({As we have already seen, after} 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Nd2 {we get
exactly the game position.}) 9... e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 {We already know that
White's plan is to transfer the knight to e3 by means of Re1 followed by
Nf1-e3. Also, we have seen that Black has time to prepare the thematic ...
f7-f5 with ...h7-h6 and ...Nh7.  In this game, however, Black played in a
different way which is also quite interesting -} Ng6 {This move should always
be considered in the Huebner Variation. Since White has already played e3-e4,
Black immediately tries to install a knight on f4. White tried to discourage
this idea with the standard} 12. Re1 {leaving the f1 square available either
for the bishop or the knight. Probably, one of these two options made
Kovalenko refraining from ...Nf4. He played} {The idea of this example, however,
is to examine the powerful} Nf4 13. Nf1 {Transferring the knight to e3 is the
most logical idea.} ({In case of} 13. Bf1 {Black's reaction is exactly the
same -} g5 $3 {Remember this fundamental idea for this pawn structure. Since
the centre is closed, Gaining space on the kingside is a pretty natural idea.
The weak f5-square is not an issue in this position. Whenever the white knight
lands on f5, we will immediately capture it. At the same time, Black can build
a dangerous kingside attack. If allowed, he will follow with ...Kh8, ...Rg8,
and ...Qf8-h6. Also, the move ...g5-g4 will create additional attacking
possibilities on the kingside.} {It's very important that after} 14. g3 {
we just play} Kh8 {[%cal Gf8g8,Gd8f8] followed by ...Rg8 and ...Qf8. We are
never afraid of sacrificing the f4-knight in this pawn structure.} {For
instance, after} 15. gxf4 gxf4 16. Bg2 Rg8 $19 {White should resign. Black is
ready to follow with either ...Ng4 and ...Qh4 or ...Qf8-h6. At the same time,
White cannot bring his pieces to the defence of the kingside.}) 13... g5 $3 {
Again, we opt for this extremely important idea.} 14. Ne3 Kh8 15. g3 {This
move is not threatening at all since we are not afraid of sacrificing the
knight.} ({Let's see what will happen if White does not pay attention to the
kingside.} 15. a4 Rg8 16. Ra2 Qf8 17. a5 Qh6 18. Kh1 Bd7 19. Rb2 Rab8 {White
does not have any constructive ideas. If keeps waiting with a move such as} 20.
Kg1 {Black can play} Ng4 21. Nxg4 Bxg4 22. f3 Bd7 $40 {[%cal Gg5g4] with a
dangerous attack. The advance ...g5-g4 is already on the agenda.}) 15... Ng4 {
By making use of the vulnerable d3-bishop, Black manages to exchange White's
most useful minor piece. The game might continue} 16. Bf1 Nxe3 17. Bxe3 f5 {
Black's attack is very dangerous. As usual, taking the knight with} 18. gxf4 {
is not dangerous for Black. A possible line would be} gxf4 19. Bd2 $2 Rg8+ 20.
Kh1 Qg5 21. Bh3 fxe4 22. Rg1 Bxh3 23. Rxg5 Rxg5 $19 {Black is winning.} *

