{In this example, we will see that installing a knight on f4 is Black's best
bet against White's main line against the Huebner Variation.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5
10. d5 Ne7 11. Nh4 {[%cal Gf2f4] This is White's main line against our system.
Besides taking the f5-square under control, White prepares the advance f2-f4.
For a very long time, Black was struggling to find counterplay against this system.
Modern computers, however, found a very reliable antidote.} Ng6 $1 {It turns
out that this move works perfectly fine in this position as well. If White
does not want to exchange the knights, Black is ready to follow with ...Nf4.} (
{Historically, Black's main line has always been} 11... h6 {with the idea
being to answer f2-f4 with ...Ng6. In this case, however, White can play} 12.
Qf3 $1 {which is a prophylactic move against ...Ng6.} ({The structure arising
after} 12. f4 Ng6 $1 13. Nxg6 fxg6 14. fxe5 dxe5 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd8e8,Gg6g5,
Ge8g6,Gf8f7,Ga8f8,Gf6e8,Ge8d6] is fine for Black. White's bishop pair is not
effective in this static position. On the other hand, Black can improve his
position by means of simple moves such as ...Bd7, ...Qe8, ...g6-g5, ...Qg6
followed by doubling the rooks on the f-file.}) {The problem is that} 12... Ng6
{will be answered with} 13. Nf5 {and after} Bxf5 {White is ready to take with
the queen -} 14. Qxf5 $14 {White has a slight but lasting edge in this line.
Black cannot organize the advance ...f7-f5. At the same time, White can
combine his play along the b-file with the kingside activity based on the
advance f2-f4.}) 12. Nf5 Nf4 $1 {This is the entire point behind Black's
strategy. Otherwise, White will restrict Black's kingside counterplay with
g2-g3.} 13. Bc2 {This is the most challenging continuation. White is now ready
to put pressure on the f4-knight by means of Qf3. Black should react quickly.}
({It's important to know that} 13. Bxf4 $2 {is a mistake.} exf4 14. Qf3 ({
Nothing changes} 14. Qd2 {when Black will play} g5 $1 {again. Remember this
typical move. Black's king is not in danger at all because Black is ready to
eliminate White's only attacking piece. In the arising position, the black
knight will be clearly superior to the white bishop.  Challenging Black's
kingside space advantage with} 15. g3 {is well met by} Bxf5 16. exf5 Kh8 17.
gxf4 g4 $17 {[%cal Gf6h5] Black has an obvious advantage. Ideas like ...Nh5
and ...Qh4 can be very annoying.}) 14... g5 15. g3 {We already know how to
fight against this idea -} Bxf5 16. exf5 {This position occurred in the game
0-1 (33) Ladron de Guevara Galar,F (2029)-Verstraeten,R (2343) Kavala 2019.
Now, Black could have followed with the thematic} Kh8 $1 17. gxf4 g4 18. Qe3
Nh5 $19 {[%cal Gd8h4,Ga8e8] Black is close to winning. He will proceed with ...
Qh4 followed by ...Rae8.}) ({The waiting} 13. Re1 {leaves Black with a
pleasant choice. After analysing for quite some time, I liked} N6h5 {[%cal
Gg7g6] supporting the f4-knight and preparing the kingside play based on ...
g7-g6 followed by ...f7-f5.} ({There is nothing wrong with the simple} 13...
Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Bxf5 ({A huge mistake would be} 14... g6 $2 15. Nh6+ Kg7 16. f4
$16 {when White has a huge advantage in this position with opposite-coloured
bishops.}) 15. exf5 h6 $132 {Black is doing fine in this static position.
After stabilizing the kingside, he can start playing on the other wing. In
such positions, the computer likes the Benko type of sacrifice - ...b7-b5 cxb5,
....a7-a6!}) 14. g3 {White cannot live forever with the f4-knight.} ({The idea
of ...N6h5 can be seen after} 14. Bf1 {[%cal Gd1f3]} g6 15. Ng3 ({After} 15.
Ne3 Qh4 {[%cal Gf7f5] Black has good attacking prospects. He is ready to
proceed with ...f7-f5.}) 15... Ng7 {[%cal Gd8g5,Gf7f5] The advance ...f7-f5 is
already on the agenda. Black can also start with ...Qg5. Depending on the
circumstances, he can also consider the advance of the h-pawn.}) 14... Nxd3 15.
Qxd3 Bxf5 16. exf5 g6 $132 {Black immediately challenges White's space
advantage. White should play very dynamically in order to compensate for his
compromised structure. Practically speaking, Black's play is easier.}) 13... g6
14. Nh6+ {This is the most ambitious continuation. White is planning to follow
with g2-g3 on the next move.} ({The calm} 14. Ne3 {is very well met by} Kh8 {
[%cal Gg6g5,Gg5g4] preparing the thematic advance of the g-pawn.} ({In such
positions, Black shouldn't go for passive play. For instance, after} 14... N4h5
15. g3 Ng7 16. f4 $14 {Dragnev, V (2461)-Oparin, G (2607) Moscow Aeroflot op-A
17th 2018 (7) 0-1 White enjoys a pleasant advantage.}) 15. g3 Nh3+ {The
inclusion of this move before ...g6-g5 seems logical.} ({The thematic} 15... g5
{is possible as well. Even though the following line is not forced, it
illustrates the character of the position.} 16. f3 ({As usual, the
materialistic approach backfires in this pawn structure -} 16. gxf4 gxf4 17.
Ng2 Bh3 {Black's attack is developing by itself. The following straightforward
line is a good illustration.} 18. Kh1 Bxg2+ 19. Kxg2 Rg8+ 20. Kh1 Ng4 {Black's
attack is unstoppable. White cannot defend against both ...Qh4 and ...Nxh2.
For instance, after} 21. Qf3 Nxh2 22. Kxh2 Rg6 $19 {White can already resign.})
16... Bh3 17. Re1 Rg8 18. Kh1 Bd7 {[%cal Gd8f8,Gf8h6] As always, Black is not
afraid of sacrificing the f4-knight. He is now planning to strengthen the
attack with the manoeuvre...Qf8-h6. Even though the position remains balanced,
Black's play is easier. The following funny line is a good illustration -} 19.
Rb1 Rb8 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. exf5 Qf8 22. gxf4 gxf4 23. Rg1 Qh6 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gh5g3]
As usual, White cannot easily bring his pieces to the defence. He should now
reckon with the dangerous threat of ...Nh5-g3.} 24. Bd2 Nh5 25. Rg4 e4 $1 26.
fxe4 Ng3+ 27. Rxg3 Rxg3 28. Bxf4 Qxf4 29. hxg3 Qxg3 30. Qg1 Qf3+ $11 {Finally,
the draw is obvious. Do not try to memorize any of these moves. The entire
line is purely illustrative. What is important is seeing many thematic
patterns. Hopefully, it will be easier for you to recognize them in your own
games.}) 16. Kh1 g5 $15 {Black is slightly better. White does not have any
active plan. At the same time, White is ready to proceed with ...Rg8 followed
by ...Qf8-h6.}) 14... Kg7 ({The alternative} 14... Kh8 {is playable as well.}
15. g3 N6h5 {Again, Black is not impressed by the move g2-g3. He is ready to
sacrifice the knight at any moment.} ({The alternative} 15... Nh3+ 16. Kg2 Ng8
$132 {is playable as well.}) 16. Ng4 ({After} 16. gxf4 Nxf4 {[%cal Gd8g5]} 17.
Ng4 Qg5 18. f3 h5 {White should force a draw by means of} 19. Bxf4 exf4 20. h4
Qxh4 21. Nf2 Qg3+ 22. Kh1 Qh4+ $11 {with a perpetual.}) 16... Nh3+ 17. Kg2 ({
After} 17. Kh1 Ng7 18. Ne3 Qe7 {Black is perfectly well coordinated. The
advance ...f7-f5 is coming.} {It's important to know that the thematic} 19. f4
$2 {can be met with} exf4 20. gxf4 f5 $17 {spoiling White's pawn structure.
Thanks to the move ...Qe7, White cannot play e4-e5.}) 17... Ng5 18. Qe2 Rb8 19.
h3 f6 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gb8b7,Gb7f7];Akdag,M (2543)-Cesetti,C (2560) ARG 200
Years A email 2010 1/2-1/2 Black has decent counterplay in this closed
position. One of his thematic ideas is ...b7-b6 followed by ...Rb7-f7(g7).
Afterwards, the advance ...f6-f5 is always on the agenda.}) 15. g3 Nh3+ 16. Kg2
Qe7 {This move is a prophylactic against f2-f4.} ({The immediate} 16... Ng8 {
can be answered with} 17. Nf5+ $1 gxf5 18. exf5 $16 {with an obvious advantage
for White.}) 17. f3 {This position occurred in the game ½-½ (41) Gligoric,
S-Castillo Bermudez,M Mar del Plata 1950. Now, Black could have played} Ng8 18.
Qd2 f6 19. Ng4 h5 20. Ne3 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gh3g5] with a balanced position. The
game revolves around the advances f3-f4 and ...f6-f5. At any moment, you
should calculate these moves.} *

