-129,-45,-156,-156,-192,-139,-245,-224,-449,-553,-1587,-1603] The advance ...
f7-f5 is not always easy to achieve. Sometimes, Black should find the most
precise move order in order to deliver this break. The following game is a
typical example. The important position arises after White's 11.Ne1.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({Obviously, our move order is} 4... c5) 5. Bd3
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. e4 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Ne1 $5 {[%cal
Ge1c2,Gc2e3] We should pay a lot of attention to this tricky idea. White is
planning to quickly transfer the knight to e3 via the c2-square.  In this case,
Black's most precise reaction is} Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gg6f4] Once again, this move
solves all the problems. We know, how annoying is the threat of ...Nf4.
Therefore, White should spend time on g2-g3.} ({Against 11.Ne1, the standard} 
11... h6 $6 {does not work well. For instance, after} 12. Nc2 Nh7 13. Ne3 f5 $2
{White is just in time to play} 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Qc2 $16 {with a huge
advantage.}) 12. g3 Re8 $2 {This move is a positional mistake. Black admits
that he failed to execute his main counterplay based on ...f7-f5. White has
now an obvious positional advantage.} ({Black should have played} 12... Bh3 13.
Ng2 Ne8 $132 {[%cal Gf7f5] with ...f7-f5 to follow. We can now execute our
light square strategy.}) 13. Ng2 $14 {Even though White eventually lost, he
has an obvious advantage in this position.} Bh3 14. Rb1 Qd7 15. Bg5 Ng4 16. f3
h6 17. fxg4 hxg5 18. Rf5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 f6 20. Rf2 Reb8 21. Rfb2 Qc7 22. Rb5 Nf8
23. Qb3 b6 24. Qd1 Nd7 25. R5b2 a6 26. Qf1 Rb7 27. a4 Rbb8 28. Qf5 Nf8 29. h4
gxh4 30. gxh4 Qd8 31. g5 g6 32. Qg4 Qd7 33. Qxd7 Nxd7 34. Be2 f5 35. h5 Rf8 36.
h6 a5 37. Rf1 Kh7 38. Bd1 Kh8 39. Rbf2 fxe4 40. Rf7 Rxf7 41. Rxf7 Nf8 42. Rf6
Nh7 43. Rxg6 Rf8 44. Bg4 e3 45. Rg7 Rf4 46. Bd1 e4 47. Kg3 Rf5 48. g6 Nf8 49.
Kg4 Rf2 50. Kg5 e2 51. Bxe2 Rxe2 52. Kf6 Rf2+ 53. Ke7 e3 54. Rf7 Nxg6+ 0-1

