{The following blitz game is a good illustration of how Black should fight
against the advance f2-f4. Usually, White tries to execute this idea after
playing d4-d5, without pushing e3-e4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5
5. Bd3 Nc6 ({As we will see a bit later, against 5.Bd3, with start with} 5...
O-O {keeping the b8-knight flexible. In the game, however, the selected move
order didn't make any difference.}) 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd2
e5 10. Re1 {For the time being White prefers keeping the central tension. As
we know, in this case, Black should make as many useful moves as possible.} b6
({A typical inaccuracy would be} 10... Re8 $6 {since after} 11. d5 Ne7 12. e4 {
[%csl Re8] The rook is misplaced on e8. In such positions, it's difficult for
Black to prepare the advance ...f7-f5. The game might continue} Ng6 13. g3 h6
14. Nf1 Nh7 15. Ne3 $14 {White is just in time to bring his knight to the
perfect e3-square. Black does not have counterplay in this position. On the
other hand, White will gradually prepare the advance f2-f4.}) ({Another useful
waiting move (my favourite one) is} 10... h6 {In this case, White should
probably keep maintaining the tension with a useful move such as} 11. Rb1 {
This move was tried by the Bulgarian GM Valentin Iotov in his game against
Papaioannou.} ({After} 11. d5 Ne7 12. e4 Nh7 {we transpose to the game Iotov, V
- Cebalo, M that we have already examined.}) 11... b6 {Black keeps making
useful moves while waiting for the advance d4-d5.} 12. Qf3 Bd7 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14.
Bxe4 Rc8 15. Bd5 {With this move, White is planning to proceed with dxc5
followed by e3-e4. Even though the structure arising after dxc5 ...dxc5 is
quite playable, Black has an even better option.} Kh7 {[%cal Gf7f5] It turns
out that the kingside activity based on the advance ...f7-f5 shouldn't be
underestimated.} 16. dxc5 bxc5 $1 {This is the point. The invasion of the
white rook is harmless. For instance, after} 17. Rb7 f5 $17 {Black's advantage
is out of the question.}) ({In this structure, taking the d4-pawn is almost never
an option. For instance, after} 10... cxd4 11. cxd4 exd4 12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Bb2
$44 {White's bishop pair and better development provide him with tremendous
compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Rb1 Qc7 12. d5 {Sooner or later White should
clarify the centre. With this move, Aleksandrov decides to go for f2-f4.} Ne7
13. f4 {White hopes that the symmetrical structure arising after the ...exf4
will favour him in view of the space advantage and the control of the e-file.
Eljanov, however, demonstrates a typical positional idea that you should always
have in mind.} exf4 14. exf4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] Preparing ...Bf5 on the next
move. The exchange of the light-squared bishops is Black's most important
positional idea in this pawn structure. If possible, Black will also exchange
one pair of knights, so that White would remain with his useless dark-squared
bishop. Due to his superior pawn structure, Black has better long-term
prospects.} 15. Nf3 Bf5 16. Rb2 {[%cal Gb2e2] A typical idea. White is
planning to double the rooks on the e-file.} Rfe8 17. Rbe2 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Nf5
$15 {Black is already slightly better since White does not have enough
compensation for the vulnerable pawn structure.} 19. h3 h5 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21.
Rxe8+ Nxe8 22. g4 Nfg7 23. gxh5 gxh5 24. Be3 Qd7 25. Kg2 Nf6 26. Bf2 Qf5 (26...
Qa4 27. Qe2 Kf8 28. Bh4 Ng8 $15 {[%cal Gg7f5]}) 27. Qxf5 Nxf5 28. Nd2 Kg7 29.
Kf3 Kg6 30. Nf1 a6 31. a4 Ng8 32. Nd2 Nf6 33. Nf1 Ng8 34. Nd2 Nf6 35. Nf1
1/2-1/2

