{[%evp 0,124,28,26,26,6,6,6,32,34,24,15,11,11,24,13,32,32,32,28,48,36,35,39,49,
49,39,25,27,18,25,6,10,-1,28,19,12,26,17,15,8,13,0,0,6,15,22,8,10,14,15,15,37,
-25,-7,-14,15,-6,13,-18,-14,-5,0,0,11,3,7,7,28,38,43,37,48,37,49,20,22,0,20,0,
35,7,12,5,14,-5,-12,-39,15,2,-88,-74,32,-10,0,0,0,-1,35,-15,-8,-40,-42,-55,-66,
-66,-74,-91,-79,-56,0,-20,-23,-66,-64,-110,-136,-264,-264,-754,-753,-803,-803,
-962,-962,-962,-972] Let's take a look at another example which is very
similar to the game of Eljanov.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ({
We will start with} 4... c5) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. Nd2
e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. Qc2 {Compared to the previous example, White is preparing
f2-f4 in a more straightforward way. This time, he does not spend time on
moves such as Re1 and Rb1.} Kh8 {Black is planning to prepare ...f7-f5. With
his last move, he makes sure that White cannot take on h7 with a check. Even
though there is nothing particularly wrong with this move, I think that Black
can play more precisely.} ({As usual, my preference would have been} 11... Ng6
{when Black is more than ready to meet} 12. f4 $2 ({Another option is} 12. g3 {
By taking the control of the f4-square, White prepares the advance e3-e4. On
the downside, the advance g2-g3 weakens the light squares around the white
king.} {Even though the g6-knight is under attack, Black can still play} h6 13.
e4 ({In case of} 13. Bxg6 $2 fxg6 14. Qxg6 Bh3 15. Re1 e4 {Black's better
development as well as the vulnerable white king make White's position
hopeless. For instance, after} 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Qf6 $19 {White can
already resign.}) 13... Nh7 $15 {Black is already slightly better. He is ready
to proceed with ...Bh3 followed by ...Qd7, and ...f7-f5. The knight can join
the attack via the f5-square.}) 12... Ng4 $1 {We have already seen this
typical motif in my comments to the game Roubalik - Banusz.} 13. Ne4 f5 14. Nf2
e4 15. Be2 Nf6 $17 {Black has an obvious advantage. He can gradually prepare
the advance ...g7-g5. At the same time, all white minor pieces are out of play.
}) 12. Rb1 Rb8 {I remind you that this is the better way of protecting the
b7-pawn. When possible, avoid playing ...b7-b6. In this case, the advance
a2-a4-a5 might be annoying.} 13. f4 exf4 14. exf4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gc8f5] Once
again we see this thematic idea. White cannot prevent ...Bf5 on the next move.}
15. Nf3 Bf5 16. Nh4 Qd7 $1 {This is an important positional idea. Holding the
blockade on f5 is more important than exchanging the light-squared bishops.
The thing is that the f4-pawn kills the activity of two important pieces -
f1-rook and c1-bishop.} ({After} 16... Bxd3 17. Qxd3 {[%cal Gf4f5] White has
an obvious advantage in view of f4-f5 which is coming on the next move.}) 17.
Nxf5 Nxf5 $15 {[%csl Rc1] In this blocked position, the knights are clearly
superior to the bishops. Also, White has several structural weaknesses. After
a lot of fighting, Berkes managed to convert his advantage.} 18. Bd2 Rfe8 19. Rfe1
Kg7 20. Qb3 b6 21. Qc2 Nh4 22. h3 h5 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Re1 Rxe1+ 25. Bxe1 Nf5
26. Qe2 h4 27. Bf2 Ng3 28. Bxg3 hxg3 29. Qe3 Qa4 30. Qxg3 Qd1+ 31. Kh2 Qd2 32.
f5 Nh5 33. Qf3 Qf4+ 34. Qxf4 Nxf4 35. Bf1 gxf5 36. Kg3 Nh5+ 37. Kh4 Kh6 38. g3
Nf6 39. Bd3 Nd7 40. Bxf5 Ne5 41. g4 Nxc4 42. g5+ Kg7 43. Bd3 Na3 44. Ba6 c4 45.
Kg4 Nb1 46. Bxc4 Nxc3 47. h4 b5 48. Bd3 b4 49. h5 Nxa2 50. h6+ Kg8 51. Kf5 Nc3
52. g6 fxg6+ 53. Ke6 Kh7 54. Kxd6 Kxh6 55. Kc5 Nxd5 56. Kxd5 g5 57. Ke4 Kh5 58.
Be2+ Kh4 59. Kf5 b3 60. Bc4 b2 61. Ba2 g4 62. Kf4 g3 0-1

