{[%evp 0,60,30,25,38,6,18,15,17,16,25,25,13,20,23,20,31,31,31,30,39,-8,-8,-14,
24,24,10,-11,-11,-12,-6,-5,7,-19,8,5,0,7,3,-66,-85,-95,-102,-97,-99,-117,-114,
-124,-135,-124,-145,-156,-159,-154,-117,-148,-156,-130,-152,-161,-159,-160,
-196] In the next two examples, we shall take a brief look at the structure
that might arise after White's dxc5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O (
{For us, the right move order starts with} 4... c5) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. O-O
Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. Qc2 {This move is strictly connected with White's idea of
exchanging on c5.} e5 10. dxc5 dxc5 11. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e4] Now, the idea behind
9.Qc2 becomes clear. After provoking the advance ...h7-h6, White is going to
exchange the knights via the e4-square. He hopes that the bishop pair as well
as the weak d5-square provide enough compensation for Black's superior pawn
structure. On the other hand, if Black plays precisely, White's temporary
initiative will be extinguished.} h6 12. Ne4 b6 {There is no point in
exchanging the e4-knight. In any case, the white bishop is heading for the
d5-square.} 13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Be4 {[%cal Ge4d5] White's idea in this
structure is pretty simple. After putting the bishop on d5, he wants to follow
with f2-f4. Sometimes, he plays e3-e4 before proceeding with f2-f4. Black's
best strategy is to focus on the weak c4-pawn.} Rb8 15. Bd5 Na5 16. f4 {
As we are going to see in a while, this straightforward continuation has one
important drawback.} ({A bit more precise would have been} 16. e4 {planning
f2-f4 on the next move. In this case, however, Black can play} Ba6 17. Qe2 Rbd8
$15 {[%cal Gd8d5] A very precise move. White cannot proceed with f2-f4 in view
of ...Rxd5.}) 16... Ba6 $6 {This move is an inaccuracy.} ({The thematic
reaction would have been} 16... e4 $1 17. Bxe4 Ba6 $17 {when Black enjoys a
huge advantage. White has spoiled pawn structure and inferior development.}) ({
Another typical option which is enough for an advantage is} 16... Be6 $17) 17.
fxe5 Qxe5 18. Rf5 $2 {After this pointless move, Black has an obvious
advantage.} ({White should have played} 18. e4 {even though after} Rbd8 19. Bf4
Qe7 {Black's chances are still preferable. The c4-pawn will be lost. It will
not be easy for White to prove his compensation for the pawn, at least in a
practical game.}) 18... Qe7 $17 19. Rh5 Qf6 20. Rf5 Qg6 21. e4 Bxc4 22. Bf4
Rbd8 23. Rd1 Bxd5 24. exd5 Nc4 25. Bc1 Rfe8 26. Qf2 Qg4 27. Qf1 Nd6 28. Rf3 Qa4
29. h3 Qxa2 30. Bf4 Ne4 0-1

