{[%evp 0,117,25,30,30,0,0,0,11,28,28,18,23,23,43,43,36,40,29,24,52,36,60,30,33,
-32,32,32,17,-49,-50,-44,-42,-44,-80,-187,-185,-185,-185,-185,-185,-185,-185,
-192,-39,-39,-43,-43,-43,-43,-43,-43,-43,-43,-51,-40,-49,-48,-48,-77,-77,-71,
-62,-133,-47,-49,-59,-83,-66,-67,-75,-160,-161,-132,-153,-228,-239,-244,-191,
-184,-177,-200,-179,-176,-155,-162,-155,-149,-162,-156,-148,-166,-156,-175,
-146,-173,-99,-101,-95,-95,-95,-95,-69,-62,-30,-31,-30,-30,-38,-27,-24,-47,-43,
-43,-37,-41,-44,-50,-49,-47]} {Another interesting line is} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 ({In this particular case, our move order will
be} 5... O-O) 6. Nf3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd2 e5 10. Ne4 {White
employs the idea from the previous example, without wasting time for Qc2.
After occupying the e4-square with the bishop, White will consider dxc5. As
always, playing against the c4-pawn is Black's most precise strategy.
Therefore, the right continuation is} Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Na5 {Black starts
attacking the c4-pawn before White manages to organise his forces. The most
challenging continuation seems to be} 12. dxc5 ({Delaying the exchange on c5
does not provide any benefits -} 12. Qd3 Kh8 13. Bd5 {This position was
reached in the game ½-½ (48) Moll, R (2642)-Neto, H (2615) ICCF email 2012.
Now, Black could have expanded on the kingside by means of} f5 $15 {when his
position is obviously preferable.}) ({A typical reaction to} 12. Bd5 {is} Be6
$11 {when Black is at least equal.}) 12... dxc5 {As we have seen from the
previous example, in this pawn structure, things can go very wrong for White.
Therefore, he should play extremely dynamic chess in order to maintain 
balance. In this regard, a logical move would be} 13. Qh5 h6 14. Bd5 {[%cal
Ge3e4,Gf2f4] preparing the most thematic idea in this pawn structure - e3-e4
followed by f2-f4.} ({Taking the pawn with} 14. Qxe5 {is harmless. The
following sequence seems pretty convincing -} Re8 15. Qf4 Qg5 $1 {A nice
decision. After the exchange of the queens, it will not be easy for White to
keep the position together.} 16. Qxg5 hxg5 17. Bd5 Be6 18. f3 f6 19. e4 Rad8
$11 {Black is ready to proceed with ...b7-b6 followed by ...Nxc4. In this case,
he would enjoy comfortable equality.}) 14... Be6 {Remember this typical move.
Black immediately emphasizes the weak c4-pawn. A logical follow-up would be}
15. e4 Qd6 16. f4 Nxc4 17. f5 Bxd5 18. f6 Bxe4 19. Bxh6 gxf6 20. Bxf8 Qe6 $132
{Black's domination on the light squares provides more than enough
compensation for the exchange.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2022.10.24"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.Bd3 and 6.Nge2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "E48"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "55"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.10.28"]

{This example is dedicated to one extremely important setup - Bd3 followed by
Nge2. I will suggest a straightforward solution that allows Black to solve all
the problems.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 O-O {Starting
with this move is important for our line. As we will see a bit later, in some
lines, we can develop the b8-knight to c6.} ({The usual continuation is} 5...
Nc6 6. Nge2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {when the play is very similar to our main line.})
6. Nge2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {Since White has developed his knight on e2 it makes
sense to opt for IQP structure. When playing with an isolated pawn, White
usually prefers to have a knight on f3, so that the active Ne5 could be
possible. Nevertheless, in some cases, White can use the position of the
knight to his advantage.} 8. cxd5 {This is the most precise continuation. By
forcing the black knight to d5, White can often use the vulnerability of the
h7-pawn.} ({Many games saw the harmless} 8. O-O {In this case, Black will
continue with} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nc6 $132 {with a very favourable version of IQP.
The e2-knight is definitely misplaced. I will not dive into details about this
position since basic IQP knowledge will be enough for you.}) ({To an IQP type
of position also leads} 8. a3 {In this case, Black's most precise reaction
seems to be} dxc4 9. Bxc4 Bd6 {When possible, it's preferable to put the
bishop on an active position. The pin created by} 10. Bg5 {is not dangerous.
Black can follow with} Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] with a preferable
position. If allowed, we will proceed with ...a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5 and ..
.Bb7.}) ({The most thematic way of meeting} 8. c5 {is} b6 {immediately
challenging White's space advantage on the queenside. Obviously, White is not
interested in taking on b6 because Black will put simultaneous pressure on d4
and b2. The following sequence illustrates the character of the position -} 9.
a3 Bxc3+ 10. Nxc3 Nc6 11. Bb5 Bb7 12. O-O bxc5 13. dxc5 d4 $132 {Black's
powerful centre gives him many dynamic possibilities. For the time being,
White's queenside majority is not significant.}) 8... Nxd5 9. O-O Re8 $5 {
I like this flexible move which was recently employed by Lenier Dominguez.
After an eventual exchange on d5, Black will recapture with the e-pawn. In
this case, the rook will be very well placed on e8. Besides, in some cases,
retreating the bishop to f8 could be very useful.} ({The standard continuation
} 9... Nc6 10. a3 Bd6 {is playable as well.}) 10. Nxd5 {White is going for a
symmetrical pawn structure. Analysis shows that Black is ready for a such
transformation of the pawn structure.} ({In case of} 10. a3 {we already prefer}
Bf8 $1 11. Re1 ({The symmetrical structure arising after} 11. Nxd5 exd5 {
is not dangerous for Black. White usually tries to put pressure on d5 by means
of} 12. Nf4 {when Black can simply follow with} Nc6 {The following line is
quite characteristic for such positions.} 13. Be3 Bd6 {With this move, Black
prepares ...Qh4. Also, it's important to point out that in such positions we
are ready to exchange the bishop for the white knight. If such an exchange is
followed by an exchange of the light-squared bishops as well, Black can even
fight for an advantage.} 14. Qf3 Qh4 {Black puts indirect pressure on the
d4-pawn. The idea is to provoke the weakening g2-g3 which will be answered
with ...Qf6.} 15. Rfe1 Be6 {Black keeps the tension.} ({A perfectly natural
alternative would have been} 15... Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qxf4 17. Bxf4 Be6 $11 {
with equality.}) 16. g3 Qf6 {Now, White should think about how to deal with the
vulnerable d4-pawn. The attempt to win a pawn by means of} 17. Qh5 g6 18. Nxd5
{is met by the powerful} Qd8 19. Qf3 Be5 $1 {It turns out that Black will
regain the material in a comfortable way. Let's continue for just a few moves.}
20. Bc4 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Nxd4 22. Qd3 Bxd5 23. Rxe8+ Qxe8 24. Bxd5 Qe5 $11 {
The position is absolutely equal.}) 11... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6] The knight is
heading for the f6-square. That's why we have delayed the move ...Nc6.} 12.
Nxd5 ({After} 12. Nf4 N7f6 $11 {Black is very solid.}) 12... exd5 $11 {In this
symmetrical structure, the knight is better placed on d7 than on c6. Black can
now consider developing activity by means of simple moves such as ...Nf6-e4,
and ...Bd6.}) ({The attempt to put pressure on d5 by means of} 10. Be4 {
is harmless. After} Nc6 {the most logical follow-up is} 11. Qd3 {provoking ...
h7-h6 and planning to increase the pressure on d5 by means of Qf3.} ({
Completely harmless is} 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. Bf3 Bf5 13. Ng3 {This position
occurred in the game 0-1 (32) Vaisser, A (2501)-Kuzubov, Y (2642) Tornelo INT
2021. Now, the simple} Bg6 $11 {would have given Black comfortable equality.}
) 11... h6 12. Qf3 ({In case of} 12. Rd1 Nf6 13. Bf3 e5 $11 {Black equalises
immediately.}) 12... Nf6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qxc6 Rb8 $44 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black's
powerful bishop pair and good development provide excellent compensation for
the pawn. The next move is going to be ...Bb7.}) ({In IQP type of positions,
we should always reckon with the idea} 10. Bc2 Nc6 11. Qd3 {This typical
battery is less dangerous when the knight is on e2 and not on f3.} g6 12. Rd1 (
{The idea of putting pressure on d5 with} 12. Qf3 {is easily neutralized by
means of} Qf6 $132) 12... Bf8 $1 {I like this idea a lot. The bishop will be
perfectly placed on g7. From this position, besides securing the safety of the
king, the bishop will also be putting pressure on d4.} 13. Qf3 Bg7 14. Be4 {
Focusing on the critical d5-square is White's only constructive strategy.
Black, however, has enough resources at his disposal.} Nce7 15. Bg5 {White
managed to fully activate his pieces. As we will see, however, this is not
enough.} ({After} 15. Nf4 {Black should be ready to sacrifice a pawn with} Nf6
16. Bxb7 Bxb7 17. Qxb7 Nf5 18. Nfe2 Nd5 $132 {Black had an excellent
compensation for the pawn in the game ½-½ (30) Salzmann, S (2310)-Vormelker, C
(2305) ICCF email 2017}) 15... h6 $1 {This cold-blooded reaction kills White's
initiative.} 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Once again, we can see how strong was the
inclusion of ...Re8. Because of the indirect pressure on the e-file, White
cannot win a pawn.} 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Nf4 ({After} 18. Qxd5 $2 Bg4 $17 {
White's position is already very dangerous.}) 18... Qg5 {[%cal Gc8g4]} 19. h3
Bf5 $132 {Black's piece activity shouldn't be underestimated. Probably, White
should go for the following sequence -} 20. Nfxd5 Rad8 21. Ne3 Rxd4 22. Rxd4
Bxd4 23. Nxf5 Qxf5 24. Qxf5 gxf5 $11 {with an equal endgame.}) 10... exd5 11.
Nf4 Nc6 12. Be3 Bd6 {We already know that this structure is not dangerous for
Black. White's temporary initiative can be easily extinguished.} 13. Qf3 {
This move was played by Swiercz in his game against Lenier Dominguez played in
2022.} ({The alternative} 13. Qh5 {is well met by} g6 14. Qf3 Qh4 15. g3 Qf6 {
As usual, after provoking g2-g3, the queen occupies the comfortable f6-square.
The d4-pawn is now under pressure.} {A huge mistake would be} 16. Qxd5 $2 {
which was played in the game 0-1 (36) Savina, A (2333)-Wirig, A (2500) Chalons
en Champagne 2021. Now, after the simple} Bxf4 {White is almost lost.} 17. gxf4
({In case of} 17. Bxf4 Nxd4 $19 {[%cal Ge8d8] followed by ...Rd8, Black has a
winning advantage. Moves such as ...Bg4, ...Bh3, and ...g6-g5 are very
annoying. White cannot handle the weakness of the light squares around the
king.}) 17... Nb4 $17 {White's terrible structure and vulnerable king give
Black a huge advantage.}) 13... Qh4 14. g3 Qg4 {The most precise continuation.
The arising endgame is completely equal.} 15. Qxg4 Bxg4 16. Nxd5 Rad8 17. Nc3
Be5 $1 $11 {The last finesse. After a few more moves, the draw was agreed.} 18.
Be2 Bxe2 19. Nxe2 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Bxd4 21. Bxd4 Rxd4 22. Rfd1 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Kf8
24. Rd7 Re7 25. Rd8+ Re8 26. Rd7 Re7 27. Rd8+ Re8 28. Rd7 {1/2-1/2 (28)
Swiercz,D (2652)-Dominguez Perez,L (2747) Saint Louis 2022} *

