{Finally, I will show a very practical variation against the topical 5.Nge2.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Nge2 {The idea of this move is
obvious. In case of ...Bxc3, White would like to recapture on c3 with the
knight. Therefore, his next move is going to be a2-a3. On the downside, the
development of the kingside is now more difficult. In our line, we will try to
make use of White's problems in the development.} d5 6. a3 {This is the only
way to fight for an advantage.} ({After} 6. cxd5 {the simplest solution is}
Nxd5 {The pressure on c3, slows down White's kingside development.} 7. a3 ({
To massive simplifications leads} 7. Bd2 {After} cxd4 8. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2
Qxd5 10. Nxd4 O-O $11 {the position is completely equal.}) 7... Nxc3 8. Nxc3 ({
After} 8. bxc3 Ba5 $15 {White has problems completing the development. After
castling, Black can strike in the centre with ...e6-e5.}) 8... Ba5 $1 {This
move is a recurring motif in this line. Black wants to get a favourable
version of IQP by means of ...cxd4. In order to rule out that possibility,
White can play} 9. dxc5 {The thematic reaction to dxc5 is} Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Bxc3
11. bxc3 Nd7 {Black would like to obtain a nice static advantage with ...Nxc5
on the next move. In such a case, the bishop pair cannot compensate for the
spoiled pawn structure. White's most logical try is} 12. c6 {when instead of
taking the pawn, Black should play for compensation -} Ne5 13. c7 {This
position was reached in the game 1-0 (68) Aleksandrov, A (2612)-Vaibhav, S (2448)
Chennai 2012. Now, the most precise would have been} Bd7 14. Rb1 Bc6 {The
c7-pawn is doomed. Sooner or later, Black will take it. White should play very
dynamically in order to compensate for the inferior structure. A possible line
would be} 15. Bb5 Kd7 16. f4 Ng4 17. Bxc6+ Kxc6 18. Ke2 Rhc8 $11 {Even though
the position is equal, playing with Black is simpler.}) ({Another possibility
is} 6. dxc5 O-O 7. a3 Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 {When possible, we should put our bishop
on the active d6-square. In this position, the bishop will be stronger both in
IQP type of position and in symmetrical structure arising after ...dxc4.} 9.
Bb2 Nc6 $132 {Black has a very nice counterplay. White should already reckon
with the threat of ...dxc4. The position with an IQP arising after} 10. cxd5
exd5 {is favourable for Black in view of his better development and the
misplaced e2-knight.}) 6... Ba5 $1 {This is the entire point of our variation.
Black wants to obtain a favourable version of IQP without parting with the
bishop pair. I think that 6...Ba5 will become the main line.} ({Even though
the traditional} 6... Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 cxd4 8. exd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nc6 {is playable,
White's bishop pair gives him some chances for the initiative.}) 7. dxc5 {
This is the critical line.} ({Completely harmless is} 7. cxd5 {when Black's
best reaction is} cxd4 8. exd4 {This move allows Black to get a favourable
version of IQP.} ({More logical would have been} 8. Nxd4 Nxd5 9. Qc2 {Now, one
of the ways to get a decent position is the following sequence -} Nxc3 10. b4 Nd5
11. bxa5 Qxa5+ 12. Bd2 Qc7 13. Qxc7 Nxc7 14. Rc1 Nba6 15. Nb5 Nxb5 16. Bxb5+
Bd7 17. Bxa6 bxa6 $11 {The position is completely equal since Black's extra
pawn is not significant.}) 8... Nxd5 9. b4 {This position occurred in the game
½-½ (51) Heimann,A (2599)-Keymer,V (2591) Dortmund 2021. Now, Black could
have played} Bb6 10. Nxd5 exd5 $15 {with a slightly better position. In
symmetrical structures, the activity of the pieces is what matters. In this
case, the superior activity of the black pieces is obvious.}) 7... dxc4 {
A very nice way to use the drawback of the move 5.Nge2. The a5-bishop is very
annoying. Whenever the white knight leaves the e2-square, we are ready to
spoil White's pawn structure by means of ...Bxc3.} 8. Qxd8+ {The most natural
and popular continuation. Having development problems, White is aiming for an
endgame.} ({Another very logical option is} 8. Bd2 {[%cal Ge2g3] By defending
against ...Bxc3, White is ready to continue with Ng3 followed by Bxc4. In this
case, I like the dynamic} O-O 9. Ng3 b6 $1 {The best way of eliminating the
c5-pawn. After the eventual ...bxc5, besides increasing the central control,
Black will be able to play along the b-file.} 10. Bxc4 {The safest choice.} ({
One of the ideas behind 9...b6 is that after} 10. cxb6 Bb7 {it's not easy for
White to develop the kingside. A possible line would be} 11. Bxc4 Bxg2 12. Rg1
Bc6 13. bxa7 Nbd7 $44 {[%cal Gd7e5] when Black has excellent compensation in
view of the vulnerable white king. He is now ready to continue with ...Ne5.})
10... bxc5 11. Qc2 {White's idea is to enjoy his slightly better structure
after stabilizing the position. As we will see, however, Black has enough
counterplay.} ({Similar positions arise after} 11. O-O Bb7 12. Be2 Nbd7 13. Qc2
Rc8 $132 {[%cal Gc5c4] This position occurred in the game ½-½ (25) Novak,V 
(2424)-Kunzelmann,F (2491) ICCF email 2018. White should now reckon with the
idea of ...c5-c4 followed by ...Ne5. Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 11...
Nbd7 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rad1 {White keeps mobilising his army.} ({The
simplifications arising after} 13. Nce4 Bxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxa5 Qxa5 16.
Qxe4 Rab8 $11 {lead to a balanced position. The play along the b-file fully
compensates for the slightly weak c5-pawn.}) 13... h5 {Nowadays, strong
players consider this advance in every position. Especially with a knight on
g3, this idea works very well.} ({Also, there is nothing wrong with the
standard idea of preparing ...c5-c4 -} 13... Ne5 14. Be2 c4 {White has nothing
better than forcing exchanges by means of} 15. Nce4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxd2 17. Nxd2
Rc8 $132 {Black is doing fine. It turns out that the c4-pawn is a hard nut to
crack. For instance, after} 18. Nxc4 $2 {Black is winning -} Rxc4 19. Bxc4 ({
After} 19. Qxc4 {the intermediate} Qg5 $19 {decides the game.}) 19... Nf3+ $1 {
This is the point.} 20. Kh1 (20. gxf3 Qg5+ 21. Kh1 Bxf3#) 20... Qh4 21. h3 Nd4
$1 $19 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gd4c2,Gh4h3,Gb7h1] The final finesse. White should
resign in view of the double threat.}) 14. Nge4 Qc7 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $132 {
Black obtained an adequate counterplay in the game ½-½ (45) Nihal, S (2620)
-Keymer,V (2591) Biel 2021. White should pay attention to his vulnerable king.}
) ({The attempt to quickly win the c4-pawn by playing} 8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. Qxc4 {
is quite risky since White is behind in development.} ({Pointless is} 9.
Nd4 $2 e5 10. Nf3 Bxc3+ {Black is more than happy to play this move when White
is forced to recapture with b-pawn. After} 11. bxc3 Qc7 12. Bxc4 O-O 13. Qc2
Nxc5 $17 {Black has a huge advantage thanks to his superior structure. White's
bishop pair is not of any significance.}) 9... O-O {[%cal Gd7e5] White should
now deal with the terrible threat of ...Ne5-d3. Therefore, the logical
continuation is} 10. Ng3 {If given enough time, White will complete the
development with Be2 followed by 0-0.} b5 $1 {Black keeps playing in a dynamic
fashion. This precise continuation is also advocated by the computer.} 11. Qxb5
$6 {White is playing into Black's hand.} ({Relatively better would have been} 
11. cxb6 {Nevertheless, after} Bb7 $44 {it's still not easy for White to
complete the development.}) 11... Bxc3+ 12. bxc3 Rb8 13. Qc4 Qa5 14. Be2 Ba6
$15 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (14) Hamidi, A (2276)-Keymer, V 
(2654) Chess.com INT 2022. Black better structure and superior development
provide fantastic compensation for the material.}) ({The typical response to} 
8. Nd4 $6 {is} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. a4 O-O 11. Qc2 Nbd7 12. Bxc4 Nxc5 $15 {
Usually, in this structure, Black is doing better since White's bishop pair
cannot compensate for the structural problems.}) 8... Bxd8 {[%cal Gb8d7]
Black's next move is going to be ...Nbd7. Most likely, the pawns on the c-file
will be exchanged. Black does not have problems in the arising symmetrical
position.} 9. Nd4 {This is the most natural continuation.} ({The alternative} 
9. Ng3 {is not dangerous. The natural continuation of the game would be} Nbd7
10. Bxc4 Nxc5 11. b4 Ncd7 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O a5 $11 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gc8d7,Gd8e7]
Immediately undermining White's queenside. Black is ready to continue with
logical moves such as ...Nb6, followed by ...Bd7, and ...Be7. In this
structure, very often the d7-knight is more flexible than his colleague on c3.}
) 9... Nbd7 10. Bxc4 {This is the most reliable choice.} ({Keeping the c4-pawn
alive can be risky. For instance, a high-profile game saw} 10. c6 Ne5 11. Ncb5
$2 {1/2-1/2 (53) Aleksandrov,A (2595)-Tunik,G (2480) St Petersburg 1998} {
Now, Black could have played} Ne4 {[%cal Gd8a5] creating the annoying threat
of ...Ba5. The following sequence looks pretty logical -} 12. c7 Be7 {[%cal
Ga7a6]} 13. f4 Nd3+ 14. Bxd3 cxd3 15. Bd2 Bd7 16. Nc3 Nd6 $17 {Black has an
obvious advantage. While the c7-pawn is doomed, the d3-pawn is alive and
kicking. Also, we shouldn't forget the potential impact of the bishop pair.})
10... Nxc5 11. f3 {White takes the e4-square away from the knight before
playing b2-b4.} ({In case of the immediate} 11. b4 Nce4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bb2
Bd7 14. f3 Nd6 $11 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga8c8,Gf7f6,Ge6e5,Gd7e6] This position
occurred in the game 1-0 (59) Vusatiuk, V (2308)-Bluebaum, M (2637) Chess.com
INT 2022. If White plays passively, the weak c4-square might tell in the
future. Black can try to use it by means of ...Rc8, ...f7-f6, ...e6-e5, and ...
Be6.}) 11... Bd7 12. e4 Bb6 {Blakc immediately makes use of the newly weakened
diagonal a7-g1.} 13. e5 {The only challenging continuation.} ({Nothing gives} 
13. Ndb5 Ke7 14. b4 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 {This position occurred in the game 1-0 (79)
Shimanov, A (2586)-Vaibhav, S (2430) Chennai 2011. At this point, Black should
have opted for} Ncd7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gh8c8,Gd7e5,Ge5c4] planning ...Rhc8
followed by ...Ne5. Fighting for the c4-square is a recurring theme in this
pawn structure.} 16. Bb2 Rhc8 17. Bb3 a6 18. Nd4 h5 $15 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gd7e5,
Ge5c4] Not only preventing White from gaining kingside space but also planning
to follow with ..h5-h4 under favourable circumstances. Also, the idea ...
Ne5-c4 is always on the agenda. Black is actually slightly better in this
position.}) ({Completely harmless is} 13. Be3 Rc8 14. Be2 Na4 ({Another good
option is} 14... e5 15. Nc2 Be6 $11 {with full equality.}) 15. Nxa4 Bxa4 16.
Kf2 Ke7 $11 {½-½ (33) Stefanova, A (2496)-Vaibhav, S (2527) Jakarta 2013. The
position is completely equal.}) 13... Nd5 $1 {This precise move is the only
thing that you need to remember. This resource is possible due to the
vulnerable d4-knight.} 14. Bxd5 {This move marks the beginning of a forced
sequence.} exd5 15. Nxd5 Nd3+ 16. Kd2 Bxd4 17. Kxd3 ({After} 17. Nc7+ Kd8 18.
Kxd3 Bxb2 19. Bxb2 Kxc7 20. Ke3 Be6 $11 {the position is completely equal.})
17... Bxe5 18. Re1 f6 19. Nc7+ ({In case of} 19. f4 Be6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21.
Rxe6+ Kf7 $44 {White's inferior development provides Black with excellent
compensation for the pawn.}) 19... Kf7 20. Rxe5 fxe5 21. Nxa8 Rxa8 $11 {
The endgame is equal.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
