[White "Fighting the Rare Lines"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "18"]
[SourceVersionDate "2022.10.28"]

{Despite its title, the last lecture is not entirely focused on rare systems
since the vast majority of the examples feature the variation} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {This aggressive and ambitious variation is very popular
in grandmaster practice. Just like in the system with 4.a3, White is planning
to build a strong pawn centre with e2-e4.} ({In this lecture, I also cover} 4.
Bd2) ({and} 4. Qb3 {which are quite harmless. In both cases, we follow with ...
c7-c5. Even though I provide concrete lines, knowing the exact theory is not that
important for Black. Very often, in these lines, Black gets a favourable version
of the structures arising in the line with 4.Qc2 c5. I advise you not to study
these 2 variations in depth. Knowing the basic ideas and setups is more than
enough to play with confidence.}) {Being consistent with our previous choice,
our move is again} 4... c5 {The first important crossroads arises after} 5. d5
({Note that after} 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 {we reach a position that
is examined in the first lecture.}) 5... b5 6. e4 ({After} 6. dxe6 $2 fxe6 7.
cxb5 d5 $36 {Black gets a fantastic version of the Bluemenfeld Gambit.}) 6...
d6 {Now, White faces some choice. He should decide how to develop the kingside
pieces. In the first model games, I prove that the natural development based
on Bd3 and Ne2 does not work well since it's time-consuming. White can also
try to improve this idea by starting with 7.a3. Nevertheless, Black has decent
play in this case as well. Neglecting the kingside development with 7.Bg5 is
also very risky. Black usually goes for a Benoni type of structure which
provides him with a wide range of dynamic possibilities. Putting pressure on
d6 with dxe6 followed by Bf4 is also not enough. Black's superior development
gives him enough compensation. The most logical continuation is} 7. Nge2 ({
Another move which is popular on the highest level is} 7. Bd2 {By creating the
threat of Nxb5, White tries to force Black to release the queenside tension. I
prove that the Benoni structure arising after} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 b4 9. Bd2 exd5 10.
cxd5 O-O {is quite acceptable for Black. The lack of the powerful dark-squared
bishop is compensated by Black's superior development. In this structure, our
counterplay is based on the advance ...f7-f5.}) 7... bxc4 8. Nf4 {This is one
of the most important positions of the variation with 4.f3. By putting
pressure on e6, White wants to provoke the advance ...e6-e5. When the centre
is closed, he will have enough time to develop his pieces and organize his
kingside activity. In this position, I provide two options. The most common
one is} e5 {when Black is going for a strategic battle where the positional
understanding is more important than the knowledge of concrete lines.} ({
A modern and energetic way of playing is} 8... g5 $5 {which is getting very
popular recently. The main line goes} 9. Nfe2 exd5 10. exd5 Qe7 11. Bxg5 Bxc3+
12. bxc3 Nbd7 {This position is highly complex and imbalanced. In my analysis,
you will find some deep computer lines which prove the reliability of Black's
approach. In my opinion, practically speaking, Black's play is a bit easier.
While White will be busy trying to untangle his kingside, Black can proceed
with natural moves such as ...Rg8 and ...Ne5.  If you like dynamic and
irrational play, the move 8...g5 is definitely for you.}) 9. Nfe2 Nbd7 {
In this position, White's main idea is to create kingside activity. He has two
options: 1) going for the immediate g2-g4 followed by Ng3 2) prioritising the
development with Ng3 followed by Be2 and 0-0 In my analysis, you will find
that Black has sufficient counterplay in both cases.  If you are a positional
player, I advise you to focus on 8...e5.} *

