{[%evp 0,36,16,21,29,-11,-3,-3,4,-44,-5,-8,-12,-17,5,-9,-6,-6,-6,-21,17,-37,-8,
7,-6,0,13,9,-6,8,17,-16,29,37,20,-9,48,48,11] At the beginning, we shall see
what happens if White accepts the pawn sacrifice.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 ({Note that after} 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. e4 d6 {
we reach a position that was examined under 4.a3 move order.}) 5... b5 {
In my opinion, this continuation is dubious. Black can fight for an advantage
in this line.} 6. dxe6 ({In the next examples, we will also deal with} 6. e4 {
which is the main line.}) 6... fxe6 7. cxb5 d5 {Black managed to achieve a
fantastic version of the Bluemenfeld Gambit. It's obvious that the move f2-f3
is more than welcome for Black. Also, instead of having his bishop on f8,
Black has managed to develop it on b4. In this example, I will demonstrate how
Black should develop his initiative.} 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd2 {White is planning to
simplify the position with Na4. Therefore, energetic play is required from
Black.} e5 $6 {This move is slightly inaccurate since it gives White the
necessary time to organize his counterplay.} ({The most precise way of
developing the initiative would have been} 9... d4 $1 10. exd4 cxd4 11. Na4 ({
The alternative} 11. Nce2 {does not solve the problems. After} Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2
e5 $17 {Black has fantastic compensation for the pawn. In a practical game,
White wouldn't survive for too long.}) 11... Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Ne4 $1 {Remember
this typical attacking idea. The next move is ...Qh4.} 13. fxe4 Qh4+ 14. g3
Qxe4+ $17 {Obviously, White does not have enough compensation for the exchange.
}) 10. Na4 $2 {Played at the wrong moment.} ({The computer suggestion is} 10.
e4 {By provoking ...d5-d4, White wants to make use of the diagonal a2-g8. For
instance, after} d4 11. Na4 {the thematic} Nxe4 {does not work so well since
after} 12. Bxb4 Qh4+ 13. g3 Nxg3 14. Qb3+ Kh8 15. hxg3 Qxh1 16. Bxc5 Qxg1 17.
O-O-O $13 {the position is completely unclear.}) 10... Qe7 {Another slow and
passive move. After mutual inaccuracies, the game finally ended in a draw.} ({
Better would have been to increase the queenside tension by means of} 10... a6
$1 $17 {with a huge advantage for Black.}) 11. Bxb4 cxb4 12. Rc1 Be6 13. Nc5
Bf7 14. Nh3 Nbd7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 16. Be2 Nb6 17. b3 Qh4+ 18. Nf2 Qg5 1/2-1/2

