{[%evp 0,36,40,1,19,19,23,22,15,-28,13,13,31,31,34,-8,45,13,14,12,46,26,26,26,
42,42,23,22,22,22,22,22,23,13,33,23,30,2,2] In this example, we shall take a
look at one natural setup - 6.e4 followed by Bd3 and Nge2. We will see why
this idea does not work quite well against our system.} 1. c4 e6 2. d4 Nf6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 {This is by far the main move. You will likely
face it in almost all of your games.} d6 {In my opinion, this is the most
practical choice. Besides increasing central control, this move makes sure
that Black does not have to reckon with e4-e5 ideas.} 7. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2]
White's idea is to complete the development in a harmonious way. He is ready
to continue with 8.Nge2 followed by 0-0. The problem with this setup is that
the centre is falling apart.} ({A tricky way to implement the idea with Bd3
followed by Nge2 is} 7. a3 $5 Ba5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 {In this case, Black's
most precise reaction is} bxc4 10. Bxc4 Ba6 ({Playing by analogy to the main
line is a bad idea. After} 10... exd5 11. Bxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 {the move} Be6 $2
{is losing on the spot. The problem is that after} 13. Qxa8 Qb6 {White has} 14.
b4 $18 {winning on the spot. This is where the inclusion of the move a2-a3
helps White.}) 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 {Practice, as well as computer analysis, show that
Black has plenty of counterplay in this position.} 12. O-O ({After} 12. dxe6
fxe6 13. O-O {Black's most precise reaction is} c4 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5d3]
planning ...Nc5-d3.} 14. Be3 Bb6 15. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 16. Qd4 Nc5 $132 {Marciz,A 
(2455)-Zidu, J (2494) FICGS rapid silver 000265 email 2020 (2) 1/2-1/2 with an
adequate counterplay.}) ({Pinning the knight with} 12. Bg5 {is a logical way.
White is planning to proceed with Qa4 followed by either 0-0 or 0-0-0.} Rb8 13.
Qa4 {Gupta, A (2631)-Arjun, K (2513) Dubai op 22nd 2022 (7) 1-0 This position
occurred in the game. Now, a logical try would have been} Bxc3+ 14. Nxc3 Nc7
15. O-O-O exd5 16. exd5 h6 17. Bh4 a6 $132 {[%cal Gc7b5] with a decent
counterplay. Black is ready to follow with ...Nb5.}) 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5
14. Qxd5 Nc7 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black managed to achieve an easy equality. His
next move is going to be ...d6-d5.}) 7... O-O 8. Nge2 bxc4 9. Bxc4 exd5 10.
Bxd5 {In order to fight for something, White should recapture on d5 with the
bishop.} ({After} 10. exd5 Nbd7 {White's setup does not make sense. The
c4-bishop is quite problematic. Black is ready to follow with ...Ne5 on the
next move. Also, the pawn on f3 weakens the kingside.} 11. O-O Ne5 {Black is
already better. In case of a move like Bb3, Black is ready to develop
tremendous initiative with ...Ba6 and ...Re8. White should also reckon with
the idea ...c5-c4 followed by ...Nd3.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 {White is relying
a lot on this move. It turns out, however, that the threat Qxa8 is not that
dangerous.} Be6 $1 12. Qxa8 {The most principled continuation.} ({In case of} 
12. Qd1 {my suggestion would be} f5 $1 {which is the most effective way of
challenging White's centre. The following line is a good illustration of how
the game might continue.} 13. O-O fxe4 14. Nxe4 d5 {Building a mobile pawn
centre is the main idea behind the break ...f7-f5. If White does not play
energetically, Black's central pawns will win the game. The most logical
sequence is} 15. Nf4 Bf7 16. a3 dxe4 17. axb4 cxb4 18. fxe4 Qxd1 19. Rxd1 Nc6
$15 {The vulnerable e4-pawn as well as the queenside majority provide Black
with a slight edge in this endgame.}) 12... Qb6 {[%cal Gb8c6] This is the
point. Black will trap the queen with ...Nc6 on the next move.} 13. O-O Nc6 14.
Qxf8+ Kxf8 {Two rooks for a queen is one of the most classical material
imbalances. Since there are no open files for the white rooks, I think that
practically speaking Black's play is easier. Nevertheless, the correspondence
game that we are currently following shows that when we analyze with strong
engines, the position is balanced.} 15. Nf4 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bc4 17. Rd1 Ne5 18.
Bd2 Qb2 {Loeffler, W (2365)-Doric, N (2388) GER CM/04-B email 2017 1/2-1/2 Even
though a draw was agreed here, practically speaking I still prefer Black.} *

