{[%evp 0,62,40,19,27,21,21,23,22,-25,17,17,31,22,31,11,15,-17,-13,-51,8,18,18,
18,18,4,9,12,12,11,11,11,11,-22,-26,-29,-34,-44,-58,-72,-34,-44,-30,-78,-79,
-74,-70,-106,-131,-166,-163,-276,-244,-222,-271,-252,-282,-266,-266,-313,-313,
-313,-313,-473,-486] In this example, we shall see what happens when White
neglects the kingside development and pins the f6-knight with 7.Bg5.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 d6 {This move order is completely playable
as well.} ({Usually, I prefer starting with} 5... b5 {trying our chance to get
the fantastic Bluemenfeld type of position. After} 6. e4 d6 {we get back to
the game.}) 6. e4 b5 7. Bg5 {In my opinion, this continuation is dubious. In
order to create a pin, White neglects the development of the kingside. At the
same time, if White manages to comfortably develop his minor pieces, the pin
along the diagonal h4-d8 will be very annoying. Therefore, Black should opt
for a dynamic play. In this line of thought, going for a Benoni structure
with ...exd5 seems pretty logical.  First of all, however, Black correctly
played} O-O 8. Bd3 h6 {As usual, it's important to clarify the position of the
dark-squared bishop. The Benoni type of position arising after} 9. Bh4 exd5 10.
cxd5 c4 {is clearly favourable for Black. He has managed to make huge
progress on the queenside. In the usual Benoni positions, Black needs to work
a lot in order to achieve ...b7-b5 and ...c5-c4. Additionally, it's not clear
how White will complete the development.} 11. Bc2 Bc5 $1 {Another important
move. It will be now very difficult for White to castle. The next couple of
moves is quite logical.} 12. Nge2 b4 13. Na4 Be3 14. Bf2 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Nbd7
$17 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gd8a5,Gc8d7] Black has an obvious advantage. He can make use
of the problematic a4-knight by means of simple moves such as ...Ne5, ...Bd7,
and ...Qa5.} 16. Rf1 Ne5 17. Kg1 Bd7 18. Qd4 Qa5 19. b3 Bxa4 20. bxa4 Rac8 21.
f4 Ned7 22. e5 dxe5 23. fxe5 Nxe5 24. Qxe5 Rfe8 25. Qg3 Qb6+ 26. Kh1 Rxe2 27.
Bf5 Rd8 28. Rad1 Qd6 29. Qh4 c3 30. Qc4 Rd2 31. Rde1 Qxd5 0-1

