{In this example, we shall see how to play when White tries to put pressure on
d6 after dxe6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 d6 ({My
preference would be} 5... b5 6. e4 d6 7. dxe6 Bxe6 {transposing to the game
position.}) 6. e4 b5 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. Bf4 {This is the entire point of White's
strategy. Black doesn't have a good way of defending the d6-pawn. On the other
hand, his superior development is enough to compensate for the missing pawn.}
O-O {This is the most challenging option.} 9. Qxd6 ({The alternative} 9. Bxd6
Re8 10. cxb5 {is well met by} Qb6 {[%cal Ge8d8] In my opinion, this is the
simplest.} ({Another possibility is} 10... Nd5 11. Be5 {The only move to stay
in the game.} ({One of the correspondence games featuring this position
continued} 11. exd5 Bf5+ 12. Kf2 Qxd6 $17 {Adelseck,H (2396)-Schmidt,T (2400)
GER M06-C email 2017 0-1 with a huge advantage for Black. White cannot cover
the vulnerable dark squares. Additionally, he has unsolvable development
problems.}) {The next couple of moves are pretty logical -} 11... Nd7 12. exd5
Bf5 13. f4 Nxe5 14. fxe5 Rxe5+ 15. Be2 Qh4+ 16. Kf1 Rae8 $44 {Black has
tremendous compensation for the piece. In practice, it's very easy for White
to make a mistake in this position.}) 11. Bf4 c4 $36 {Black has tremendous
compensation for the material. It's not clear how White will complete the
development.}) 9... Qa5 10. Nge2 Bxc4 11. a3 Na6 {Black is planning to follow
with ...Rfd8. White's position looks very dangerous since his king is stacked in
the centre. The computer shows how he can make a draw with only moves -} 12.
Bg5 $1 {This is the saving option. Besides attacking the knight, White makes
the g3-square available for the queen. The following sequence is pretty forced}
Bxe2 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qxf6 Bxf1 15. Qg5+ Kh8 16. Qf6+ Kg8 17. Qg5+ Kh8 {
with a perpetual.} 1/2-1/2

