{From this game, we start dealing with the main line with 7.Nge2.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 d6 7. Nge2 {This is the most popular
continuation on the highest level. As we have already seen, White cannot
afford to delay the kingside development for a very long time. He is now planning
to develop his pieces with simple moves such as Nf4, Be2 and 0-0. After
stabilizing the position, White will rely on the long-term value of his space
advantage. Note that in all these lines, White is ready to temporarily
sacrifice the c4-pawn.} bxc4 8. Nf4 {by putting pressure on e6, White wants to
provoke his opponent to clarify the position in the centre. Also, he is ready
to take with a piece on d5 in case of ...exd5.} e5 {This move has been
established as the main line.} ({In my opinion, however, even more interesting
is the new trend} 8... g5 $5 {Even if you like the positions after 8...
g5, I strongly advise you to study 8...e5 as well. In this way, besides having
a solid backup option, you will improve your general Nimzo-Indian
understanding.} 9. Nfe2 exd5 10. exd5 Qe7 {Black's main strategy is to make it
difficult for White to develop the kingside. The threat of ...Nb8-d7-e5-d3 can
be particularly annoying for White.} 11. Bxg5 {This is the only challenging
continuation.} ({The attempt to untangle with} 11. Kf2 $6 Nbd7 12. Ng3 {
was seen in the game 1-0 (34) Mamedyarov, S (2765)-Ding, L (2799) Chess.com INT
2021. Now, Black could have played} Ne5 13. Be2 Bxc3 14. bxc3 h5 $1 {A very
strong concept. Black is planning to push the pawn all the way to h3. White
cannot complete the development of the kingside in a comfortable way. A
possible follow-up would be} 15. Re1 h4 16. Nf1 h3 17. g3 O-O 18. Kg1 Nh7 $17 {
White does not have enough compensation for the pawn. The c4-pawn is actually
quite important since it controls the d3-square. For example, one of Black's
ideas is ...Re8 followed by ...Nd3.}) 11... Bxc3+ {An important move. Black
makes use of the fact that White is forced to recapture with a pawn.} 12. bxc3
Nbd7 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gd7e5,Ge5d3] The position is highly double-edged. In my
opinion, however, playing with Black is a bit easier. His next two moves are
clear - ...Rg8 and ...Ne3, threatening ...Nd3. If White manages to untangle, however, Black's weaknesses, as well as vulnerable king, will start telling.} 13.
Qd2 {[%cal Ge1f2] By overprotecting the bishop White is planning to follow
with Kf2. The immediate 13.Kf2 will be met by 13...Ng4} Rg8 {Bringing the rook
into play and once again putting pressure on the bishop.} 14. h4 Ne5 15. Kf2 {
White is ready to proceed with Ng3 followed by Re1. In such a case, Black's
position will fall apart. Therefore, we need to play energetically here.} h6 $1
{As we are going to see, opening the g-file is an important part of Black's
strategy.} 16. Bxh6 Nd3+ {In OTB game, this move might create a lot of
practical problems for the opponent. Black is planning to continue with the
manoeuvre...Rb8-b2.} ({A decent alternative is} 16... Nh5 {immediately making
use of the g3-square.} 17. Rh2 {[%cal Ge2f4,Ga1e1] Sidestepping ...Ng3 and
preparing Nf4 followed by Re1.} ({The direct} 17. Bg5 {is well met by} f6 {
[%cal Ge5d3,Ga8b8]} 18. Nf4 Ng3 {Deflecting the white king to g3, wins Black a
valuable time.} 19. Kxg3 fxg5 20. hxg5 Qxg5+ 21. Kf2 Rb8 $17 {Black has
tremendous compensation for the pawn. With his vulnerable king, White cannot
survive for too long.}) ({The immediate} 17. Nf4 $2 {loses to} Ng3 18. Rh2 Ne4+
$1 19. fxe4 Ng4+ 20. Kg1 Nxh2 21. Bg5 f6 22. Kxh2 fxg5 $19 {when White does
not have compensation for the material.}) 17... Nd3+ {This position was
reached in the game ½-½ (17) Yeo, G (2482)-Beecham, C (2478) ICCF email 2020.
The attempt to play for a win with} 18. Kg1 Ne5 19. Kh1 $6 {might backfire.} ({
Instead, White should play} 19. Kf2 {with a draw.}) {The problem is that after}
19... Rb8 20. Nf4 $4 {loses to} Ng3+ 21. Kg1 Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 Ne4+ $19 {when the
queen is dropping.}) 17. Kg1 Rb8 {Black is planning to follow with ...Rb2 on
the next move. It's clear that his play is easier in practical terms. The
computer, however, claims equality and provides the following fantastic line
that I will not comment -} 18. Nd4 cxd4 19. Bxd3 dxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxd5 21. Qxc4
Ne3 22. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 23. Kf1 Rxg2 24. Kxg2 Rb2+ 25. Bc2 Qd2+ 26. Kg3 Rxc2 $11 {
Believe it or not, this position is a draw! I demonstrate this sequence for the
sake of enjoyment. Of course, you don't need to memorize this stuff.}) 9. Nfe2
{After securing the central stability, White can consider playing on the
kingside. He has two main strategies for developing the kingside initiative: 1)
expand with g2-g4 followed by Ng3 2) prepare the advance f3-f4 by means of Ng3
followed by Be2, and 0-0 In this game, MVL opted for the first plan.} Nbd7 10.
g4 h5 $1 {Black immediately seizes the opportunity to undermine White's space
advantage on the kingside.} 11. Ng3 {This is a very natural move. Besides
activating the knight, White wants to regain the pawn with Bxc4.} ({Another
thematic option is} 11. g5 {In similar structures, I prefer} Nh7 12. h4 g6 13.
Ng3 Nb6 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black will try to keep the c4-pawn as long as possible.
His counterplay is based on the advance ...f7-f6. A logical follow-up would be}
14. Be2 f6 15. gxf6 Qxf6 16. Qc2 Rb8 17. Bd2 Bd7 $132 {Black has plenty of
counterplay in this position. After castling, he can bring the king to the
safe h8-square. Later on, he can consider doubling the rooks on the b-file.
White's play is mainly based on the advance f3-f4. The problem, however, is
that 0-0-0 is always well met by ...Bxc3 followed by ...Ba4. In a practical
game, it will not be easy for White to prove his compensation for the pawn.})
11... g6 $6 {I don't like this move which gives White a lot of freedom.} ({
I would have preferred the thematic} 11... Nb6 12. g5 ({Black has many ways to
deal with the pin occurring after} 12. Bg5 $2 {The most elegant solution is}
hxg4 13. fxg4 Bxg4 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxg4 Na4 $17 {with a terrific
compensation for the piece. Black's attack is almost winning.}) 12... Nh7 13.
h4 ({The greedy} 13. Nxh5 $2 {would backfire after the following forced
sequence} Nxg5 14. Nxg7+ Kf8 15. Rg1 Nh3 16. Bxh3 Rxh3 17. Bg5 f6 18. Be3 Rxh2
$17 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd8h8] White is on the verge of losing. Black is ready to
proceed with ...Ke7 followed by ...Qh8.}) 13... g6 {transposing to 11.g5.}) 12.
Bxc4 $6 {This slow move gives Black enough time to create counterplay.} ({
White should have played} 12. h4 $1 {when the kingside tension is highly
unpleasant for Black. Provoking g4-g5 with the standard} Nb6 $2 {does not work
here in view of} 13. Bg5 $18 {creating a decisive pin. Black is paralyzed.})
12... Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qa5 $132 {Finally, Black got decent counterplay and
eventually managed to win the game.} 14. Qd3 Nb6 15. Bb5+ Bd7 16. Bxd7+ Nbxd7
17. g5 h4 18. Ne2 Nh5 19. O-O Rb8 20. f4 Qa4 21. f5 gxf5 22. Rxf5 c4 23. Qe3
Qd1+ 24. Rf1 Qd3 25. Qf2 Qxe4 26. Qxf7+ Kd8 27. Qf3 Qxf3 28. Rxf3 Rb5 29. Be3
Rxd5 30. Rb1 Ra5 31. Rb7 Ke7 32. Rxa7 Rxa7 33. Bxa7 Ra8 34. Bf2 Rxa2 35. Kf1
Nf8 36. Bxh4 Ng6 37. Bf2 Ke6 38. Bb6 Ra1+ 39. Kf2 Nhf4 40. Nxf4+ exf4 41. Rh3
Kf5 42. Rh7 Ne5 43. h4 Kg4 44. g6 Nxg6 45. Rg7 Kf5 46. h5 Ne5 47. h6 Rh1 48. h7
Kf6 49. Ra7 Kg6 50. Kg2 Rxh7 51. Rxh7 Kxh7 52. Bc7 Kg6 53. Bxd6 Kf5 54. Bc5 Ke4
55. Bd4 Ng4 56. Kf1 Kd3 0-1

