{[%evp 0,78,19,31,14,-14,-11,-3,4,-47,12,7,-11,9,72,-10,6,-53,-25,-32,-27,-27,
-21,-37,39,-30,-22,-42,-9,28,32,6,64,49,68,46,45,28,15,-48,21,-81,-77,-49,-49,
-49,-62,-74,-64,-55,-104,-117,-57,-65,-76,-67,-132,-144,-152,-136,-166,-160,
-177,-148,-143,-117,-139,-135,-135,-132,-156,-161,-163,-137,-151,-151,-247,
-252,-244,-231,-277] From this example, we shall start examining the White's
attempts to prepare the kingside break f2-f4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
f3 c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 d6 7. Nge2 bxc4 8. Nf4 e5 9. Nfe2 Nbd7 10. Ng3 {This is
the most natural continuation. Before going for active actions, White first
mobilizes the kingside. Obviously, if allowed, he will play Bxc4 on the next
move. Therefore, Black should play} Nb6 11. Be2 {White's strategy is very
simple. He is ready to proceed with 0-0 followed by f3-f4. For the time being,
White is not interested in the c4-pawn. He relies on the fact that Black's
queenside pieces will remain isolated from the battle on the kingside. Black,
however, has a powerful strategic idea at his disposal -} Ng8 $1 {[%csl Ge7]
[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Gg6f4] Remember this idea. The knight is heading to the key
f4-square via the route g8-e7-g6. Additionally, in many lines, Black can go
for the advance ...f7-f5.} 12. h4 $5 {This provocative approach is actually
very challenging. Besides gaining space on the kingside, White prevents the
manoeuvre...Ne7-g6. On the downside, the advance h2-h4 weakens the kingside.
Now, castling short is a bit risky for White.} {In my opinion, Black's most
precise reaction is} f5 $1 {which is one of the ideas behind ...Ng8.} {White's
most principled continuation is} 13. f4 {creating enormous tension in the
centre.} ({Black's idea is to answer} 13. exf5 {with} Ne7 {when White cannot
keep the f5-pawn for too long.} {White does not have anything better at his
disposal.} 14. O-O ({Inferior is} 14. Bg5 $6 {when after} h6 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 $17
{Black has a huge advantage. He is ready to castle on the next move. Sooner or
later the f5-pawn will drop. At the same time, there is no safe place for the
white king.}) 14... O-O {The f5-pawn is doomed. The most logical follow-up
would be} 15. f6 Rxf6 16. Nce4 {Even though 16...Rf8 is perfectly acceptable,
I like the exchange sacrifice a la Petrosian -} Rf4 $5 {Obviously, White
cannot take the rook because after ...exf4 followed by ...Nf5, Black is pretty
much winning. A logical continuation is} 17. Qc2 Ba5 18. Bxf4 ({Another
possible line is} 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Rb8 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Ne2 Ng6 22. h5
Ne5 {when Black has a very strong initiative for the exchange. He is ready to
follow with either ...Ba6 or ...Nd3.}) 18... exf4 19. Nh5 Nf5 $44 {The weak
dark squares give Black decent compensation for the exchange.}) 13... Nf6 14.
O-O O-O {White should already clarify the position in the centre. Otherwise,
Black can proceed with ...Bxc3 followed by ...exf4, and ...fxe4.} 15. fxe5 dxe5
16. exf5 Bb7 $132 {Even though the position remains complicated, I prefer
Black because of the vulnerable white king.} *

