{In this example, we shall see how Black should react when White prepares
f2-f4 without weakening the kingside by means of h2-h4.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 d6 7. Nge2 bxc4 8. Nf4 e5 9. Nfe2 Nbd7 10. Ng3
Nb6 11. Be2 Ng8 12. O-O Ne7 {Black has achieved his optimal regroupment.
Depending on the concrete circumstances, after castling, he will follow with
either ...f7-f5 or ...Ng6. White's most ambitious continuation is} 13. f4 {
trying to overtake the initiative before Black castles.} ({Regaining the
c4-pawn is rather time-consumming. Meanwhile, Black will manage to organize
his kingside counterplay based on ...f7-f5. The following examples illustrate
how the game might develop.} 13. Qc2 O-O 14. a4 {Besides gaining space on the
queenside, White wants to provoke the weakening ...a7-a5 advance.} ({In case
of the straightforward} 14. Nd1 $6 {Black can immediately go for the thematic}
f5 {[%cal Gf5f4] when the threat of ...f5-f4 is very annoying. This position
occurred in the online blitz game Richter, M - Kollars, D, 2021. In this game,
White played} 15. exf5 $2 {which is actually losing on the spot.} ({Relatively
the best would have been} 15. Bg5 {Nevertheless, after} f4 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17.
exf5 h6 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 $15 {Black has the upper hand. After ...Qd7, the f5-pawn
will be lost and White should still prove his compensation.}) ({After} 15. Bxc4
$2 Nxc4 16. Qxc4 f4 17. Ne2 g5 {[%cal Ge7g6] Black has a fantastic version of
the King's Indian Defence. He is ready to proceed with the standard moves ...
Ng6 followed by ...h7-h5 and ...g5-g4 when the attack plays itself. Black is
strategically winning.}) {Now, instead of the game continuation 15...Nxf5,
more precise would have been} 15... Bxf5 16. Nxf5 Nxf5 {when the black knight
will land on d4 with tremendous effect. For instance, after} 17. Bxc4 Nd4 18.
Qd3 Qh4 19. g3 Qh5 $19 {White is losing since the kingside is falling apart.})
{This is the better way of stopping a4-a5.} 14... Ba5 15. Nb5 Ng6 {I like this
multi-purpose move. Besides, the standard ...Nf4, Black can also consider ...
Nh4 followed by ...f7-f5.} ({In case of} 15... f5 $6 16. f4 {White is better
prepared for the central tension.}) {White wants to regain the pawn without
granting Black the bishop pair.} 16. Na3 ({Black is doing fine after} 16. Bxc4
Nxc4 17. Qxc4 Nf4 $132 {[%cal Ga7a6,Ga8b8] Black's next moves might be ...
a7-a6 and ...Rb8. In this case, it becomes obvious that the move a2-a4
weakened the queenside.}) 16... Nh4 {Black prepares the advance ...f7-f5.} ({
Of course,} 16... Nf4 {is playable as well.}) 17. Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 f5 19.
exf5 ({In this structure, before playing ...f7-f5, we should always calculate} 
19. f4 $5 {In this case, Black was going to execute the thematic} exf4 20. Bxf4
g5 21. Bd2 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 f4 {This is the critical position. If White allows
the manoeuvre...Ng6-e5, he will be positionally lost. Therefore, the energetic}
23. e5 {is the only way to stay in the game. Now, Black's practical choice
would be} Bf5 ({After} 23... fxg3 24. hxg3 Ng6 25. e6 $44 {White's e6-pawn
gives his sufficient compensation for the piece.}) 24. Nxf5 Nxf5 $132 {Black
has decent counterplay since the knight is superior to the bishop in this
position. White should always reckon with the threat of ... Ne3.}) 19... Nxf5
$132 {This position occurred in the game ½-½ (31) Vugt, W (2275)-Muniz
Pardino,A (2381) ICCF email 2018. The possibility to play on the semi-open b
and f-files gives Black enough counterplay.}) ({Artificial looks} 13. Nh5 O-O
14. f4 {It's not clear how the possibility of recapturing on f4 with the
knight actually helps White.} exf4 15. Nxf4 ({A mistake is} 15. a4 $2 {because
now Black is not forced to reckon with the advance a4-a5. Instead, he can
immediately start fighting for the e5-square by playing} Ng6 {The only game
where this position occurred followed with} 16. a5 Nd7 17. Bxc4 Nde5 18. Be2
Bxa5 $19 {Black was already winning in the game. 0-1 (65) O'Gorman, T (2377)
-Peralta,F (2570) Barcelona 2021 EXT 2022. White does not have any
compensation for the sacrificed material.}) {Once again, Black starts fighting
for the important e5-square.} 15... Ng6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bf4 Qe7 $17 {[%cal
Gb6d7,Gd7e5] Black is obviously better. The key positional idea is ...
Nb6-d7-e5. In this case, White wouldn't have any counterplay.}) ({Completely
pointless is} 13. Re1 $6 {The rook has nothing to do on e1 in this structure.
Obviously, White wants to execute the manoeuvre Nf1-e3. Besides being
time-consuming, it's not clear how actually this idea helps White. Black can
immediately organize his kingside activity with} O-O 14. Nf1 f5 15. Ne3 {
This position was reached in the game Hua, L - Wojtaszek, R, 2022. Now, the
simplest would have been} f4 16. Nxc4 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 g5 $17 {when Black is
strategically winning since he has a fantastic version of the King's Indian.})
13... exf4 14. Bxf4 Ng6 {It's important to start with this move before
castling. Obviously, the advance e4-e5 shouldn't be allowed.} 15. Qc1 {[%cal
Gc3b5] This continuation was tested in several correspondence games. White is
planning to put pressure on d6 by means of Nb5.} ({Harmless is} 15. Be3 O-O 16.
Qd2 {which was played in the game Pantzar, M - Wagner, D, 2021. At this point,
the most natural way of mobilizing the queenside would be} Qe7 17. Rf2 Bd7 18.
Raf1 Rae8 $17 {when White does not have any compensation for the pawn.
Additionally, the e5-square as well as the vulnerable e4-pawn are big issues
for White.}) ({Probably, you are asking yourself what to do when in this
structure White answers ...Qe7 with Nf5. The following example, is very
instructive.} 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Rf2 Qe7 17. Raf1 Bd7 18. Nf5 $2 {This is a
typical mistake. Black's best reaction is going for the following exchange
operation -} Bxf5 19. exf5 Nxf4 20. Rxf4 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rae8 22. Bxc4 Qe3+ 23.
Qxe3 Rxe3 $19 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (124) Kokoszczynski, J 
(2297)-Markowski,T (2531) Elblag 2022. Black was already winning since White
cannot cover his multiple weaknesses.}) {We should start with this move in
order to prevent Nb5.} 15... Bxc3 $1 16. Qxc3 ({After} 16. bxc3 $6 O-O 17. Qe3
Nxf4 18. Qxf4 f6 $15 {White does not have enough compensation for the pawn.})
16... Nxf4 17. Rxf4 O-O {Even though the position is balanced, White should
play very dynamically in order to compensate for Black's static advantage. If
White plays it slowly, Black can either execute the manoeuvre...Nd7-e5 or
prepare the exchange of the queens via the e5-square.} 18. Nh5 f6 {This move
forces White to show even more precision.} ({Another simple solution would be} 
18... Qg5 19. h4 Qe5 20. Qxe5 {when the draw was agreed in the game ½-½ (20)
Yeo, G (2477)-Balshaw, A (2456) ICCF email 2021}) 19. Qg3 Qe7 20. Raf1 Kh8 {
Black managed to neutralize the immediate threats of his opponent. In OTB
games, White can easily lose momentum in such positions. The computer
, however, claims that the position is just a draw and comes up with the
following sequence -} 21. e5 dxe5 22. d6 Qb7 23. Rh4 Qf7 24. Bf3 Bb7 25. Bxb7
Qxb7 26. Qg6 Qf7 27. Qxh7+ Kxh7 28. Nxf6+ Kg6 29. Rg4+ Kh6 30. Rh4+ $11 {
with perpetual.} *

