{We will finish our survey on 4.f3 by examining the continuation 7.Bd2
which became very popular recently.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5.
d5 b5 6. e4 d6 7. Bd2 {This continuation has solid positional grounds. White
is immediately addressing the annoying pin on the diagonal a5-e1. By creating
the threat of Nxb5, White wants to provoke his opponent to release the
queenside tension.  Even though the common 7...a6 is completely playable, I
prefer} Bxc3 8. Bxc3 b4 {Black grants the bishop pair to his opponent but wins
space on the queenside. Also, White wastes valuable time playing with his
bishop. After} 9. Bd2 {Black's most logical idea is to play a Benoni type of
position after} exd5 10. cxd5 {the arising Benoni structure is balanced.
Unlike the usual Benoni positions, Black does not have his powerful
dark-squared bishop. As always, in the long term, White will rely on his space
advantage. On the other hand, in this specific position, Black has several
important advantages 1) space advantage on the queenside which is very
important in Benoni structures 2) better development 3) since one pair of
minor pieces has been exchanged, White's space advantage is less significant
In the future, Black's counterplay will be based on the advance ...f7-f5.} ({
The symmetrical position arising after} 10. exd5 {is favourable for
Black. Usually, in symmetrical structures, development and piece activity are
the most important factor. Black is better developed and can easily activate
his minor pieces. Let's take a look at an example -} O-O 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Ne2
Ne5 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bh4 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (33) Abrashkin,
B (2407)-Mirzoev,E (2467) Chess.com INT 2020. Now, Black's most promising plan
would have been} Qe7 15. O-O a5 16. Qc2 g5 {Gaining space on the wings is a
very common strategy in symmetrical positions. After} 17. Bg3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Nh5
19. Bf2 f5 $15 {Black is alredy slightly better. If allowed Black can proceed
with ...Qf6 followed by ...f5-f4.}) 10... O-O 11. Be3 {This is a prophylactic
move. White wants to answer ...Nh5 with g2-g4.} ({The attempt to quickly
complete the development with} 11. Bc4 $6 {followed by Nge2 is dubious since
the c4-bishop is quite vulnerable.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5] Now, White should spend
a tempo on preventing the annoying ...Ne5, The c4-bishop, however, can be
attacked with ...Nb6 as well.} 12. Bf4 Nb6 13. Be2 {This position occurred in
the online blitz game 0-1 (30) Aditya, M (2438)-Eljanov, P (2672) Chess.com INT
2021. Now, the simplest would have been} Nh5 14. Be3 f5 $19 {with a decisive
advantage for Black. It's not clear how White will manage to develop his
kingside.}) ({With the kingside being undeveloped, the inclusion of} 11. Bg5 h6
12. Bh4 {is a pure waste of time. This position was reached in the game 0-1 (27)
Raupp,T (2283)-Tutisani,N (2435) Bregenz 2022. Now, after} Nbd7 $15 {[%cal
Gd7e5,Ge5g6] Black is ready to get rid of the pin by means of the thematic
manoeuvre...Ne5-g6. It's not clear what exactly White has achieved.}) ({Playing
} 11. Ne2 $6 {without Be3 is well met by} Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] when Black
immediately prepares the thematic ...f7-f5.} 12. Nf4 Nxf4 {This is how Black
should play for a win in this position. When our opponent has a space
advantage, we are happy to exchange minor pieces.} ({Of course, Black can
immediately force a draw by means of} 12... Qh4+ 13. g3 Nxg3 14. Ng2 Qh5 15.
Nf4 Qh4 $11 {with a repetition.}) 13. Bxf4 f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 $132 {[%cal Gd8f6,
Gb8d7,Gd7e5] Black has plenty of counterplay in this position. His superior
development and piece activity provide good compensation for White's bishop
pair. Black will proceed with ...Qf6 followed by ...Nd7-e5.}) 11... Nfd7 {
[%cal Gf7f5] Without wasting time, Black starts preparing the advance ...f7-f5.
} ({The point of 11.Be3 is that} 11... Nh5 $2 {will be answered with} 12. g4
$16 {The point is that after} Qh4+ $2 13. Bf2 $18 {Black is losing a piece.})
12. Ne2 {This is the most flexible continuation.} ({The move} 12. Nh3 {
occurred in the game 0-1 (30) Agibileg, U (2413)-Ter Sahakyan, S (2643) Paracin
2021. Now, the simplest would have been} Ne5 13. Nf2 f5 $132 {From a practical
point of view, Black's position is easier. White should now reckon with the
positional threat of ...f5-f4.}) 12... Nb6 {In my opinion this is the most
flexible continuation. The immediate f7-f5 will provide White with the extra
possibility of Nf4.} 13. Ng3 ({In case of} 13. Nf4 {, Black can provoke g2-g3
with} Qh4+ 14. g3 Qf6 15. Qd2 N8d7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5] Black has enough
counterplay in this complex position. After ...Ne5 White should always reckon
with the vulnerable f3-pawn. Additionally, a possible knight jump to c4 is
always in the air.}) 13... f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Nxf5 {The most precise move.
White wants to develop his light-squared bishop with a tempo.} ({Clearly worse
is} 15. Bd3 $6 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 N8d7 17. O-O {This position occurred in the game
½-½ (31) Yeganegi,B (2060)-Makaraci,T (2275) Nakhchivan 2022. Now, Black
could have played} Ne5 18. Qd1 Nec4 19. Bc1 Qf6 20. Ne4 Qe5 $17 {with a huge
advantage. The d5-pawn will be lost.}) 15... Rxf5 16. Bd3 Re5 17. Be4 {White
finally managed to stabilize the position and is ready to castle. The
following couple of moves is forced and logical.} N8d7 18. O-O Nf6 19. Bf4 Re8
20. Bg5 Re5 21. Bf4 Re8 $11 {with a repetition. This position occurred in the
game 0-1 (58) Kalogridis, A (2272)-Arjun, K (2499) Belgrade 2022. In the game,
Black avoided repetition and even managed to win. Nevertheless, it's fair to
say that such a decision is a bit risky.} *

