{In this example, I will provide you with an easy and practical weapon against
the system with 4.Bd2.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 {The idea of this
system is to prevent Black from spoiling White's pawn structure by means of ...
Bxc3. Very often, White is trying to obtain the bishop pair with a2-a3. On the
downside, the bishop is very passive on d2. Also, now White does not have
sufficient control of the important d4-square. Therefore, Black's most logical
choice is} c5 {which is also consistent with our reaction to all other setups
that White might choose against the Nimzo-Indian Defence.  In this position,
White's most common reaction is} 5. e3 {Actually, White is not fighting for an
opening advantage. He just wants to develop his pieces with simple moves such
as Nf3 and Bd3.} ({After} 5. dxc5 O-O 6. Nf3 Bxc5 {we get a position which is
quite similar to the line 4.Qc2 c5. Black can go for a Hedgehog setup with ...
b7-b6 followed by ...Bb7, and ...Be7.}) ({The most ambitious way of justifying
4.Bd2 is} 5. a3 Bxc3 6. Bxc3 {It turns out, however, that after} Ne4 7. Qc2 {
The most natural continuation. Since the e4-knight is pretty annoying, White
wants to provoke ...Nxc3 as soon as possible.} ({In case of} 7. Rc1 {Black can
play the thematic} Qh4 {Besides the simple checkmate threat, Black is putting
annoying pressure on d4. His idea is to answer} 8. g3 {with} Nxc3 {White's
most practical decision is going for an endgame with} 9. gxh4 ({Another
possibility is} 9. bxc3 Qe7 10. Bg2 {This position was reached in the game 0-1
(41) Rasulov,V (2469)-Yilmaz,M (2626) Chess.com INT 2021. Now, Black could
have played in the style of the Huebner Variation -} O-O 11. Nf3 d6 12. O-O Nc6
$132 {[%cal Ge6e5] followed by ...e6-e5. As often happens in Nimzo-Indian
Defence, White should play dynamically in order to compensate for his inferior
structure.}) 9... Nxd1 10. Rxd1 cxd4 11. Nf3 Nc6 {This position was reached in
the game ½-½ (11) Bocharov, D (2533)-Lysyj, I (2605) Barnaul 2021. After} 12.
Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 b6 14. Bg2 Rb8 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black is ready to follow with .
..Bb7 on the next move. The arising endgame with heavy pieces is completely
equal.}) 7... Nxc3 8. Qxc3 cxd4 9. Qxd4 {The structure is pretty similar to
the line with 4.Qc2 c5. Black has many ways to get a comfortable position. Let's
follow one example taken from the practice of Fabiano Caruana.} O-O ({The
endgame arising after} 9... Qf6 10. Qxf6 gxf6 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gb7b6,Gb8c6] is
also quite playable. The good central control as well as the vulnerable
c4-pawn provide Black with an excellent counterplay.}) 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Qd6 ({
In case of} 11. Qc3 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8c8] Black is planning to proceed
with ...Bb7 and ...Rc8. Once again, the position is pretty similar to the line
with 4.Qc2.}) 11... b6 12. e3 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (40)
Rasulov,V (2445)-Caruana,F (2781) Chess.com INT 2022. Among the multiple
possible solutions, I would prefer} Qf6 13. O-O-O Ba6 $15 {when Black is
already slightly better. He can follow with ...Rac8 and ...Na5. White must
think about how to secure the safety of his own king.}) ({I will not examine in
detail harmless lines such as} 5. Nf3 {The simplest solution is} cxd4 6. Nxd4
O-O {when Black is ready to follow with ...Nc6 or ...d7-d5 against pretty much
everything.} {I would just like to mention the move} 7. a3 {which was tried by
MVL.} ({Obviously, after} 7. e3 Nc6 {[%cal Gd7d5] followed by ...d7-d5, Black
has nothing to worry about.}) ({Playing in the Catalan style with} 7. g3 {
does not work so well. Black's simplest solution seems to be} d5 8. cxd5 Bxc3
9. Bxc3 Nxd5 10. Bg2 Nxc3 11. bxc3 e5 $11 {Even though the position is
dynamically balanced, White should play very actively in order to prove his
compensation for the inferior pawn structure.}) 7... Bc5 {I like this move.
Caruana is planning to continue with ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7.} 8. e3 b6 9. Be2 Bb7
10. O-O Nc6 $132 {This position occurred in the game 0-1 (47) Vachier Lagrave,
M (2766)-Caruana,F (2791) Chess.com INT 2021. Once again, Black managed to
obtain a nice version of the line 4.Qc2 c5.}) ({The Benoni structure arising
after} 5. d5 exd5 6. cxd5 d6 $132 {is obviously favourable for Black since he
is ahead in development. After ...0-0 followed by ...Re8, it will be difficult
for White to build his pawn centre.}) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 O-O 7. Nf3 d5 {Due to
the passive d2-bishop, Black is interested in getting an IQP type of position.
With a bishop on d2, White will not be able to build his usual kingside
activity.} 8. a3 {This is the only way to somehow justify the move Bd2.} ({
The symmetrical structure arising after} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Ne4
$132 {is already slightly preferable for Black in view of his more active
pieces. Black eventually managed to win in the game 0-1 (50) Prieto Aranguren,
A (2206)-Nisipeanu, L (2670) Benasque 2013}) ({Another principled approach is} 
8. c5 {In this case, Black should immediately challenge White's space
advantage with} b6 $1 {We shouldn't allow White to fortify the c5-pawn by
means of a2-a3 followed by b2-b4.} 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4 {Typical move for
this pawn structure. Besides putting pressure on c5, Black also prevents the
advance b2-b4.} 11. Qc2 bxc5 12. dxc5 {This position was reached in the game
0-1 (46) Sandipan,C (2603)-Eljanov,P (2719) Doha 2014. Now, the most precise
continuation would have been} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] planning to fix the queenside
structure with ...a5-a4. The position arising after} 13. b4 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 axb4
15. axb4 d4 16. Nxd4 Rxa1+ 17. Qxa1 Qd5 $44 {provides Black with excellent
compensation for the pawn. Playing with the king stack in the centre is
practically very difficult.}) ({The IQP type of position arising after} 8. Bd3
dxc4 9. Bxc4 b6 $132 {is always favourable for Black in view of the misplaced
d2-bishop.}) {In my opinion, this is the simplest solution.} 8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3
dxc4 10. Bxc4 b6 11. O-O Ba6 $15 {After the exchange of the light-squared
bishops, Black will be slightly better.} *

