{[%evp 0,34,27,27,25,15,15,15,20,1,1,-33,-19,-18,-29,-29,-21,-28,-31,-28,-2,
-24,-5,-20,-13,-30,1,-12,-3,1,11,-2,42,10,26,-9,-11] Finally, we shall take a
look at 4.Qb3. Against such a move, Black can play in many ways and you don't
need to know any theory. I will show the setup that I am playing but feel free
to improvise and play according to your taste. It is difficult to go wrong!} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qb3 c5 {Once again, this is the most logical
continuation. Additionally, this move is consistent with all the lines that we
have been studying so far.} 5. dxc5 {This is the main continuation. The
character of the arising positions is pretty much similar to the line with 4.
Qc2 c5. We should point out, however, that the queen on b3 is simply misplaced.
} ({After} 5. e3 {Black`s most precise reaction is} Nc6 6. Nf3 d5 {Since White
has spent a tempo on 4.Qb3, Black logically tries to open up the centre. Also,
we are more than ready to play IQP type of position.} 7. cxd5 ({Now} 7. a3 {
can be met by} Na5 {This move leads to simplifications and equality.} 8. Qc2
Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxc4 11. Bxc4 dxc4 12. Qxc4 O-O 13. O-O b6 {
This position was reached in the game 1/2 Phillips, R-Bluvshtein, M (2303)/
Montreal 2001/EXT 2002 (23). After} 14. b4 Bb7 15. Bb2 $11 {the position is
completely equal.}) 7... exd5 8. dxc5 {Black is not afraid of playing with an
isolated pawn because of his active minor pieces. At the same time, the
misplaced b3-queen will create problems for White.} ({The structure arising
after} 8. a3 $6 c4 9. Qc2 Ba5 {if usually quite favourable for Black. In the
future, he can consider expanding on the queenside by means of ...b7-b5-b4.
White's only counterplay is based on the advance e3-e4. Therefore, before
expanding on the queenside, Black should take the e4-square under control. In
such structures, the dark-squared bishop is a huge problem for White. Let's
take a look at one instructive example -} 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. b3 $2 {
It's understandable that White wants to get rid of the annoying c4-pawn. The
problem is that Black has enough resources to sustain his space advantage.} ({
The lesser evil would have been} 12. Bd2 $15) 12... Bxc3 {An important move.
Black should eliminate the c3-knight in order to proceed with ...b7-b5.} 13.
Qxc3 Ne4 14. Qe1 b5 15. a4 Na5 $17 {Black obtained an almost decisive
positional advantage in the game 0-1 Canal, E-Castillo Larenas, M/Dubrovnik 1950/
MCD (26)}) 8... O-O 9. Be2 Be6 10. Nd4 Bxc5 11. Nxe6 fxe6 $15 {[%cal Ga7a6,
Gd8d6,Gf8f7] This position occurred in the game 0-1 (17) Karpov, A (2760)
-Kramnik,V (2740)/Monte Carlo 1997/CBM 057 ext (68). Black's better
development and good central control are more than enough compensation for
White's bishop pair. As usual, the c1-bishop is problematic here. Black will
improve his position with simple moves such as ...a7-a6 followed by ...Qd6, ...
Rf7, and ...Raf8. Under favourable circumstances, he can consider opening the
position with ...d5-d4.  Note that} 12. Qxb7 $4 {will be met by} Nb4 $19 {
[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga8b8,Gf8f7] when the white queen is trapped.}) ({In case of} 
5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 d5 {we transpose to the previous variation with 5.e3}) 5...
Nc6 {This is the most common continuation.} ({Obviously, Black can also play} 
5... Na6 {with ideas similar to the line 4.Qc2 c5.}) 6. Nf3 ({In the event of} 
6. Bd2 Bxc5 7. e3 O-O 8. Nf3 b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Rc8 {we get again the
structure typical for the line 4.Qc2 c5. In this case, however, the white
queen is really misplaced on b3.}) ({if White plays} 6. Bg5 {then Black solves
problems by} h6 7. Bxf6 {This is the safest choice.} ({After} 7. Bh4 $6 {
Black can overtake the initiative by means of} g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {White is forced
to accept an inferior pawn structure without any compensation for it.} 9. e3 Bxc3+
10. bxc3 {This position occurred in the game 1-0 (15) Agdestein, S (2585)
-Hjartarson,J (2570)/Reykjavik 1996/CBM 052 (41). At this point, the most
precise way to stabilize the advantage would have been} Nxc5 11. Qc2 d6 12. Nf3
e5 $17 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gc8f5] By means of a precise pawn play, Black managed to
restrict all white minor pieces. He is ready to proceed with ...Qf6 followed
by ...Bf5. It's not clear how White is going to create counterplay here.}) 7...
Qxf6 8. Nf3 {This position occurred in the game 1/2 (14) Akopian,V (2590)
-Tiviakov,S (2535)/Mamaia 1991/CBM 025 ext (55). Almost every move gives Black
decent play. I think that the most elegant continuation is the following
positional pawn sacrifice -} Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 10. bxc3 b6 11. cxb6 axb6 12.
e3 Na5 $15 {[%cal Ga5b7,Gb7c5,Ge8e7] Black is better. In the next couple of
moves, he will stabilize the advantage with ...Nb7-c5 followed by ...Ke7.})
6... Ne4 {Now, White needs to part with his dark-squared bishop in order to
keep the pawn structure intact.} 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2 Bxc5 9. e3 {This is the
most common move. White is not actually fighting for an advantage. He just
wants to complete the development.} ({Practice has also seen} 9. Nde4 Be7 10.
Rd1 {White is playing against the d7-pawn. His development, however, is not
enough to sustain such activity.} ({After} 10. O-O-O O-O 11. e3 {Black
should prepare the advance ...b7-b5 with} a6 {In one of the old games in this
line, White tries to make use of the b6-square by means of} 12. Na4 $2 {
which is a mistake.} ({In case of} 12. c5 {, Black will play} b5 {with the
following tactical justification -} 13. cxb6 $140 $6 Na5 14. Qc2 Qxb6 $40 {
[%cal Gd7d5,Gc8d7,Gf8c8,Ga8b8] Black's queenside attack is very dangerous.})
12... b5 $1 {Black should open the queenside at any cost. Therefore, the pawn
sacrifice is fully justified.} 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Bxb5 {This position was
reached in the game 1/2 Steiner,L-Adam,H/Vienna 1937/EXT 1999/(69). Now, the
natural} Rb8 $17 {[%cal Gd7d5] threatening ...d7-d5 would have provided Black
with a huge advantage.}) 10... O-O 11. e3 Qc7 12. Be2 f5 {The plan with the
advance of the f-pawn is typical for such positions.} 13. Ng3 f4 14. exf4 Qxf4
15. O-O Nd4 16. Qa4 {0-1 Hess,R (2335)-Bernhardt,R/Germany 1978/EXT 1999 (64)}
{and now was correct} a6 17. Bd3 Rb8 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) ({In case of} 9. g3 {
I would prefer} f5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd2] restricting the access of the white knights
to the e4-square.} 10. Bg2 b6 11. e3 Bb7 $132 {with comfortable position for
Black. He is even slightly better in view of the bishop pair.}) 9... O-O 10.
Be2 b6 {Even though the alternative 10...f5 is possible as well, I think that
the text move is more consistent with our setup against 4.Qc2.} 11. O-O ({After
} 11. Nde4 {the simplest reaction is} Be7 12. Rd1 a6 {Black will continue with
...Qc7 followed by ...f7-f5. We know that after} 13. Nd6 $140 Qc7 $132 {
the d6-knight is often vulnerable in such structures.}) {At this point, I
prefer starting with} 11... Be7 {when Black is going to rely on his bishop
pair. Note that the white knights don't have stable squares in this pawn
structure.} 12. Rad1 a6 {It's important to rule out any Nb5 ideas.} 13. Qc2 {
This position occurred in the game 1/2 Hejberg, C (2120)-Eriksson, A (2300)/
Copenhagen 1997/EXT 2000 (38). Now, Black could have employed the following
plan -} f5 14. Nf3 Bf6 15. Rd2 Qe7 16. Rfd1 Rb8 17. Rd6 g5 $132 {[%cal Gg5g4,
Gc6e5,Gc8b7] Black is already slightly better. After kicking the f3-knight
back with ...g5-g4, he can proceed with ...Bb7 followed by ...Ne5.} *

